{"title_page": "Annika Linde", "text_new": "{{short description|Swedish physician, virologist}}\n'''Gerda Annika Linde''' (born [[26 February]] [[1948]]) is a Swedish physician, virologist and retired civil servant. From 2005 to 2013 she served as [[State epidemiologist (Sweden)|State Epidemiologist]] at the Swedish Institute for Communicable Disease Control.\n\n== Biography ==\nLinde was born in [[Sk\u00f6vde]] and grew up there. She was inspired by the novel ''[[Exodus (Uris novel)|Exodus]]'' by [[Leon Uris]] to study medicine. She enrolled at Gothenburg University in 1968, studying medicine and sociology, obtaining a medical degree in 1974.<ref>{{cite web |last=\u00d6rn |first=Peter |title=Annika Linde varnar f\u00f6r fortsatt virushot |url=http://www.lakartidningen.se/Functions/OldArticleView.aspx?articleId=12163 |publisher=L\u00e4kartidningen |accessdate=12 April 2020}}</ref> After her internship at [[Danderyd Hospital]] she went on to work as an infectious disease specialist at the presently defunct Roslagstull Hospital in Stockholm. In 1979 she started working at the virological department at the Swedish National Bacteriological Laboratory, and completed her PhD in Clinical Virology in 1987. In 1993 she became head of the Swedish influenza centre of the WHO and started working for Department of Virology at the Swedish Institute for Communicable Disease Control, where she in 2002 became department head.<ref name=\"SMI\">{{cite web |title=Annika Linde |url=http://www.smittskyddsinstitutet.se/om-smi/smis-ledningsgrupp/annika-linde/  |publisher=Swedish Institute for Communicable Disease Control |accessdate=12 April 2020}}</ref> In 2005 she became head of the Department of Epidemiology and was in the same year appointed State Epidemiologist.<ref name=\"Dagens Medicin\">{{cite web |url=http://www.dagensmedicin.se/nyheter/annika-linde-utsedd-till-statsepidemiolog-/ |title=Annika Linde utsedd till statsepidemiolog |publisher=Dagens Medicin Sverige |accessdate=2014-06-15 |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20140615121033/http://www.dagensmedicin.se/nyheter/annika-linde-utsedd-till-statsepidemiolog-/ |archivedate=2014-06-15 }}</ref> She served in this role until her retirement in 2013, when she was succeeded by [[Anders Tegnell]].\n\nLinde's research is mainly focused on adapting basic research results to clinical applications. She has researched the reaction of the human body to different types of viruses and evaluation of diagnostic methods. She mainly focused on [[Human herpesviruses|herpes virus]]es to begin with, but eventually came to focus her work mostly on [[Orthomyxoviridae|influenza]] and respiratory viruses. She has published more than 200 peer-reviewed scientific papers.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sfvh.se/studiedagar-2010 |title=SFVH:s studiedagar 19-21 april 2010 p\u00e5 Hotell Skogsh\u00f6jd i S\u00f6dert\u00e4lje |publisher=Svensk F\u00f6rening f\u00f6r V\u00e5rdhygien |accessdate=2014-06-15}}</ref>\n\nLinde has served as [[adjunct professor]] at the [[Karolinska Institute]]. She hosted an episode of the popular radio show ''[[Sommar i P1]]'' for [[Sveriges Radio]] in 2010.\n\n== References ==\n<references/>\n\n{{authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Linde, Annika}}\n[[Category:Swedish epidemiologists]]\n[[Category:Swedish virologists]]\n[[Category:1948 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Sk\u00f6vde Municipality]]\n[[Category:Swedish civil servants]]\n[[Category:Karolinska Institute faculty]]\n[[Category:Sommar (radio program) hosts]]\n[[Category:Swedish women physicians]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Swedish physician, virologist}}\n'''Gerda Annika Linde''' (born [[26 February]] [[1948]]) is a Swedish physician, virologist and retired civil servant. From 2005 to 2013 she served as State Epidemiologist at the Swedish Institute for Communicable Disease Control.\n\n== Biography ==\nLinde was born in [[Sk\u00f6vde]] and grew up there. She was inspired by the novel ''[[Exodus (Uris novel)|Exodus]]'' by [[Leon Uris]] to study medicine. She enrolled at Gothenburg University in 1968, studying medicine and sociology, obtaining a medical degree in 1974.<ref>{{cite web |last=\u00d6rn |first=Peter |title=Annika Linde varnar f\u00f6r fortsatt virushot |url=http://www.lakartidningen.se/Functions/OldArticleView.aspx?articleId=12163 |publisher=L\u00e4kartidningen |accessdate=12 April 2020}}</ref> After her internship at [[Danderyd Hospital]] she went on to work as an infectious disease specialist at the presently defunct Roslagstull Hospital in Stockholm. In 1979 she started working at the virological department at the Swedish National Bacteriological Laboratory, and completed her PhD in Clinical Virology in 1987. In 1993 she became head of the Swedish influenza centre of the WHO and started working for Department of Virology at the Swedish Institute for Communicable Disease Control, where she in 2002 became department head.<ref name=\"SMI\">{{cite web |title=Annika Linde |url=http://www.smittskyddsinstitutet.se/om-smi/smis-ledningsgrupp/annika-linde/  |publisher=Swedish Institute for Communicable Disease Control |accessdate=12 April 2020}}</ref> In 2005 she became head of the Department of Epidemiology and was in the same year appointed State Epidemiologist.<ref name=\"Dagens Medicin\">{{cite web |url=http://www.dagensmedicin.se/nyheter/annika-linde-utsedd-till-statsepidemiolog-/ |title=Annika Linde utsedd till statsepidemiolog |publisher=Dagens Medicin Sverige |accessdate=2014-06-15 |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20140615121033/http://www.dagensmedicin.se/nyheter/annika-linde-utsedd-till-statsepidemiolog-/ |archivedate=2014-06-15 }}</ref> She served in this role until her retirement in 2013, when she was succeeded by [[Anders Tegnell]].\n\nLinde's research is mainly focused on adapting basic research results to clinical applications. She has researched the reaction of the human body to different types of viruses and evaluation of diagnostic methods. She mainly focused on [[Human herpesviruses|herpes virus]]es to begin with, but eventually came to focus her work mostly on [[Orthomyxoviridae|influenza]] and respiratory viruses. She has published more than 200 peer-reviewed scientific papers.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sfvh.se/studiedagar-2010 |title=SFVH:s studiedagar 19-21 april 2010 p\u00e5 Hotell Skogsh\u00f6jd i S\u00f6dert\u00e4lje |publisher=Svensk F\u00f6rening f\u00f6r V\u00e5rdhygien |accessdate=2014-06-15}}</ref>\n\nLinde has served as [[adjunct professor]] at the [[Karolinska Institute]]. She hosted an episode of the popular radio show ''[[Sommar i P1]]'' for [[Sveriges Radio]] in 2010.\n\n== References ==\n<references/>\n\n{{authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Linde, Annika}}\n[[Category:Swedish epidemiologists]]\n[[Category:Swedish virologists]]\n[[Category:1948 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Sk\u00f6vde Municipality]]\n[[Category:Swedish civil servants]]\n[[Category:Karolinska Institute faculty]]\n[[Category:Sommar (radio program) hosts]]\n[[Category:Swedish women physicians]]\n", "name_user": "Zanimum", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Annika_Linde"}
{"title_page": "Doris Lusk", "text_new": "{{EngvarB|date=April 2015}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2015}}\n{{Infobox artist\n| name           = Doris More Lusk\n| image          = Photo of Doris Lusk.jpg\n| imagesize      =\n| caption        = \n| birth_name     = \n| birth_date     = {{birth date|1916|5|5|df=y}}\n| birth_place    = [[Dunedin]], New Zealand\n| death_date     = {{death date and age|1990|4|14|1916|5|5|df=y}}\n| death_place   = [[Christchurch]], New Zealand\n|| education     = Dunedin School of Art\n| field         = [[Painting]]\n| training      =\n| movement      = \n| works         =\n| patrons       =\n| awards        = \n| spouse        = {{marriage|Dermot Holland|1942|}}\n}}\n\n'''Doris More Lusk''' (5 May 1916 \u2013 14 April 1990) was a New Zealand artist and art teacher, potter, university lecturer. In 1990 she was posthumously awarded the Governor General Art Award in recognition of her artistic career and contributions.<ref name ='DPAG'>{{cite web|title=Doris Lusk 1916-1990|url=http://dunedin.art.museum/exhibitions/now/1916-1990|website=Dunedin Public Art Gallery|accessdate=8 September 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\n\nLusk was born in [[Dunedin]], [[Otago]], New Zealand on 5 May 1916. She was the daughter of Alice Mary (n\u00e9e Coats), and Thomas Younger Lusk, a draughtsman and architect, and had two older siblings, Marion and Paxton.<ref name=\"DNZB Lusk\">{{cite web|last1=Beaven|first1=Lisa|title=Lusk, Doris More|url=http://www.teara.govt.nz/en/biographies/5l22/lusk-doris-more|website=Te Ara|accessdate=7 March 2015}}</ref>\n\nThe family moved to [[Hamilton, New Zealand|Hamilton]] where she went to primary school. A woman who had an art studio near to the Lusks, encouraged her to paint. In 1928 the family returned to Dunedin when her father joined the architectural firm, Mandeno and Frazer. Lusk had one more year at Arthur Street primary school before attending Otago Girl's High School in 1930.\n\nIn 1933 she left high school, before she matriculated, and enrolled in the [[King Edward Technical College]], the formal name for the Dunedin School of Art.<ref name=\"DNZB Lusk\"/> Lusk enrolled against her father's wishes and later noted there had been 'one hell of a row' about her decision.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Kirker|first1=Anne|title=New Zealand women artists|date=1986|publisher=Reed Methuen|location=Auckland|isbn=0474001814}}</ref>{{Rp|106}}\n\nLusk attended the art school from 1934 to 1939. The school was a member of the La Trobe programme which involved the importation of practising artists from England to staff New Zealand schools. These artists included [[W. H. Allen]] and [[Robert Nettleton Field|R. N Field]], who arrived in 1925 and had a major impact on the Dunedin art scene.\n\nLusk was taught by [[J. D. Charlton Edgar|Charlton Edgar]] and took life classes under [[Russell Clark (artist)|Russell Clark]] in his studio.<ref name='Summers'>{{cite journal|last1=Summers|first1=John|title=Doris Lusk: An Appreciation|journal=Art New Zealand|date=1986|volume=40|issue=Spring|pages=54\u201357}}</ref>{{Rp|54}} Through a fellow student, Anne Hamblett, she met [[Colin McCahon]] and [[Toss Woollaston]].<ref name='Summers'/>{{Rp|54}}\n\n==Career==\nIn 1939 Lusk and a small group of her artist peers in Dunedin rented a studio in the central city, on the corner of Moray Place and Princes Street.<ref name ='DPAG'/> It was here that her first solo show was held in 1940.<ref name='Landmarks'>{{cite web|title=Landmarks: The Landscape Paintings of Doris Lusk|url=http://christchurchartgallery.org.nz/multimedia/print/digitized-gallery-publications/landmarks-the-landscape-paintings-of-doris-lusk/|website=Christchurch Art Gallery|accessdate=10 March 2015}}</ref>{{Rp|119}}\n\nIn December 1942 Lusk married Dermot Holland, and in 1943 the couple moved to Christchurch.<ref name ='Milburn'>{{cite web|last1=Milburn|first1=Felicity|title=Doris Lusk: An Inventive Eye|url=https://christchurchartgallery.org.nz/bulletin/184/doris-lusk-an-inventive-eye|website=Christchurch Art Gallery|accessdate=8 September 2016}}</ref> In Christchurch Lusk quickly became affiliated with [[The Group (New Zealand art)|The Group]], an association of artists based in that city but with ties to artists throughout New Zealand.<ref name=\"DNZB Lusk\"/> Although Lusk's painting output was restricted due to the obligations of caring for her young children, she quickly became established with special reference to her landscape painting.<ref name=\"DNZB Lusk\"/> The combined exhibitions held by The Group members suited her better than striving to make enough work for solo exhibitions at this point in her career; as she later recalled \"I did not paint in a continual professional manner. I painted when I could, and I would produce about six paintings a year, which was pretty good going in the circumstances.\"<ref name ='Milburn'/>\n\nIn the 1940s Lusk completed a series of paintings, including ''Landscape, Overlooking Kaitawa, Waikaremoana'' (1948), which documented the massive engineering projects underlying the development of the Lake Waikaremoana hydroelectric scheme in the central North Island.<ref name='Te Papa'>{{cite book|last1=McAloon|first1=William|title=Art at Te Papa|date=2009|publisher=Te Papa Press|location=Wellington|isbn=9781877385483|page=222}}</ref> She had a close friendship with Adelaide and Ian McCubbin - Ian was a construction engineer on the Lake Waikaremoana project.<ref name ='Milburn'/> Through the McCubbins Lusk was introduced to [[Onekaka]] in [[Golden Bay]], and especially the long wharf built for the exporting of [[pig iron]] from the nearby ironworks. Lusk took this landscape as her subject for the next 25 years.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Milburn|first1=Felicity|title=Onekaka Estuary by Doris Lusk|url=https://christchurchartgallery.org.nz/blog/collection/2016/09/onekaka-estuary-by-doris-lusk|website=Christchurch Art Gallery|accessdate=8 September 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn 1979, two years before she ceased teaching at the art school, Lusk began a series of works based on buildings in Christchurch's central city that were being demolished in order to build office buildings and apartment blocks.<ref name ='Milburn'/> She worked from photographs that she took and collaged with images culled from newspapers, and translated these into paintings made with watercolour, acrylic and coloured pencil.<ref name ='Milburn'/> In a 1983 interview Lusk denied that the subject carried any psychological charge, saying that \"My work is really very practical, and it would be quite dishonest if I tried to put in psychological meanings [\u2026] The Demolition works were a little misunderstood. [People thought] that I became very fascinated with the factual destruction of buildings as a sort of sociological thing. But that was not true [\u2026] It was a visual image to hang my media painting on, that\u2019s all.\"<ref name ='Milburn'/>\n\nLusk's late series of watercolours, ''The Arcade Awnings'', based on the famous tourist scene at [[Piazza San Marco|St Mark's Square]] in Venice, is held in the collection of the [[Auckland Art Gallery]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Doris Lusk Arcade Awnings|url=http://www.aucklandartgallery.com/whats-on/events/2004/august/doris-lusk-arcade-awnings|website=Auckland Art Gallery|accessdate=10 March 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150923180625/http://www.aucklandartgallery.com/whats-on/events/2004/august/doris-lusk-arcade-awnings|archivedate=23 September 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn Gordon H Brown and Hamish Keith's 1969 book ''An introduction to New Zealand painting 1839\u20131967'' (the first modern overview of painting in New Zealand) Lusk's work was contextualised with that of artists such as [[Rita Angus]], McCahon and [[Toss Woollaston]]. The authors wrote:\n\n<blockquote>In a number of ways the unpretentious, well-considered and solid qualities of her work summed-up a good deal that was thought to be the best tendencies of the Canterbury painters during this decade. In essence it was straightforward, uncomplicated and while not denying detail when necessary, remained uncluttered. Doris Lusk continued to develop this style through the 1940s and fifties with paintings like ''Tahananui'', ''Power House at Tuai'' and ''Botanical Gardens, H\u0101wera''.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Brown|first1=Gordon H|last2=Keith|first2=Hamish|title=An introduction to New Zealand painting 1839\u20131967|date=1969|publisher=Collins|location=Auckland|pages=135\u20136}}</ref></blockquote>\n\nIn a 1996 publication accompanying ''Landmarks: The Landscape Paintings of Doris Lusk'', an exhibition of Lusk's work she co-curated, art historian Lisa Beaven disputed this assessment, writing:\n\n<blockquote>An analysis of her art throughout her career reveals a deep fascination with particular motifs, centring around industrial imagery in landscape settings. For more than five decades, Lusk consistently pursued this preoccupation, using different techniques and employing different media. From being the result of random excursions, Lusk's paintings were directed explorations, not just of the relationship between the structures and the land around them, but also of the buildings themselves, and aspects of the juxtapositions of interior and exterior, exposure and concealment, surface and depth. The manifold layers of meaning embedded in the buildings and their role in projecting a certain mood, suggest her painting may profit from being read as expressions of moods, metaphors and symbols.<ref name='Landmarks'/>{{Rp|9\u201310}}</blockquote>\n\nArt historian Julie King, in a review of ''Landmarks'', noted that the exhibition gave the opportunity to assess Lusk's later paintings, and 'how she was positioned in relation to the new artistic models, values, and professionalism of the art institutional world which emerged in New Zealand in the late 1950s and '60s.'<ref name=King>{{cite journal|last1=King|first1=Julie|title=Landmarks: The Landscape Paintings of Doris Lusk|journal=Art New Zealand|date=Spring 1996|issue=80|pages=67\u201371}}</ref> King argued that the negative reception of Lusk's previous 1973 survey exhibition (organised by the [[Dowse Art Museum]] and toured to [[Auckland Art Gallery|Auckland City Art Gallery]]) by Auckland critics reflected the 'exclusivity of the canon created in Auckland by critics and curators in the early '70s' and the way art history in New Zealand had been written, 'with its focus on Colin McCahon and modernism, on internationalism and abstraction, so that placed within this context, her career appears peripheral.'<ref name=King/>{{Rp|70}}\n\nIn the same article, King examined how being a woman artist may have inflected Lusk's career and opportunities:\n\n<blockquote>Despite her reluctance to acknowledge the political issues surrounding women's art practice, Lusk's significance also lies within the history of women's artistic culture during the post-war period. At a time when social assumptions emphasised women's domestic role, she challenged these expectations by retaining her firm commitment to painting, and gained recognition as one of New Zealand's leading painters. Yet her painting was always fitted within the constraints of domestic life. After her marriage and birth of three children in the '40s, she dealt with the practicalities of looking after her family by painting in the kitchen,and it was not until the late '60s that she even had a studio of her own. Lusk was unable to study overseas until 1974, and her art was fitted into her personal life, so that visits to friends at Tuai and family holidays became her opportunity for painting.<ref name=King/>{{Rp|70}}</blockquote>\n\nIn a 1996 article, art historian Grant Banbury noted that while Lusk was usually discussed in terms of her landscape painting, she also produced a number of portraits and self-portraits, and championed life drawing as both an artist and a teacher.<ref name=Banbury>{{cite journal|last1=Banbury|first1=Grant|title=The Portraits of Doris Lusk|journal=Art New Zealand|date=Spring 1996|issue=80|pages=72\u201375}}</ref>{{Rp|72}} Lusk mainly painted close friends, family and colleagues, along with a small number of commissions and a several works painted in the 1970s based on images from newspapers.<ref name=Banbury/>{{Rp|72}} In 1939, while at art school, Lusk painted a portrait of Colin McCahon; nearly 50 years later, in 1987, Lusk painted ''Return to Otago'', a portrait of Anne McCahon and their son William - Colin McCahon had died earlier that year.<ref name=Banbury/>{{Rp|72\u201373}}\n\n==Career as a potter==\n\nIn addition to her painting career, Lusk was also a pioneer potter in New Zealand.<ref name=\"DNZB Lusk\"/> She was introduced to modelling with clay by Field while at art school, which ignited her interest in the medium.<ref name ='DPAG'/> She made her ceramics largely under her married name, Doris Holland, most of it in earthenware.<ref name ='DPAG'/>\n\nIn 1947 she began teaching pottery at Risingholme Community Centre with Margaret Frankel, and continued there until 1967. She was president of the Canterbury Potters' Association from 1970 to 1972.<ref name=\"DNZB Lusk\"/> In 1970 she was awarded a travel scholarship by the Canterbury Society of Arts and used this to research contemporary Australian ceramics in [[Canberra]], [[Adelaide]], [[Alice Springs]] and [[Melbourne]].<ref name='Landmarks'/>{{Rp|122}}\n\n==Teaching career==\n\nLusk was appointed a tutor at the [[Ilam School of Fine Arts|University of Canterbury School of Fine Arts]] in 1966 and was made a permanent staff member within the following 18 months. She continued to teach at the School until 1981.<ref>{{cite web|title=Doris Lusk|url=http://christchurchartgallery.org.nz/media/uploads/2010_07/Doris_Lusk_Landscape_overlooking_Kaitawa_69_92.pdf|website=Christchurch Art Gallery|accessdate=10 March 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402100227/http://christchurchartgallery.org.nz/media/uploads/2010_07/Doris_Lusk_Landscape_overlooking_Kaitawa_69_92.pdf|archivedate=2 April 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n==Exhibiting career and retrospective exhibitions==\n\nLusk exhibited mainly with [[The Group (New Zealand art)|The Group]] in Christchurch in the 1940s and 1950s.<ref name=\"DNZB Lusk\"/> In the 1950s and 1960s her work was regularly included in the [[Auckland Art Gallery|Auckland City Art Gallery]]'s annual surveys of recent New Zealand painting.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Beaven|first1=Lisa|last2=Banbury|first2=Grant|title=Landmarks : the landscape paintings of Doris Lusk / Lisa Beaven and Grant Banbury|date=1996|publisher=Hazard Press and Robert McDougall Art Gallery|location=Christchurch|isbn=0908874391}}</ref>\n\nThe first retrospective exhibition of Lusk's work was held at the [[Dunedin Public Art Gallery]] in 1966.<ref name=\"DNZB Lusk\"/> A second retrospective was held at the [[Dowse Art Museum]] in 1973.<ref name=\"DNZB Lusk\"/> A major exhibition of her landscape works, ''Landmarks: The Landscape Paintings of Doris Lusk'', was held at the [[Christchurch Art Gallery]] in 1996, accompanied by a publication with contributions by Lisa Beaven and Grant Banbury.<ref name='Landmarks'/>\n\nTo mark the centenary of Lusk's birth in 1916, in 2016 exhibitions were held at the Dunedin Public Art Gallery (''Doris Lusk 1916-1990'') and Christchurch Art Gallery (''Doris Lusk: Practical Visionary'').<ref name ='DPAG'/><ref>{{cite web|title=Doris Lusk: Practical Visionary|url=https://christchurchartgallery.org.nz/exhibitions/doris-lusk-practical-visionary|website=Christchurch Art Gallery|accessdate=8 September 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Collections==\n\nExamples of Lusk's work are held by most New Zealand public art galleries. Significant works include ''Tahunanui'' in the [[Hocken Collections]];<ref>{{cite web|title=Collection: Works by Doris Lusk|url=http://otago.ourheritage.ac.nz/items/browse?collection=31|website=Otago University Research Heritage|publisher=University of Otago|accessdate=2 June 2015}}</ref> ''Tobacco Fields, Pangatotara, Nelson'' (1943) and ''The Pumping Station'' (1958) at the [[Auckland Art Gallery]]; ''Power House, Tuai'' (1948), ''Landscape, Overlooking Kaitawa, Waikaremoana'' (1948) and ''Canterbury Plains from Cashmere Hills'' (1952) at the [[Christchurch Art Gallery]]; ''Akaroa Harbour, Banks Peninsula'' (1949) in the collection of the [[Museum of New Zealand Te Papa Tongarewa]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Tahunanui|url=http://www.teara.govt.nz/en/artwork/28996/tahunanui-doris-lusk|website=Te Ara|accessdate=10 March 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Power House, Tuai (1948)|url=http://christchurchartgallery.org.nz/collection/objects/95-65|website=Christchurch Art Gallery|accessdate=10 March 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150403134935/http://christchurchartgallery.org.nz/collection/objects/95-65/|archivedate=3 April 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Landscape, Overlooking Kaitawa, Waikaremoana (1948)|url=http://christchurchartgallery.org.nz/collection/objects/69-92/|website=Christchurch Art Gallery|accessdate=10 March 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20150310025148/http://christchurchartgallery.org.nz/collection/objects/69-92/|archivedate=10 March 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Canterbury Plains from Cashmere Hills (1952)|url=http://christchurchartgallery.org.nz/collection/objects/74-172/|website=Christchurch Art Gallery|accessdate=10 March 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402113317/http://christchurchartgallery.org.nz/collection/objects/74-172/|archivedate=2 April 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=The Pumping Station (1958)|url=http://www.aucklandartgallery.com/the-collection/browse-artwork/3483/the-pumping-station|website=Auckland Art Gallery|accessdate=10 March 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Tobacco Fields, Pangatotara, Nelson (1943)|url=http://www.aucklandartgallery.com/the-collection/browse-artwork/3355/tobacco-fields,-pangatotara,-nelson|website=Auckland Art Gallery|accessdate=10 March 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Further information==\n\n* [[Courtney Johnston]], [http://best-of-3.blogspot.co.nz/2016/09/on-radio.html Review of Doris Lusk centenary exhibitions], [[Radio New Zealand]], 21 September 2016\n*Anne Kirker, ''New Zealand Women Artists: A Survey of 150 Years'' (1986, Craftsman House) {{ISBN|976-8097-30-2}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n{{The Group NZ}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lusk, Doris More}}\n[[Category:1916 births]]\n[[Category:1990 deaths]]\n[[Category:New Zealand artists]]\n[[Category:New Zealand educators]]\n[[Category:New Zealand academics]]\n[[Category:New Zealand art teachers]]\n[[Category:People from Dunedin]]\n[[Category:People associated with the Canterbury Society of Arts]]\n[[Category:20th-century women artists]]\n", "text_old": "{{EngvarB|date=April 2015}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2015}}\n{{Infobox artist\n| name           = Doris More Lusk\n| image          = Photo of Doris Lusk.jpg\n| imagesize      =\n| caption        = \n| birth_name     = \n| birth_date     = {{birth date|1916|5|5|df=y}}\n| birth_place    = [[Dunedin]], New Zealand\n| death_date     = {{death date and age|1990|4|14|1916|5|5|df=y}}\n| death_place   = [[Christchurch]], New Zealand\n|| education     = Dunedin School of Art\n| field         = [[Painting]]\n| training      =\n| movement      = \n| works         =\n| patrons       =\n| awards        = \n| spouse        = {{marriage|Dermot Holland|1942|}}\n}}\n\n'''Doris More Lusk''' (5 May 1916 \u2013 14 April 1990) was a New Zealand artist and art teacher, potter, university lecturer. In 1990 she was posthumously awarded the Governor General Art Award in recognition of her artistic career and contributions.<ref name ='DPAG'>{{cite web|title=Doris Lusk 1916-1990|url=http://dunedin.art.museum/exhibitions/now/1916-1990|website=Dunedin Public Art Gallery|accessdate=8 September 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\n\nLusk was born in [[Dunedin]], [[Otago]], New Zealand on 5 May 1916. She was the daughter of Alice Mary (n\u00e9e Coats), and Thomas Younger Lusk, a draughtsman and architect, and had two older siblings, Marion and Paxton.<ref name=\"DNZB Lusk\">{{cite web|last1=Beaven|first1=Lisa|title=Lusk, Doris More|url=http://www.teara.govt.nz/en/biographies/5l22/lusk-doris-more|website=Te Ara|accessdate=7 March 2015}}</ref>\n\nThe family moved to [[Hamilton, New Zealand|Hamilton]] where she went to primary school. A woman who had an art studio near to the Lusks, encouraged her to paint. In 1928 the family returned to Dunedin when her father joined the architectural firm, Mandeno and Frazer. Lusk had one more year at Arthur Street primary school before attending Otago Girl's High School in 1930.\n\nIn 1933 she left high school, before she matriculated, and enrolled in the [[King Edward Technical College]], the formal name for the Dunedin School of Art.<ref name=\"DNZB Lusk\"/> Lusk enrolled against her father's wishes and later noted there had been 'one hell of a row' about her decision.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Kirker|first1=Anne|title=New Zealand women artists|date=1986|publisher=Reed Methuen|location=Auckland|isbn=0474001814}}</ref>{{Rp|106}}\n\nLusk attended the art school from 1934 to 1939. The school was a member of the La Trobe programme which involved the importation of practising artists from England to staff New Zealand schools. These artists included [[W. H. Allen]] and [[Robert Nettleton Field|R. N Field]], who arrived in 1925 and had a major impact on the Dunedin art scene.\n\nLusk was taught by [[J. D. Charlton Edgar|Charlton Edgar]] and took life classes under [[Russell Clark (artist)|Russell Clark]] in his studio.<ref name='Summers'>{{cite journal|last1=Summers|first1=John|title=Doris Lusk: An Appreciation|journal=Art New Zealand|date=1986|volume=40|issue=Spring|pages=54\u201357}}</ref>{{Rp|54}} Through a fellow student, Anne Hamblett, she met [[Colin McCahon]] and [[Toss Woollaston]].<ref name='Summers'/>{{Rp|54}}\n\n==Career==\nIn 1939 Lusk and a small group of her artist peers in Dunedin rented a studio in the central city, on the corner of Moray Place and Princes Street.<ref name ='DPAG'/> It was here that her first solo show was held in 1940.<ref name='Landmarks'>{{cite web|title=Landmarks: The Landscape Paintings of Doris Lusk|url=http://christchurchartgallery.org.nz/multimedia/print/digitized-gallery-publications/landmarks-the-landscape-paintings-of-doris-lusk/|website=Christchurch Art Gallery|accessdate=10 March 2015}}</ref>{{Rp|119}}\n\nIn December 1942 Lusk married Dermot Holland, and in 1943 the couple moved to Christchurch.<ref name ='Milburn'>{{cite web|last1=Milburn|first1=Felicity|title=Doris Lusk: An Inventive Eye|url=https://christchurchartgallery.org.nz/bulletin/184/doris-lusk-an-inventive-eye|website=Christchurch Art Gallery|accessdate=8 September 2016}}</ref> In Christchurch Lusk quickly became affiliated with [[The Group (New Zealand art)|The Group]], an association of artists based in that city but with ties to artists throughout New Zealand.<ref name=\"DNZB Lusk\"/> Although Lusk's painting output was restricted due to the obligations of caring for her young children, she quickly became established with special reference to her landscape painting.<ref name=\"DNZB Lusk\"/> The combined exhibitions held by The Group members suited her better than striving to make enough work for solo exhibitions at this point in her career; as she later recalled \"I did not paint in a continual professional manner. I painted when I could, and I would produce about six paintings a year, which was pretty good going in the circumstances.\"<ref name ='Milburn'/>\n\nIn the 1940s Lusk completed a series of paintings, including ''Landscape, Overlooking Kaitawa, Waikaremoana'' (1948), which documented the massive engineering projects underlying the development of the Lake Waikaremoana hydroelectric scheme in the central North Island.<ref name='Te Papa'>{{cite book|last1=McAloon|first1=William|title=Art at Te Papa|date=2009|publisher=Te Papa Press|location=Wellington|isbn=9781877385483|page=222}}</ref> She had a close friendship with Adelaide and Ian McCubbin - Ian was a construction engineer on the Lake Waikaremoana project.<ref name ='Milburn'/> Through the McCubbins Lusk was introduced to [[Onekaka]] in [[Golden Bay]], and especially the long wharf built for the exporting of [[pig iron]] from the nearby ironworks. Lusk took this landscape as her subject for the next 25 years.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Milburn|first1=Felicity|title=Onekaka Estuary by Doris Lusk|url=https://christchurchartgallery.org.nz/blog/collection/2016/09/onekaka-estuary-by-doris-lusk|website=Christchurch Art Gallery|accessdate=8 September 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn 1979, two years before she ceased teaching at the art school, Lusk began a series of works based on buildings in Christchurch's central city that were being demolished in order to build office buildings and apartment blocks.<ref name ='Milburn'/> She worked from photographs that she took and collaged with images culled from newspapers, and translated these into paintings made with watercolour, acrylic and coloured pencil.<ref name ='Milburn'/> In a 1983 interview Lusk denied that the subject carried any psychological charge, saying that \"My work is really very practical, and it would be quite dishonest if I tried to put in psychological meanings [\u2026] The Demolition works were a little misunderstood. [People thought] that I became very fascinated with the factual destruction of buildings as a sort of sociological thing. But that was not true [\u2026] It was a visual image to hang my media painting on, that\u2019s all.\"<ref name ='Milburn'/>\n\nLusk's late series of watercolours, ''The Arcade Awnings'', based on the famous tourist scene at [[Piazza San Marco|St Mark's Square]] in Venice, is held in the collection of the [[Auckland Art Gallery]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Doris Lusk Arcade Awnings|url=http://www.aucklandartgallery.com/whats-on/events/2004/august/doris-lusk-arcade-awnings|website=Auckland Art Gallery|accessdate=10 March 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150923180625/http://www.aucklandartgallery.com/whats-on/events/2004/august/doris-lusk-arcade-awnings|archivedate=23 September 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn Gordon H Brown and Hamish Keith's 1969 book ''An introduction to New Zealand painting 1839\u20131967'' (the first modern overview of painting in New Zealand) Lusk's work was contextualised with that of artists such as [[Rita Angus]], McCahon and [[Toss Woollaston]]. The authors wrote:\n\n<blockquote>In a number of ways the unpretentious, well-considered and solid qualities of her work summed-up a good deal that was thought to be the best tendencies of the Canterbury painters during this decade. In essence it was straightforward, uncomplicated and while not denying detail when necessary, remained uncluttered. Doris Lusk continued to develop this style through the 1940s and fifties with paintings like ''Tahananui'', ''Power House at Tuai'' and ''Botanical Gardens, Hawera''.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Brown|first1=Gordon H|last2=Keith|first2=Hamish|title=An introduction to New Zealand painting 1839\u20131967|date=1969|publisher=Collins|location=Auckland|pages=135\u20136}}</ref></blockquote>\n\nIn a 1996 publication accompanying ''Landmarks: The Landscape Paintings of Doris Lusk'', an exhibition of Lusk's work she co-curated, art historian Lisa Beaven disputed this assessment, writing:\n\n<blockquote>An analysis of her art throughout her career reveals a deep fascination with particular motifs, centring around industrial imagery in landscape settings. For more than five decades, Lusk consistently pursued this preoccupation, using different techniques and employing different media. From being the result of random excursions, Lusk's paintings were directed explorations, not just of the relationship between the structures and the land around them, but also of the buildings themselves, and aspects of the juxtapositions of interior and exterior, exposure and concealment, surface and depth. The manifold layers of meaning embedded in the buildings and their role in projecting a certain mood, suggest her painting may profit from being read as expressions of moods, metaphors and symbols.<ref name='Landmarks'/>{{Rp|9\u201310}}</blockquote>\n\nArt historian Julie King, in a review of ''Landmarks'', noted that the exhibition gave the opportunity to assess Lusk's later paintings, and 'how she was positioned in relation to the new artistic models, values, and professionalism of the art institutional world which emerged in New Zealand in the late 1950s and '60s.'<ref name=King>{{cite journal|last1=King|first1=Julie|title=Landmarks: The Landscape Paintings of Doris Lusk|journal=Art New Zealand|date=Spring 1996|issue=80|pages=67\u201371}}</ref> King argued that the negative reception of Lusk's previous 1973 survey exhibition (organised by the [[Dowse Art Museum]] and toured to [[Auckland Art Gallery|Auckland City Art Gallery]]) by Auckland critics reflected the 'exclusivity of the canon created in Auckland by critics and curators in the early '70s' and the way art history in New Zealand had been written, 'with its focus on Colin McCahon and modernism, on internationalism and abstraction, so that placed within this context, her career appears peripheral.'<ref name=King/>{{Rp|70}}\n\nIn the same article, King examined how being a woman artist may have inflected Lusk's career and opportunities:\n\n<blockquote>Despite her reluctance to acknowledge the political issues surrounding women's art practice, Lusk's significance also lies within the history of women's artistic culture during the post-war period. At a time when social assumptions emphasised women's domestic role, she challenged these expectations by retaining her firm commitment to painting, and gained recognition as one of New Zealand's leading painters. Yet her painting was always fitted within the constraints of domestic life. After her marriage and birth of three children in the '40s, she dealt with the practicalities of looking after her family by painting in the kitchen,and it was not until the late '60s that she even had a studio of her own. Lusk was unable to study overseas until 1974, and her art was fitted into her personal life, so that visits to friends at Tuai and family holidays became her opportunity for painting.<ref name=King/>{{Rp|70}}</blockquote>\n\nIn a 1996 article, art historian Grant Banbury noted that while Lusk was usually discussed in terms of her landscape painting, she also produced a number of portraits and self-portraits, and championed life drawing as both an artist and a teacher.<ref name=Banbury>{{cite journal|last1=Banbury|first1=Grant|title=The Portraits of Doris Lusk|journal=Art New Zealand|date=Spring 1996|issue=80|pages=72\u201375}}</ref>{{Rp|72}} Lusk mainly painted close friends, family and colleagues, along with a small number of commissions and a several works painted in the 1970s based on images from newspapers.<ref name=Banbury/>{{Rp|72}} In 1939, while at art school, Lusk painted a portrait of Colin McCahon; nearly 50 years later, in 1987, Lusk painted ''Return to Otago'', a portrait of Anne McCahon and their son William - Colin McCahon had died earlier that year.<ref name=Banbury/>{{Rp|72\u201373}}\n\n==Career as a potter==\n\nIn addition to her painting career, Lusk was also a pioneer potter in New Zealand.<ref name=\"DNZB Lusk\"/> She was introduced to modelling with clay by Field while at art school, which ignited her interest in the medium.<ref name ='DPAG'/> She made her ceramics largely under her married name, Doris Holland, most of it in earthenware.<ref name ='DPAG'/>\n\nIn 1947 she began teaching pottery at Risingholme Community Centre with Margaret Frankel, and continued there until 1967. She was president of the Canterbury Potters' Association from 1970 to 1972.<ref name=\"DNZB Lusk\"/> In 1970 she was awarded a travel scholarship by the Canterbury Society of Arts and used this to research contemporary Australian ceramics in [[Canberra]], [[Adelaide]], [[Alice Springs]] and [[Melbourne]].<ref name='Landmarks'/>{{Rp|122}}\n\n==Teaching career==\n\nLusk was appointed a tutor at the [[Ilam School of Fine Arts|University of Canterbury School of Fine Arts]] in 1966 and was made a permanent staff member within the following 18 months. She continued to teach at the School until 1981.<ref>{{cite web|title=Doris Lusk|url=http://christchurchartgallery.org.nz/media/uploads/2010_07/Doris_Lusk_Landscape_overlooking_Kaitawa_69_92.pdf|website=Christchurch Art Gallery|accessdate=10 March 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402100227/http://christchurchartgallery.org.nz/media/uploads/2010_07/Doris_Lusk_Landscape_overlooking_Kaitawa_69_92.pdf|archivedate=2 April 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n==Exhibiting career and retrospective exhibitions==\n\nLusk exhibited mainly with [[The Group (New Zealand art)|The Group]] in Christchurch in the 1940s and 1950s.<ref name=\"DNZB Lusk\"/> In the 1950s and 1960s her work was regularly included in the [[Auckland Art Gallery|Auckland City Art Gallery]]'s annual surveys of recent New Zealand painting.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Beaven|first1=Lisa|last2=Banbury|first2=Grant|title=Landmarks : the landscape paintings of Doris Lusk / Lisa Beaven and Grant Banbury|date=1996|publisher=Hazard Press and Robert McDougall Art Gallery|location=Christchurch|isbn=0908874391}}</ref>\n\nThe first retrospective exhibition of Lusk's work was held at the [[Dunedin Public Art Gallery]] in 1966.<ref name=\"DNZB Lusk\"/> A second retrospective was held at the [[Dowse Art Museum]] in 1973.<ref name=\"DNZB Lusk\"/> A major exhibition of her landscape works, ''Landmarks: The Landscape Paintings of Doris Lusk'', was held at the [[Christchurch Art Gallery]] in 1996, accompanied by a publication with contributions by Lisa Beaven and Grant Banbury.<ref name='Landmarks'/>\n\nTo mark the centenary of Lusk's birth in 1916, in 2016 exhibitions were held at the Dunedin Public Art Gallery (''Doris Lusk 1916-1990'') and Christchurch Art Gallery (''Doris Lusk: Practical Visionary'').<ref name ='DPAG'/><ref>{{cite web|title=Doris Lusk: Practical Visionary|url=https://christchurchartgallery.org.nz/exhibitions/doris-lusk-practical-visionary|website=Christchurch Art Gallery|accessdate=8 September 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Collections==\n\nExamples of Lusk's work are held by most New Zealand public art galleries. Significant works include ''Tahunanui'' in the [[Hocken Collections]];<ref>{{cite web|title=Collection: Works by Doris Lusk|url=http://otago.ourheritage.ac.nz/items/browse?collection=31|website=Otago University Research Heritage|publisher=University of Otago|accessdate=2 June 2015}}</ref> ''Tobacco Fields, Pangatotara, Nelson'' (1943) and ''The Pumping Station'' (1958) at the [[Auckland Art Gallery]]; ''Power House, Tuai'' (1948), ''Landscape, Overlooking Kaitawa, Waikaremoana'' (1948) and ''Canterbury Plains from Cashmere Hills'' (1952) at the [[Christchurch Art Gallery]]; ''Akaroa Harbour, Banks Peninsula'' (1949) in the collection of the [[Museum of New Zealand Te Papa Tongarewa]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Tahunanui|url=http://www.teara.govt.nz/en/artwork/28996/tahunanui-doris-lusk|website=Te Ara|accessdate=10 March 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Power House, Tuai (1948)|url=http://christchurchartgallery.org.nz/collection/objects/95-65|website=Christchurch Art Gallery|accessdate=10 March 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150403134935/http://christchurchartgallery.org.nz/collection/objects/95-65/|archivedate=3 April 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Landscape, Overlooking Kaitawa, Waikaremoana (1948)|url=http://christchurchartgallery.org.nz/collection/objects/69-92/|website=Christchurch Art Gallery|accessdate=10 March 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20150310025148/http://christchurchartgallery.org.nz/collection/objects/69-92/|archivedate=10 March 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Canterbury Plains from Cashmere Hills (1952)|url=http://christchurchartgallery.org.nz/collection/objects/74-172/|website=Christchurch Art Gallery|accessdate=10 March 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402113317/http://christchurchartgallery.org.nz/collection/objects/74-172/|archivedate=2 April 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=The Pumping Station (1958)|url=http://www.aucklandartgallery.com/the-collection/browse-artwork/3483/the-pumping-station|website=Auckland Art Gallery|accessdate=10 March 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Tobacco Fields, Pangatotara, Nelson (1943)|url=http://www.aucklandartgallery.com/the-collection/browse-artwork/3355/tobacco-fields,-pangatotara,-nelson|website=Auckland Art Gallery|accessdate=10 March 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Further information==\n\n* [[Courtney Johnston]], [http://best-of-3.blogspot.co.nz/2016/09/on-radio.html Review of Doris Lusk centenary exhibitions], [[Radio New Zealand]], 21 September 2016\n*Anne Kirker, ''New Zealand Women Artists: A Survey of 150 Years'' (1986, Craftsman House) {{ISBN|976-8097-30-2}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n{{The Group NZ}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lusk, Doris More}}\n[[Category:1916 births]]\n[[Category:1990 deaths]]\n[[Category:New Zealand artists]]\n[[Category:New Zealand educators]]\n[[Category:New Zealand academics]]\n[[Category:New Zealand art teachers]]\n[[Category:People from Dunedin]]\n[[Category:People associated with the Canterbury Society of Arts]]\n[[Category:20th-century women artists]]\n", "name_user": "Onco p53", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eCareer:clean up, replaced: Hawera \u2192 H\u0101wera as perWikipedia:Naming_conventions_(New_Zealand)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Doris_Lusk"}
{"title_page": "Phife Dawg", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2016}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name             = Phife Dawg\n| background       = solo_singer\n| image            = Phife Dawg-mika.jpg\n| image_size       = \n| caption          = Phife Dawg in 1999\n| birth_name       = Malik Izaak Taylor\n| alias            = Phife, Phife Dawg, The Phifer, Phife Diggy, The Five-Foot Assassin, The Five-Footer, Malik The Five-Foot Freak, The Funky Diabetic, Dynomutt, Mutty Ranks, The Trini-Gladiator, Don Juice, Dr. Pepper\n| birth_date       = {{birth date|1970|11|20}}\n| birth_place      = [[St. Albans, Queens]], [[New York (state)|New York]], U.S.\n| origin           = \n| death_date       = {{Death date and age|2016|03|22|1970|11|20}}\n| death_place      = [[Oakley, California]], U.S.\n| genre            = [[Hip hop music|Hip hop]]\n| occupation       = Rapper\n| instrument       = Vocals\n| years_active     = 1988\u20132016<ref name=\"thesource\"/>\n| label            = [[Jive Records|Jive]], Groove Attack Records\n| associated_acts  = [[A Tribe Called Quest]], [[De La Soul]], [[Jungle Brothers]], [[J Dilla]], [[Hi-Tek]], [[Pete Rock]], [[Busta Rhymes]], [[Queen Latifah]], [[Monie Love]], [[TLC (band)|TLC]]\n| website          = \n}}\n'''Malik Izaak Taylor'''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://phifedawgs.com/|title=Ghostface Killah, Jay Electronica and Others Honor 'Phife Dawg'|publisher=Hip-Hop Wired|date=January 20, 2010|accessdate=February 23, 2016|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160831204521/http://phifedawgs.com/|archivedate=August 31, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref> (November 20, 1970{{snd}}March 22, 2016), known professionally as '''Phife Dawg''' (or simply '''Phife'''), was an American [[rapper]] and a member of the group [[A Tribe Called Quest]] with [[Q-Tip (rapper)|Q-Tip]] and [[Ali Shaheed Muhammad]] (and for a short time [[Jarobi White]]). He was also known as the \"Five-Foot Assassin\" and \"The Five-Footer\", because he stood at {{convert|5|ft|3|in}}.\n\n==Career==\nPhife Dawg initially formed [[A Tribe Called Quest]], then simply named Quest, with childhood friend [[Q-Tip (musician)|Q-Tip]] and DJ [[Ali Shaheed Muhammad]] in 1985;<ref name=\"thesource\">{{cite journal|last=Lewis |first=Miles |title=After the Love is Gone |work=[[The Source]] |publisher=[[L. Londell McMillan]]|date=October 1998 }}</ref> the group was later expanded with the addition of [[Jarobi White]]. A Tribe Called Quest were closely associated with fellow hip-hop acts [[De La Soul]] and [[Jungle Brothers]], with the groups being collectively known as the [[Native Tongues]].<ref name=\"avc\">{{cite web|url=https://news.avclub.com/r-i-p-malik-phife-dawg-taylor-co-founder-of-a-tribe-1798245583|title=R.I.P. Malik \"Phife Dawg\" Taylor, co-founder of A Tribe Called Quest|last=Chavez|first=Danette|date=March 23, 2016|publisher=[[The A.V. Club]]|accessdate=March 23, 2016}}</ref> A Tribe Called Quest were initially offered a demo deal by [[Geffen Records]] in 1989, but signed to [[Jive Records]] to release their 1990 d\u00e9but ''[[People's Instinctive Travels and the Paths of Rhythm]]''.<ref name=avc/>\n\nPhife Dawg's contributions to the group increased on their second album, 1991's ''[[The Low End Theory]]'', which saw Phife\u2014often referring to himself as \"the Five-Foot Assassin\"\u2014rapping about social and political issues; the record has since been acclaimed by critics and fellow musicians.<ref name=avc/> The group released three further albums throughout the decade\u2014''[[Midnight Marauders]]'' in 1993, ''[[Beats, Rhymes and Life]]'' in 1996, and ''[[The Love Movement]]'' in 1998\u2014before disbanding as a result of conflict both with their record label and between members. The band's troubles, especially the tense relationship between Phife and Q-Tip, were featured in the 2011 documentary ''[[Beats, Rhymes & Life: The Travels of A Tribe Called Quest]]'', directed by [[Michael Rapaport]].<ref name=avc/>\n\nIn addition to being a member of pioneering hip hop group A Tribe Called Quest, Phife performed on songs with other artists. He was featured on the [[Fu-Schnickens]] song \"[[La Schmoove]]\", [[Diamond D]]'s \"Painz & Strife\" with [[Pete Rock]], and [[Chi-Ali]]'s \"Let the Horns Blow\" with [[Dres (rapper)|Dres]], [[The Beatnuts|Al' Tariq]] and [[David Jolicoeur|Trugoy]]. In 2000, he released his debut solo album, ''[[Ventilation: Da LP]]''. In 2013, it was reported that Phife was working on a solo album titled ''MUTTYmorPHosis''.<ref>{{cite web|title=A Tribe Called Quest {{!}} Phife Dawg Pens Song Tribute To J. Dilla|url=http://www.contactmusic.com/story/phife-dawg-pens-song-tribute-to-j-dilla_3973465|work=[[Contactmusic.com]]|accessdate=November 28, 2013|author=WENN|date=November 28, 2013}}</ref> A single titled \"Sole Men\" was released one day after Phife's death (March 23, 2016) along with a posthumously released music video.<ref>{{Citation|last=Steve Petersen|title=\"Sole Men\" Music Video {{!}} Phife Dawg|date=2016-03-23|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=NnEH7uNduJE|accessdate=2018-02-11}}</ref> Another single, \"Nutshell\", was released online in April 2016 along with a posthumously released music video.<ref name=avc/>\n\nOn November 13, 2015, A Tribe Called Quest reunited for a performance on ''[[The Tonight Show Starring Jimmy Fallon]]'', in commemoration of the 25th anniversary of ''People's Instinctive Travels and the Paths of Rhythm''.<ref name=\"toure\">{{cite web | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/11/06/arts/music/a-tribe-called-quest-new-album-interview.html?_r=0 | title=Loss Haunts A Tribe Called Quest's First Album in 18 Years | work=[[The New York Times]] | date=November 2, 2016 | accessdate=March 28, 2020 | author=Tour\u00e9}}</ref> That night, Phife and Q-Tip decided to put aside their differences and record a new group album, ''[[We Got It from Here... Thank You 4 Your Service]]'', in secrecy.<ref name=\"toure\"/> Phife spent four months working on the album before his death; it was completed by the surviving group members and released on November 11, 2016.<ref name=\"toure\"/> In February 2017, it was announced that Phife's second studio album, posthumously titled ''Forever'', would be released later in the year. The single \"Wanna Dance\" was released that month and features [[Dwele]] and [[Mike City]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://hiphopdx.com/news/id.42369/title.phife-dawgs-posthumous-solo-album-to-be-titled-forever|title=Phife Dawg's Posthumous Solo Album To Be Titled \"Forever\"|first=HipHopDX -|last=http://hiphopdx.com|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\n\nPhife Dawg was born Malik Izaak Taylor to Cheryl Allison Boyce-Taylor and Walt Taylor on November 20, 1970. He was born prematurely and his twin Mikal died shortly after birth. His mother, who was born in [[Arima]], [[Trinidad and Tobago]], moved to [[St. Albans, Queens|St. Albans]] in [[Queens, New York]] when she was 13 years old.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://ubuntubiographyproject.com/2017/12/06/cheryl-boyce-taylor/|title=Cheryl Boyce-Taylor|last=|first=|date=December 6, 2017|work=The Ubuntu Biography Project by Stephen A. Maglott|access-date=27 April 2018}}</ref> Phife described himself as a \"West Indian\" of Trinidadian descent.<ref name=hiphopdx>{{cite web|url=http://www.hiphopdx.com/index/interviews/id.1545/title.phife-dawg-his-name-is-mutty-ranks|title=Phife Dawg: His Name Is Mutty Ranks|publisher=HipHopDX|accessdate=November 24, 2010}}</ref> He was a cousin of writer [[Zinzi Clemmons]].<ref>Clemmons, Zinzi, [https://www.theparisreview.org/blog/2016/03/25/a-gritty-little-something-on-the-new-york-street/ \"A Gritty Little Something on the New York Street\"], ''[[The Paris Review]]'', March 25, 2016.</ref>\n\nPhife was an avid sports fan and was featured on various radio shows and sports programming on ESPN.<ref>{{cite web|accessdate=February 23, 2016 |url=http://espn.go.com/espnradio/play?id=9236357|title=Phife Dawg, Rapper|website=Espn.go.com}}</ref> He was also a playable character in the video games ''[[NBA 2K7]]'' and ''[[NBA 2K9]]''.\n\nPhife was diagnosed with [[diabetes mellitus]]<!--conflicting reliable sources state different types--> in May 1990. Conflicting reports indicate it as [[diabetes mellitus type 1|type 1]],<ref>{{cite news|title=Phife Dawg of A Tribe Called Quest Has Passed Away, But His Legacy Lives On|url=http://www.vh1.com/news/252973/phife-dawg-tribe-called-quest-died/|accessdate=November 28, 2016|work=VH1 News}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Phife Dawg Dead: A Tribe Called Quest Rapper Honored on Social Media|url=http://people.com/celebrity/phife-dawg-dead-a-tribe-called-quest-rapper-honored-on-social-media/|accessdate=November 28, 2016|work=PEOPLE.com|publisher=Time Inc.|date=23 March 2016}}</ref> while other sources report it as [[diabetes mellitus type 2|type 2]].<ref name=\"bbc\"/><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nme.com/news/a-tribe-called-quest/92478|title=Phife Dawg Of A Tribe Called Quest Reportedly Dead At 45|author=NME.COM|work=NME.COM|date=March 23, 2016|accessdate=March 23, 2016}}</ref> He mentioned being a \"funky diabetic\" in the single \"[[Oh My God (A Tribe Called Quest song)|Oh My God]]\" from the group's third album, ''[[Midnight Marauders]]''.<ref>{{cite web|author=Kamau High|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/1043898/the-cool-kids-to-headline-nba2k9-tour|title=The Cool Kids To Headline 'NBA2K9' Tour|publisher=Billboard|accessdate=February 23, 2016}}</ref> After being on a waiting list for two years,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://allhiphop.com/2008/10/24/exclusive-rapper-phife-receives-kidney-transplant/|title=Hip-Hop News, Rumors, Rap Music & Videos -AllHipHop\u00bb EXCLUSIVE: Rapper Phife Receives Kidney Transplant|author=Allhiphop |work=Hip-Hop News, Rumors, Rap Music & Videos -AllHipHop|date=October 24, 2008}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Phife Dawg Gets Kidney Transplant|accessdate=March 23, 2016|date=October 27, 2008|url=http://www.contactmusic.com/news/phife-dawg-gets-kidney-transplant_1084778|author=WENN|work=Contactmusic.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url= http://www.phresh.cc/news/music/a-tribe-called-quest-rapper-phife-dawg-gets-kidney-transplant/|title=A Tribe Called Quest Rapper, Phife Dawg Gets Kidney Transplant |accessdate=March 23, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://madnewsuk.com/2008/10/24/rapper-phife-dawg-receives-long-awaited-kidney-transplant/|title=Rapper PHIFE DAWG Receives Long Awaited Kidney Transplant|work=MAD NEWS|date=October 24, 2008|accessdate=March 23, 2016}}</ref> Phife received a [[kidney transplant]] from his wife in 2008. It was unsuccessful, however, and by 2012 he once again required a transplant.<ref name=bbc>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-35879876 |title=Tribe Called Quest star Phife Dawg dies aged 45|first=Mark|last=Savage|publisher=[[BBC News]]|date=March 23, 2016|accessdate=March 23, 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Death===\nPhife died at the age of 45 in his home in [[Contra Costa County, California]], on March 22, 2016, due to complications related to diabetes.<ref name=bbc/><ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/hip-hop/7271780/phife-dawg-a-tribe-called-quest-obit|title=Phife Dawg, Founding Member of A Tribe Called Quest, Dead at 45|work=Billboard|date=March 23, 2016|accessdate=March 23, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Meline, Gabe|url=http://ww2.kqed.org/arts/2016/03/23/why-phife-mattered-remembering-hip-hops-relatable-mc/|title=Why Phife Mattered: Remembering Hip-Hop\u2019s Relatable MC|publisher=[[KQED]]|date=March 23, 2016|accessdate=March 23, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Legacy==\n\nPhife has been described as having had a \"self-deprecating swagger\", and his work with A Tribe Called Quest helped to challenge the \"macho posturing\" of rap and hip-hop music during the late 1980s and early 1990s.<ref name=bbc/> Phife's work has been cited as an influence on [[Kanye West]], [[Jill Scott]], [[The Roots]] and [[Common (rapper)|Common]],<ref name=avc/> while the 1991 album ''[[The Low End Theory]]'' is considered one of the greatest hip-hop albums ever released.<ref name=\"bbc\"/>\n\n==Discography==\n{{further|A Tribe Called Quest discography}}\n\n===Studio albums===\n\n*''[[Ventilation: Da LP]]'' (2000)\n*''Forever''<ref>{{cite web|title=Phife Dawg's Posthumous Solo Album To Be Titled \"Forever\"|url=http://hiphopdx.com/news/id.42369/title.phife-dawgs-posthumous-solo-album-to-be-titled-forever|website=HipHopDX|accessdate=15 April 2017}}</ref> (TBA)\n\n===Guest appearances===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|+ List of guest appearances\n! Title\n! Year\n! Other performer(s)\n! Album\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"[[Buddy (De La Soul song)|Buddy (Native Tongue Decision)]]\"\n| 1989\n| [[De La Soul]], [[Q-Tip (musician)|Q-Tip]], [[Jungle Brothers]], [[Queen Latifah]], [[Monie Love]]\n| ''Buddy'' (VLS)\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"Let the Horns Blow\"\n| rowspan=\"2\"| 1992\n| [[Chi-Ali]], [[Dres (rapper)|Dres]], [[The Beatnuts|Fashion]], [[David Jude Jolicoeur|Trugoy the Dove]]\n| ''[[The Fabulous Chi-Ali]]''\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"[[La Schmoove]]\"\n| [[Fu-Schnickens]]\n| ''[[F.U. Don't Take It Personal]]''\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"Where Ya At?\"\n| rowspan=\"2\"| 1993\n| rowspan=\"2\"| [[Shaquille O'Neal]]\n| rowspan=\"2\"| ''[[Shaq Diesel]]''\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"Giggin' on 'Em\"\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"Intro-lude\" \n| 1994\n| [[TLC (group)|TLC]]\n| ''[[CrazySexyCool]]''\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"Who Got the Funk\"\n| rowspan=\"2\"| 1995\n| Science of Sound\n| ''Kaleidoscope Phonetics''\n|-\n! scope=\"row| \"Artical\"\n| Whitey Don, [[Fu-Schnickens|Chip Fu]]\n| ''Artical'' (VLS)\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"Game Day\"\n| 1996\n| [[Rodney Hampton]]\n| ''[[NFL Jams (1996 album)|NFL Jams]]''\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"Painz & Strife\"\n| rowspan=\"3\"| 1997\n| [[Diamond D]], [[Pete Rock]]\n| ''[[Hatred, Passions and Infidelity]]''\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"Let Me Be the One ([[The Ummah|Ummah]] Remix Featuring Phife)\"\n| [[Mint Condition]]\n| ''Let Me Be the One'' (VLS)\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"All I Do ([[J Dilla|Jay Dee]]'s Shit! Mix)\"\n| [[Somethin' for the People]]\n| ''All I Do'' (CDS)\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"Never Say Goodbye\"\n| 1998\n| [[Adriana Evans]]\n| [[Ride (soundtrack)|''Ride'' soundtrack]]\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"Phife's Speech\"\n| rowspan=\"4\"| 2000\n| rowspan=\"3\"| Ambivalence\n| rowspan=\"3\"| ''Electric Treatment''\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"Committed\"\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"What's da Deal\"\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"Hold Ya Karna\"\n| Mastermind, Nefarius\n| ''Mastermind Presents Volume 50: Street Legal''\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"In My Mind (Dodge's Main Mix)\"\n| rowspan=\"3\"| 2001\n| rowspan=\"2\"| [[Al Jarreau]]\n| rowspan=\"2\"| ''Tomorrow Today (Reissue)''\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"In My Mind (Dodge's Melodic Mix)\"\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"Solo Movement\"\n| K-Mel\n| ''Reflexions Vol. 1''\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"Take You There\"\n| 2002\n| [[AK1200]]\n| ''Shoot to Kill''\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"Nah Mean\"\n| 2003\n| [[will.i.am]]\n| ''[[Must B 21]]''\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"How It's Gonna Be\"\n| rowspan=\"2\"| 2004\n| rowspan=\"2\"| Truth Enola\n| ''6 O'Clock Straight''\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"How It's Gonna Be (Remix)\"\n| ''Ten Past 6''\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"Scheming\"\n| 2010\n| [[Slum Village]], [[Kelvin Mercer|Posdnuos]]\n| ''[[Villa Manifesto]]''\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"Tell the Whole City\"\n| rowspan=\"2\"| 2011\n| [[Consequence (rapper)|Consequence]]\n| ''Movies on Demand 2''\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"They Say (Legendary Remix)\"\n| [[Slum Village|T3]], [[Rapper Big Pooh]]\n| ''3illa Madness''\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"Dues n Donts\"\n| 2012\n| [[Oh No (musician)|Oh No]], [[Jos\u00e9 James]]\n| ''Ohnomite''\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"Seek Well\"\n| 2013\n| [[CJ Fly]], A La Sole\n| ''[[Thee Way Eye See It]]''\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"Push It Along\"\n| 2015\n| Slum Village\n| ''[[Yes! (Slum Village album)|Yes!]]''\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"All Around the World\"\n| 2018\n| [[The Black Eyed Peas|Black Eyed Peas]], [[Ali Shaheed Muhammad]], Posdnuos\n| ''[[Masters of the Sun Vol. 1]]''\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"No Place Like Home\"\n| 2019\n| Consequence\n| {{n/a}}\n|}\n\n==Filmography==\n*1993: ''[[Who's the Man?]]''&nbsp;\u2013 Gerald\n*1998: ''[[The Rugrats Movie]]''&nbsp;\u2013 Newborn Baby\n*2007:  ''[[NBA 2K8]]''&nbsp;\u2013 Himself\n*2011: ''[[Beats, Rhymes & Life: The Travels of A Tribe Called Quest]]''&nbsp;\u2013 Himself\n*2017: ''[[NBA 2K18]]''&nbsp;- Himself\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n* {{IMDb name|0205954}}\n* [http://atribecalledquest.com/ Official A Tribe Called Quest website]\n\n{{A Tribe Called Quest}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Phife Dawg}}\n[[Category:1970 births]]\n[[Category:2016 deaths]]\n[[Category:American male rappers]]\n[[Category:Rappers from New York City]]\n[[Category:A Tribe Called Quest members]]\n[[Category:People from St. Albans, Queens]]\n[[Category:Rappers from Atlanta]]\n[[Category:American rappers of Trinidad and Tobago descent]]\n[[Category:East Coast hip hop musicians]]\n[[Category:Deaths from diabetes]]\n[[Category:Kidney transplant recipients]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2016}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n|name = Phife Dawg\n|background = solo_singer\n|image = Phife Dawg-mika.jpg\n|image_size = \n|caption = Phife Dawg in 1999\n|birth_name = Malik Izaak Taylor\n|alias = Phife, Phife Dawg, The Phifer, Phife Diggy, The Five-Foot Assassin, The Five-Footer, Malik The Five-Foot Freak, The Funky Diabetic, Dynomutt, Mutty Ranks, The Trini-Gladiator, Don Juice, Dr. Pepper\n|birth_date = {{birth date|1970|11|20}}\n|birth_place = [[St. Albans, Queens]], [[New York (state)|New York]], U.S.\n|origin = \n|death_date = {{Death date and age|2016|03|22|1970|11|20}}\n|death_place = [[Oakley, California]], U.S.\n|genre = [[Hip hop music|Hip hop]]\n|occupation = Rapper\n|instrument = Vocals\n|years_active = 1985\u20132016<ref name=\"thesource\"/>\n|label = [[Jive Records|Jive]], Groove Attack Records\n|associated_acts = [[A Tribe Called Quest]], [[De La Soul]], [[Jungle Brothers]], [[J Dilla]], [[Hi-Tek]], [[Pete Rock]], [[Busta Rhymes]], [[Queen Latifah]], [[Monie Love]], [[TLC (band)|TLC]]\n|website =\n}}\n'''Malik Izaak Taylor'''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://phifedawgs.com/|title=Ghostface Killah, Jay Electronica and Others Honor 'Phife Dawg'|publisher=Hip-Hop Wired|date=January 20, 2010|accessdate=February 23, 2016|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160831204521/http://phifedawgs.com/|archivedate=August 31, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref> (November 20, 1970{{snd}}March 22, 2016), known professionally as '''Phife Dawg''' (or simply '''Phife'''), was an American [[rapper]] and a member of the group [[A Tribe Called Quest]] with [[Q-Tip (rapper)|Q-Tip]] and [[Ali Shaheed Muhammad]] (and for a short time [[Jarobi White]]). He was also known as the \"Five-Foot Assassin\" and \"The Five-Footer\", because he stood at {{convert|5|ft|3|in}}.\n\n==Career==\nPhife Dawg initially formed [[A Tribe Called Quest]], then simply named Quest, with childhood friend [[Q-Tip (musician)|Q-Tip]] and DJ [[Ali Shaheed Muhammad]] in 1985;<ref name=\"thesource\">{{cite journal|last=Lewis |first=Miles |title=After the Love is Gone |work=[[The Source]] |publisher=[[L. Londell McMillan]]|date=October 1998 }}</ref> the group was later expanded with the addition of [[Jarobi White]]. A Tribe Called Quest were closely associated with fellow hip-hop acts [[De La Soul]] and [[Jungle Brothers]], with the groups being collectively known as the [[Native Tongues]].<ref name=\"avc\">{{cite web|url=https://news.avclub.com/r-i-p-malik-phife-dawg-taylor-co-founder-of-a-tribe-1798245583|title=R.I.P. Malik \"Phife Dawg\" Taylor, co-founder of A Tribe Called Quest|last=Chavez|first=Danette|date=March 23, 2016|publisher=[[The A.V. Club]]|accessdate=March 23, 2016}}</ref> A Tribe Called Quest were initially offered a demo deal by [[Geffen Records]] in 1989, but signed to [[Jive Records]] to release their 1990 d\u00e9but ''[[People's Instinctive Travels and the Paths of Rhythm]]''.<ref name=avc/>\n\nPhife Dawg's contributions to the group increased on their second album, 1991's ''[[The Low End Theory]]'', which saw Phife\u2014often referring to himself as \"the Five-Foot Assassin\"\u2014rapping about social and political issues; the record has since been acclaimed by critics and fellow musicians.<ref name=avc/> The group released three further albums throughout the decade\u2014''[[Midnight Marauders]]'' in 1993, ''[[Beats, Rhymes and Life]]'' in 1996, and ''[[The Love Movement]]'' in 1998\u2014before disbanding as a result of conflict both with their record label and between members. The band's troubles, especially the tense relationship between Phife and Q-Tip, were featured in the 2011 documentary ''[[Beats, Rhymes & Life: The Travels of A Tribe Called Quest]]'', directed by [[Michael Rapaport]].<ref name=avc/>\n\nIn addition to being a member of pioneering hip hop group A Tribe Called Quest, Phife performed on songs with other artists. He was featured on the [[Fu-Schnickens]] song \"[[La Schmoove]]\", [[Diamond D]]'s \"Painz & Strife\" with [[Pete Rock]], and [[Chi-Ali]]'s \"Let the Horns Blow\" with [[Dres (rapper)|Dres]], [[The Beatnuts|Al' Tariq]] and [[David Jolicoeur|Trugoy]]. In 2000, he released his debut solo album, ''[[Ventilation: Da LP]]''. In 2013, it was reported that Phife was working on a solo album titled ''MUTTYmorPHosis''.<ref>{{cite web|title=A Tribe Called Quest {{!}} Phife Dawg Pens Song Tribute To J. Dilla|url=http://www.contactmusic.com/story/phife-dawg-pens-song-tribute-to-j-dilla_3973465|work=[[Contactmusic.com]]|accessdate=November 28, 2013|author=WENN|date=November 28, 2013}}</ref> A single titled \"Sole Men\" was released one day after Phife's death (March 23, 2016) along with a posthumously released music video.<ref>{{Citation|last=Steve Petersen|title=\"Sole Men\" Music Video {{!}} Phife Dawg|date=2016-03-23|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=NnEH7uNduJE|accessdate=2018-02-11}}</ref> Another single, \"Nutshell\", was released online in April 2016 along with a posthumously released music video.<ref name=avc/>\n\nOn November 13, 2015, A Tribe Called Quest reunited for a performance on ''[[The Tonight Show Starring Jimmy Fallon]]'', in commemoration of the 25th anniversary of ''People's Instinctive Travels and the Paths of Rhythm''.<ref name=\"toure\">{{cite web | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/11/06/arts/music/a-tribe-called-quest-new-album-interview.html?_r=0 | title=Loss Haunts A Tribe Called Quest's First Album in 18 Years | work=[[The New York Times]] | date=November 2, 2016 | accessdate=March 28, 2020 | author=Tour\u00e9}}</ref> That night, Phife and Q-Tip decided to put aside their differences and record a new group album, ''[[We Got It from Here... Thank You 4 Your Service]]'', in secrecy.<ref name=\"toure\"/> Phife spent four months working on the album before his death; it was completed by the surviving group members and released on November 11, 2016.<ref name=\"toure\"/> In February 2017, it was announced that Phife's second studio album, posthumously titled ''Forever'', would be released later in the year. The single \"Wanna Dance\" was released that month and features [[Dwele]] and [[Mike City]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://hiphopdx.com/news/id.42369/title.phife-dawgs-posthumous-solo-album-to-be-titled-forever|title=Phife Dawg's Posthumous Solo Album To Be Titled \"Forever\"|first=HipHopDX -|last=http://hiphopdx.com|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\n\nPhife Dawg was born Malik Izaak Taylor to Cheryl Allison Boyce-Taylor and Walt Taylor on November 20, 1970. He was born prematurely and his twin Mikal died shortly after birth. His mother, who was born in [[Arima]], [[Trinidad and Tobago]], moved to [[St. Albans, Queens|St. Albans]] in [[Queens, New York]] when she was 13 years old.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://ubuntubiographyproject.com/2017/12/06/cheryl-boyce-taylor/|title=Cheryl Boyce-Taylor|last=|first=|date=December 6, 2017|work=The Ubuntu Biography Project by Stephen A. Maglott|access-date=27 April 2018}}</ref> Phife described himself as a \"West Indian\" of Trinidadian descent.<ref name=hiphopdx>{{cite web|url=http://www.hiphopdx.com/index/interviews/id.1545/title.phife-dawg-his-name-is-mutty-ranks|title=Phife Dawg: His Name Is Mutty Ranks|publisher=HipHopDX|accessdate=November 24, 2010}}</ref> He was a cousin of writer [[Zinzi Clemmons]].<ref>Clemmons, Zinzi, [https://www.theparisreview.org/blog/2016/03/25/a-gritty-little-something-on-the-new-york-street/ \"A Gritty Little Something on the New York Street\"], ''[[The Paris Review]]'', March 25, 2016.</ref>\n\nPhife was an avid sports fan and was featured on various radio shows and sports programming on ESPN.<ref>{{cite web|accessdate=February 23, 2016 |url=http://espn.go.com/espnradio/play?id=9236357|title=Phife Dawg, Rapper|website=Espn.go.com}}</ref> He was also a playable character in the video games ''[[NBA 2K7]]'' and ''[[NBA 2K9]]''.\n\nPhife was diagnosed with [[diabetes mellitus]]<!--conflicting reliable sources state different types--> in May 1990. Conflicting reports indicate it as [[diabetes mellitus type 1|type 1]],<ref>{{cite news|title=Phife Dawg of A Tribe Called Quest Has Passed Away, But His Legacy Lives On|url=http://www.vh1.com/news/252973/phife-dawg-tribe-called-quest-died/|accessdate=November 28, 2016|work=VH1 News}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Phife Dawg Dead: A Tribe Called Quest Rapper Honored on Social Media|url=http://people.com/celebrity/phife-dawg-dead-a-tribe-called-quest-rapper-honored-on-social-media/|accessdate=November 28, 2016|work=PEOPLE.com|publisher=Time Inc.|date=23 March 2016}}</ref> while other sources report it as [[diabetes mellitus type 2|type 2]].<ref name=\"bbc\"/><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nme.com/news/a-tribe-called-quest/92478|title=Phife Dawg Of A Tribe Called Quest Reportedly Dead At 45|author=NME.COM|work=NME.COM|date=March 23, 2016|accessdate=March 23, 2016}}</ref> He mentioned being a \"funky diabetic\" in the single \"[[Oh My God (A Tribe Called Quest song)|Oh My God]]\" from the group's third album, ''[[Midnight Marauders]]''.<ref>{{cite web|author=Kamau High|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/1043898/the-cool-kids-to-headline-nba2k9-tour|title=The Cool Kids To Headline 'NBA2K9' Tour|publisher=Billboard|accessdate=February 23, 2016}}</ref> After being on a waiting list for two years,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://allhiphop.com/2008/10/24/exclusive-rapper-phife-receives-kidney-transplant/|title=Hip-Hop News, Rumors, Rap Music & Videos -AllHipHop\u00bb EXCLUSIVE: Rapper Phife Receives Kidney Transplant|author=Allhiphop |work=Hip-Hop News, Rumors, Rap Music & Videos -AllHipHop|date=October 24, 2008}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Phife Dawg Gets Kidney Transplant|accessdate=March 23, 2016|date=October 27, 2008|url=http://www.contactmusic.com/news/phife-dawg-gets-kidney-transplant_1084778|author=WENN|work=Contactmusic.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url= http://www.phresh.cc/news/music/a-tribe-called-quest-rapper-phife-dawg-gets-kidney-transplant/|title=A Tribe Called Quest Rapper, Phife Dawg Gets Kidney Transplant |accessdate=March 23, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://madnewsuk.com/2008/10/24/rapper-phife-dawg-receives-long-awaited-kidney-transplant/|title=Rapper PHIFE DAWG Receives Long Awaited Kidney Transplant|work=MAD NEWS|date=October 24, 2008|accessdate=March 23, 2016}}</ref> Phife received a [[kidney transplant]] from his wife in 2008. It was unsuccessful, however, and by 2012 he once again required a transplant.<ref name=bbc>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-35879876 |title=Tribe Called Quest star Phife Dawg dies aged 45|first=Mark|last=Savage|publisher=[[BBC News]]|date=March 23, 2016|accessdate=March 23, 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Death===\nPhife died at the age of 45 in his home in [[Contra Costa County, California]], on March 22, 2016, due to complications related to diabetes.<ref name=bbc/><ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/hip-hop/7271780/phife-dawg-a-tribe-called-quest-obit|title=Phife Dawg, Founding Member of A Tribe Called Quest, Dead at 45|work=Billboard|date=March 23, 2016|accessdate=March 23, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Meline, Gabe|url=http://ww2.kqed.org/arts/2016/03/23/why-phife-mattered-remembering-hip-hops-relatable-mc/|title=Why Phife Mattered: Remembering Hip-Hop\u2019s Relatable MC|publisher=[[KQED]]|date=March 23, 2016|accessdate=March 23, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Legacy==\n\nPhife has been described as having had a \"self-deprecating swagger\", and his work with A Tribe Called Quest helped to challenge the \"macho posturing\" of rap and hip-hop music during the late 1980s and early 1990s.<ref name=bbc/> Phife's work has been cited as an influence on [[Kanye West]], [[Jill Scott]], [[The Roots]] and [[Common (rapper)|Common]],<ref name=avc/> while the 1991 album ''[[The Low End Theory]]'' is considered one of the greatest hip-hop albums ever released.<ref name=\"bbc\"/>\n\n==Discography==\n{{further|A Tribe Called Quest discography}}\n\n===Studio albums===\n\n*''[[Ventilation: Da LP]]'' (2000)\n*''Forever''<ref>{{cite web|title=Phife Dawg's Posthumous Solo Album To Be Titled \"Forever\"|url=http://hiphopdx.com/news/id.42369/title.phife-dawgs-posthumous-solo-album-to-be-titled-forever|website=HipHopDX|accessdate=15 April 2017}}</ref> (TBA)\n\n===Guest appearances===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|+ List of guest appearances\n! Title\n! Year\n! Other performer(s)\n! Album\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"[[Buddy (De La Soul song)|Buddy (Native Tongue Decision)]]\"\n| 1989\n| [[De La Soul]], [[Q-Tip (musician)|Q-Tip]], [[Jungle Brothers]], [[Queen Latifah]], [[Monie Love]]\n| ''Buddy'' (VLS)\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"Let the Horns Blow\"\n| rowspan=\"2\"| 1992\n| [[Chi-Ali]], [[Dres (rapper)|Dres]], [[The Beatnuts|Fashion]], [[David Jude Jolicoeur|Trugoy the Dove]]\n| ''[[The Fabulous Chi-Ali]]''\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"[[La Schmoove]]\"\n| [[Fu-Schnickens]]\n| ''[[F.U. Don't Take It Personal]]''\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"Where Ya At?\"\n| rowspan=\"2\"| 1993\n| rowspan=\"2\"| [[Shaquille O'Neal]]\n| rowspan=\"2\"| ''[[Shaq Diesel]]''\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"Giggin' on 'Em\"\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"Intro-lude\" \n| 1994\n| [[TLC (group)|TLC]]\n| ''[[CrazySexyCool]]''\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"Who Got the Funk\"\n| rowspan=\"2\"| 1995\n| Science of Sound\n| ''Kaleidoscope Phonetics''\n|-\n! scope=\"row| \"Artical\"\n| Whitey Don, [[Fu-Schnickens|Chip Fu]]\n| ''Artical'' (VLS)\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"Game Day\"\n| 1996\n| [[Rodney Hampton]]\n| ''[[NFL Jams (1996 album)|NFL Jams]]''\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"Painz & Strife\"\n| rowspan=\"3\"| 1997\n| [[Diamond D]], [[Pete Rock]]\n| ''[[Hatred, Passions and Infidelity]]''\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"Let Me Be the One ([[The Ummah|Ummah]] Remix Featuring Phife)\"\n| [[Mint Condition]]\n| ''Let Me Be the One'' (VLS)\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"All I Do ([[J Dilla|Jay Dee]]'s Shit! Mix)\"\n| [[Somethin' for the People]]\n| ''All I Do'' (CDS)\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"Never Say Goodbye\"\n| 1998\n| [[Adriana Evans]]\n| [[Ride (soundtrack)|''Ride'' soundtrack]]\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"Phife's Speech\"\n| rowspan=\"4\"| 2000\n| rowspan=\"3\"| Ambivalence\n| rowspan=\"3\"| ''Electric Treatment''\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"Committed\"\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"What's da Deal\"\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"Hold Ya Karna\"\n| Mastermind, Nefarius\n| ''Mastermind Presents Volume 50: Street Legal''\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"In My Mind (Dodge's Main Mix)\"\n| rowspan=\"3\"| 2001\n| rowspan=\"2\"| [[Al Jarreau]]\n| rowspan=\"2\"| ''Tomorrow Today (Reissue)''\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"In My Mind (Dodge's Melodic Mix)\"\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"Solo Movement\"\n| K-Mel\n| ''Reflexions Vol. 1''\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"Take You There\"\n| 2002\n| [[AK1200]]\n| ''Shoot to Kill''\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"Nah Mean\"\n| 2003\n| [[will.i.am]]\n| ''[[Must B 21]]''\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"How It's Gonna Be\"\n| rowspan=\"2\"| 2004\n| rowspan=\"2\"| Truth Enola\n| ''6 O'Clock Straight''\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"How It's Gonna Be (Remix)\"\n| ''Ten Past 6''\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"Scheming\"\n| 2010\n| [[Slum Village]], [[Kelvin Mercer|Posdnuos]]\n| ''[[Villa Manifesto]]''\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"Tell the Whole City\"\n| rowspan=\"2\"| 2011\n| [[Consequence (rapper)|Consequence]]\n| ''Movies on Demand 2''\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"They Say (Legendary Remix)\"\n| [[Slum Village|T3]], [[Rapper Big Pooh]]\n| ''3illa Madness''\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"Dues n Donts\"\n| 2012\n| [[Oh No (musician)|Oh No]], [[Jos\u00e9 James]]\n| ''Ohnomite''\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"Seek Well\"\n| 2013\n| [[CJ Fly]], A La Sole\n| ''[[Thee Way Eye See It]]''\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"Push It Along\"\n| 2015\n| Slum Village\n| ''[[Yes! (Slum Village album)|Yes!]]''\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"All Around the World\"\n| 2018\n| [[The Black Eyed Peas|Black Eyed Peas]], [[Ali Shaheed Muhammad]], Posdnuos\n| ''[[Masters of the Sun Vol. 1]]''\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"No Place Like Home\"\n| 2019\n| Consequence\n| {{n/a}}\n|}\n\n==Filmography==\n*1993: ''[[Who's the Man?]]''&nbsp;\u2013 Gerald\n*1998: ''[[The Rugrats Movie]]''&nbsp;\u2013 Newborn Baby\n*2007:  ''[[NBA 2K8]]''&nbsp;\u2013 Himself\n*2011: ''[[Beats, Rhymes & Life: The Travels of A Tribe Called Quest]]''&nbsp;\u2013 Himself\n*2017: ''[[NBA 2K18]]''&nbsp;- Himself\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n* {{IMDb name|0205954}}\n* [http://atribecalledquest.com/ Official A Tribe Called Quest website]\n\n{{A Tribe Called Quest}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Phife Dawg}}\n[[Category:1970 births]]\n[[Category:2016 deaths]]\n[[Category:American male rappers]]\n[[Category:Rappers from New York City]]\n[[Category:A Tribe Called Quest members]]\n[[Category:People from St. Albans, Queens]]\n[[Category:Rappers from Atlanta]]\n[[Category:American rappers of Trinidad and Tobago descent]]\n[[Category:East Coast hip hop musicians]]\n[[Category:Deaths from diabetes]]\n[[Category:Kidney transplant recipients]]\n", "name_user": "Jacktinkonea", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Phife_Dawg"}
{"title_page": "Erbsl\u00f6h", "text_new": "{{italic title}}\n[[File:1910 Erbsloh airship jpl.jpg|thumb|The airship ''Erbsl\u00f6h'']]\nThe '''''Erbsl\u00f6h''''' was an [[airship]] named for the [[Germany|German]] aviation pioneer [[Oskar Erbsl\u00f6h]] that was operational in the years 1909/10. In July 1910 the ''Erbsl\u00f6h'' crashed near [[Leverkusen]], killing all five people on board, including Oskar Erbsl\u00f6h himself.\n\n==History==\nThe ''Erbsl\u00f6h'' was a [[blimp]] with a {{convert|27|m|adj=on}} long [[airship#gondola|gondola]] made from [[Fraxinus|ash]]. The trim was regulated by pumping water back and forth between two tanks in the bow and aft section of the ship so that the airship adopted a nose up or nose down attitude.\n\nThe first test flight took place on 20 August 1909. After the airship had been moved out of its [[Airship hangar|hangar]], the manoeuvrability was tested for about one hour at a height of {{convert|100|m}} on the [[Leichlingen]] airship grounds. The official [[maiden flight]] was conducted on 1 December 1909, during which the airship successfully flew across Leichlingen and neighbouring towns.\n\nOn 12 December supporters of the Rheinisch-Westf\u00e4lische Motorluftschiff-Gesellschaft [Rhine-Westphalian Motor Airship Society] participated in a flight. However, a transmission fault forced the ''Erbsl\u00f6h'' to land at Reusrath. When the faulty parts had been repaired, the ''Erbsl\u00f6h'' flew on toward [[M\u00f6nchengladbach]] on the next day. The intermediate stop over there was terminated by a storm which tore the [[airship#envelope|envelope]] from the gondola, necessitating an extensive repairs.\n\n==Crash==\nOn 13 July 1910, a partly cloudy day, the ''Erbsl\u00f6h'' crashed near [[Pattscheid]] (today a quarter of [[Leverkusen]]). The cause that was accepted by the subsequent investigation committee was that a sudden exposure of the envelope to the sun after the ship had been flying under cloud cover and cool morning fog had heated the [[lifting gas]], causing it to expand. The relief valves could not vent the developing excess pressure quickly enough. This allowed [[hydrogen]] to leak from the envelope and come into contact with sparks from the propulsion system, causing the gas to explode.\n\nWitnesses on the ground only heard an explosion: the ship was not visible in the morning fog. The ''Erbsl\u00f6h'' crashed in a field close to Neuenkamp. The front part of the gondola was destroyed, with the torn envelope lying across it. The crew was found dead among the debris. The airship planned to be flown over Leichlingen for only half an hour.\n\nIn addition to [[Oskar Erbsl\u00f6h]], crash fatalities included Max von Toelle, Rudolf Kranz, Hans Leo H\u00f6pp, and mechanic Joseph Spicks. A monument was erected at the \"Oskar-Erbsl\u00f6h-Stra\u00dfe\" [Oskar Erbsl\u00f6h Road] of [[Leichlingen]] in their memory.\n\n==Technical data==\n* Length: {{convert|53.20|m}}\n* Diameter: {{convert|10.50|m}}\n* Volume: {{convert|2900|m3}}\n* Propulsion: 92&nbsp;kW (125&nbsp;hp) engine with 400 rpm, double-winged propeller with a diameter of {{convert|4.55|m}}\n* Maximum speed: {{convert|45|km/h|abbr=on}}\n\n==References==\n* {{cite book|first=Oskar |last=Erbsl\u00f6h |chapter=Die Entwicklung der Luftschiffahrt in Elberfeld in den Jahren 1903 bis 1910 [The Development of airborne shipping in Elberfeld in the years 1903 to 1910] | title=Festschrift zur Dreijahrhundertfeier |publisher= J. H. Born |location=Elberfeld |year=1910 |language=German}}\n* {{cite news|title=Der Absturz des Lenkballons 'Erbsl\u00f6h' [The crash of the airship 'Erbsl\u00f6h'] |work=S\u00fcddeutsche Illustrierte Zeitung |issue= 31 |volume=5|publisher= Otto Weber Verlag |location= Heilbronn |date= 31 July 1910 |pages=483 et seq.|language=German}}\n* {{cite book|first=Ansbert |last=Vorreiter |title=Jahrbuch \u00fcber die Fortschritte auf allen Gebieten der Luftschiffahrt 1911 |publisher= J. F. Lehmann |location=Munich|year= 1910|language=German}}\n* {{citation |mode=cs1 |chapter=Das Platzen der Stoffluftschiffe |trans-chapter=The Bursting of textile Airships |title=Im Reich der L\u00fcfte. Deutschland voran |volume= III |issue= 15 |date=10 August 1910 |publisher= Verlag Emil Pilger Nachf |location= Berlin|language=German}}\n* {{cite news|title=Die Katastrophe von Leichlingen | work=[[Berliner Tageblatt]] |volume= 39 |issue=352 |date= 14 July 1910 |location=Berlin|language=German}}\n* {{cite news|first=Hans Werner |last=Hinrichs |title='Erbsl\u00f6h' explodierte im Morgennebel |work=Westdeutsche Rundschau |location=Wuppertal |date= 8 July 1960|language=German}}\n* {{cite book|first=G. |last=Schmitt |first2=W. |last2=Schwipps |title=Pioniere der fr\u00fchen Luftfahrt |publisher= Gondrom Verlag |location=Blindlach |year=1995 |ISBN=3-8112-1189-7|language=German}}\n* {{cite book|first=Erich |last=Schroeder |title=Oskar Erbsl\u00f6h, ein rheinischer Luftfahrt-Pionier |publisher= Deutscher Aero-Philatelisten Club e.V. |location= Cologne |year= 1997|language=German}}\n* {{cite book|first=Uwe |last=Boelken |title=Rheinische Luftschifffahrtsgeschichte in Leichlingen. Zur Erinnerung an den Absturz des Luftschiffes Erbsl\u00f6h am 13. Juli 1910 |editor=Town of Leichlingen |location= Leichlingen |year=2010 |language=German}}\n* {{cite journal|first=Karl-Hugo |last=Dierichs |title=Der Tod kam aus der Nebelwand. Erbsl\u00f6hs Absturz |journal=Bergische Bl\u00e4tter |volume= 33 |issue= 13 |year= 2010 |pages=7\u20139 |language=German}}\n\n{{coord|51|05|41|N|7|01|09|E|region:DE-NW_type:event_source:dewiki|display=title}}\n\n{{Aviation accidents and incidents before 1920}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Erbsloh}}\n[[Category:1910 in Germany]]\n[[Category:Airships of Germany]]\n[[Category:Accidents and incidents involving balloons and airships]]\n[[Category:Aviation accidents and incidents in Germany]]\n[[Category:Aviation accidents and incidents in 1910]]\n", "text_old": "{{italic title}}\n[[File:1910 Erbsloh airship jpl.jpg|thumb|The airship ''Erbsl\u00f6h'']]\nThe '''''Erbsl\u00f6h''''' was an [[airship]] named for the [[Germany|German]] aviation pioneer [[Oskar Erbsl\u00f6h]] that was operational in the years 1909/10. In July 1910 the ''Erbsl\u00f6h'' crashed near [[Leverkusen]], killing all five people on board, including Oskar Erbsl\u00f6h himself.\n\n==History==\nThe ''Erbsl\u00f6h'' was a [[blimp]] with a {{convert|27|m|adj=on}} long [[airship#gondola|gondola]] made from [[Fraxinus|ash]]. The trim was regulated by pumping water back and forth between two tanks in the bow and aft section of the ship so that the airship adopted a nose up or nose down attitude.\n\nThe first test flight took place on 20 August 1909. After the airship had been moved out of its [[Airship hangar|hangar]], the maneouvrability was tested for about one hour at a height of {{convert|100|m}} on the [[Leichlingen]] airship grounds. The official [[maiden flight]] was conducted on 1 December 1909, during which the airship successfully flew across Leichlingen and neighbouring towns.\n\nOn 12 December supporters of the Rheinisch-Westf\u00e4lische Motorluftschiff-Gesellschaft [Rhine-Westphalian Motor Airship Society] participated in a flight. However, a transmission fault forced the ''Erbsl\u00f6h'' to land at Reusrath. When the faulty parts had been repaired, the ''Erbsl\u00f6h'' flew on toward [[M\u00f6nchengladbach]] on the next day. The intermediate stop over there was terminated by a storm which tore the [[airship#envelope|envelope]] from the gondola, necessitating an extensive repairs.\n\n==Crash==\nOn 13 July 1910, a partly cloudy day, the ''Erbsl\u00f6h'' crashed near [[Pattscheid]] (today a quarter of [[Leverkusen]]). The cause that was accepted by the subsequent investigation committee was that a sudden exposure of the envelope to the sun after the ship had been flying under cloud cover and cool morning fog had heated the [[lifting gas]], causing it to expand. The relief valves could not vent the developing excess pressure quickly enough. This allowed [[hydrogen]] to leak from the envelope and come into contact with sparks from the propulsion system, causing the gas to explode.\n\nWitnesses on the ground only heard an explosion: the ship was not visible in the morning fog. The ''Erbsl\u00f6h'' crashed in a field close to Neuenkamp. The front part of the gondola was destroyed, with the torn envelope lying across it. The crew was found dead among the debris. The airship planned to be flown over Leichlingen for only half an hour.\n\nIn addition to [[Oskar Erbsl\u00f6h]], crash fatalities included Max von Toelle, Rudolf Kranz, Hans Leo H\u00f6pp, and mechanic Joseph Spicks. A monument was erected at the \"Oskar-Erbsl\u00f6h-Stra\u00dfe\" [Oskar Erbsl\u00f6h Road] of [[Leichlingen]] in their memory.\n\n==Technical data==\n* Length: {{convert|53.20|m}}\n* Diameter: {{convert|10.50|m}}\n* Volume: {{convert|2900|m3}}\n* Propulsion: 92&nbsp;kW (125&nbsp;hp) engine with 400 rpm, double-winged propeller with a diameter of {{convert|4.55|m}}\n* Maximum speed: {{convert|45|km/h|abbr=on}}\n\n==References==\n* {{cite book|first=Oskar |last=Erbsl\u00f6h |chapter=Die Entwicklung der Luftschiffahrt in Elberfeld in den Jahren 1903 bis 1910 [The Development of airborne shipping in Elberfeld in the years 1903 to 1910] | title=Festschrift zur Dreijahrhundertfeier |publisher= J. H. Born |location=Elberfeld |year=1910 |language=German}}\n* {{cite news|title=Der Absturz des Lenkballons 'Erbsl\u00f6h' [The crash of the airship 'Erbsl\u00f6h'] |work=S\u00fcddeutsche Illustrierte Zeitung |issue= 31 |volume=5|publisher= Otto Weber Verlag |location= Heilbronn |date= 31 July 1910 |pages=483 et seq.|language=German}}\n* {{cite book|first=Ansbert |last=Vorreiter |title=Jahrbuch \u00fcber die Fortschritte auf allen Gebieten der Luftschiffahrt 1911 |publisher= J. F. Lehmann |location=Munich|year= 1910|language=German}}\n* {{citation |mode=cs1 |chapter=Das Platzen der Stoffluftschiffe |trans-chapter=The Bursting of textile Airships |title=Im Reich der L\u00fcfte. Deutschland voran |volume= III |issue= 15 |date=10 August 1910 |publisher= Verlag Emil Pilger Nachf |location= Berlin|language=German}}\n* {{cite news|title=Die Katastrophe von Leichlingen | work=[[Berliner Tageblatt]] |volume= 39 |issue=352 |date= 14 July 1910 |location=Berlin|language=German}}\n* {{cite news|first=Hans Werner |last=Hinrichs |title='Erbsl\u00f6h' explodierte im Morgennebel |work=Westdeutsche Rundschau |location=Wuppertal |date= 8 July 1960|language=German}}\n* {{cite book|first=G. |last=Schmitt |first2=W. |last2=Schwipps |title=Pioniere der fr\u00fchen Luftfahrt |publisher= Gondrom Verlag |location=Blindlach |year=1995 |ISBN=3-8112-1189-7|language=German}}\n* {{cite book|first=Erich |last=Schroeder |title=Oskar Erbsl\u00f6h, ein rheinischer Luftfahrt-Pionier |publisher= Deutscher Aero-Philatelisten Club e.V. |location= Cologne |year= 1997|language=German}}\n* {{cite book|first=Uwe |last=Boelken |title=Rheinische Luftschifffahrtsgeschichte in Leichlingen. Zur Erinnerung an den Absturz des Luftschiffes Erbsl\u00f6h am 13. Juli 1910 |editor=Town of Leichlingen |location= Leichlingen |year=2010 |language=German}}\n* {{cite journal|first=Karl-Hugo |last=Dierichs |title=Der Tod kam aus der Nebelwand. Erbsl\u00f6hs Absturz |journal=Bergische Bl\u00e4tter |volume= 33 |issue= 13 |year= 2010 |pages=7\u20139 |language=German}}\n\n{{coord|51|05|41|N|7|01|09|E|region:DE-NW_type:event_source:dewiki|display=title}}\n\n{{Aviation accidents and incidents before 1920}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Erbsloh}}\n[[Category:1910 in Germany]]\n[[Category:Airships of Germany]]\n[[Category:Accidents and incidents involving balloons and airships]]\n[[Category:Aviation accidents and incidents in Germany]]\n[[Category:Aviation accidents and incidents in 1910]]\n", "name_user": "Rbstrachan", "label": "safe", "comment": "Fixed typo found by theTypo Team Moss Project- become a member atWP:TYPO", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Erbsl%C3%B6h"}
{"title_page": "Hartfield Academy", "text_new": "{{Infobox school\n| name                    = Hartfield Academy\n| image                   = Hartfield Academy.png\n| motto                   = Learn eagerly, Play skillfully, Live honorably\n| address                 = 1240 Luckney Road\n| city                    = [[Flowood, Mississippi|Flowood]]\n| state                   = [[Mississippi]]\n| zipcode                 = 39232\n| country                 = United States\n| coordinates             = {{Coord|32.3479226|-90.0486955|display=inline,title}}\n| former_names            = University Christian School, Pinelake Christian School\n| type                    = [[Independent school]]\n| religious_affiliation   = [[Christianity]]\n| established             = 2012\n| opened                  = {{Start date and age|2012|08}}\n| principal               = Jim Delaughter\n| principal_label         = High School Principal\n| principal1              = John Bakelaar\n| principal_label1        = Middle School Principal\n| head_of_school          = David Horner\n| grades                  = [[Kindergarten|K3]]\u2013[[Twelfth grade|12th]]\n| gender                  = [[Mixed-sex_education|Coeducational]]\n| campus_type             = [[Suburb|Suburban]]\n| colors                  = Garnet and Gold {{Color box|#97002d}} {{Color box|#bb9b6a}}\n| accreditations          = [[Southern Association of Colleges and Schools|SACS]], [[Mississippi_Association_of_Independent_Schools|MAIS]], [[Association of Christian Schools International|ACSI]], [[Southern Association of Independent Schools|SAIS]]\n| yearbook                = The Legacy\n| website                 = {{URL|www.hartfield.org}}\n}}\n\n'''Hartfield Academy''' (or simply known as '''Hartfield''') is an independent private school in [[Rankin County, Mississippi|Rankin County]], Mississippi.<ref>https://www.privateschoolreview.com/hartfield-academy-profile</ref> The school hosts K3-12th and has two campuses, West and East. Hartfield's main west campus, located in [[Flowood, Mississippi]], is home to grades 3rd\u201312th, and Hartfield's smaller east campus, located in [[Brandon, Mississippi]], is home to grades K3-2nd.\n\n==History==\n===Founding===\nHartfield Academy was formerly known as University Christian School and Pinelake Christian School, a well-known private school in Flowood, Mississippi and a elementary private school in Brandon, Mississippi respectively, which both schools merged together in 2012.<ref>{{cite web |title=Pres. Christian lands Hartfield Aca. coach Dorman |url=https://usatodayhss.com/2014/pres-christian-lands-hartfield-aca-coach-dorman |website=USA TODAY High School Sports |language=en |date=25 March 2014}}</ref> Prior to the founding of the school, the school was originally known as University Christian School, which was also known before as Brandon Academy. Brandon Academy established in July 1970, and in August 1990<ref>{{cite web |title=MPSA 25 Service Awards Nomination Email (2006-2007) |url=http://mailouts.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/toyawd.pdf |accessdate=11 December 2019 |pages=3, 7}}</ref>, the name changed from Brandon Academy to University Christian School.<ref>{{cite web |title=Brandon Academy Football Team History |url=http://www.ahsfhs.org/mississippi/teams/teampage.asp?Team=Brandon%20Academy |website=www.ahsfhs.org |accessdate=11 December 2019}}</ref> The school moved to a new location from Brandon, Mississippi to Flowood, Mississippi. In 2012, University Christian School merged with Pinelake Christian School, founding Hartfield Academy.\n<br><br>\nBefore the school opened its doors, the school went through a transition phase, which the west campus, formerly University Christian School, moved away from its former school identity.<ref>{{cite web |title=Rankin County coaching icon makes his return at Hartfield |url=https://www.wapt.com/article/newly-formed-hartfield-academy-taps-proven-winner/2078175 |website=WAPT |accessdate=4 December 2019 |language=en |date=30 March 2012}}</ref> After a substantial change in identity, Hartfield was open for school in August 2012. The school was renovated to adopt its new identity. The mascot was changed to the 'Hawks' and colors to garnet and gold.\n\n===Major expansion===\nHartfield Academy's main west campus was relatively small. The school administration and its Board of Trustees planned a new 45,000-square foot addition, which cost around $9 million. The school ran a capital campaign Undeniably Different for the expansion efforts, which raised nearly $4.5 million, and the expansion included new interactive classrooms, high school administrative offices, IT Help Center, Thomas W. Colbert Theater, a main plaza, Cockrell Administrative Offices, a redesigned dining hall, new athletic equipment, a basketball practice gym, and three labs. Construction began in the summer 2018 and finished before August 2019. <ref>{{cite web |title=Hartfield Academy opens doors to major expansion |url=https://www.northsidesun.com/news-breaking-news/hartfield-academy-opens-doors-major-expansion |website=The Northside Sun |publisher=The Northside Sun |accessdate=4 December 2019 |language=en |date=15 August 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Hartfield Academy Expansion and Renovation |url=https://www.ccdarchitects.com/portfolio-item/hartfield-academy-renovation/ |website=CANIZARO CAWTHON DAVIS |accessdate=5 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Academics==\nHartfield Academy focuses on the mission and vision that every student \"fulfill their God-given purpose\", and the school exists to help families to prepare their students to purse \"the next stage of life.\" Hartfield holds the five core values: Truth, Excellence, Service, Leadership, and Honor.<ref>{{cite web |title=Mission and Vision |url=https://www.hartfield.org/about-us/mission-and-vision |website=Hartfield.org |accessdate=5 December 2019}}</ref><br>\n\n===Partnership with Belhaven University===\nIn 2016, David Horner, Hartfield Academy's Head of School, and Kevin Russell, [[Belhaven University]]'s Vice President for Enrollment Management and University Marketing, signed an agreement, which Belhaven established a dual-enrollment program with Hartfield and gave eligable Hartfield's students a tutition discount for the university's undergraduate program.<ref>{{cite web |title=Hartfield and Belhaven Partner on Multiple Fronts |url=https://www.belhaven.edu/news/articles/Hartfield-and-Belhaven-Partner-on-Multiple-Fronts-2016-06-02.htm |website=Belhaven.edu |accessdate=5 December 2019 |date=2 June 2016}}</ref> Students as of 2019 can take up 40 hours of dual-enrollment classes before graduation.<ref>{{cite web |title=Why Hartfield |url=https://www.hartfield.org/admissions/why-hartfield |website=Hartfield.org |accessdate=5 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Extracurricular Activities==\n\n===Athletics===\nAs of 2019, Hartfield Academy provides 24 sports team ranging from junior high football to varsity baseball. <ref>{{cite web |title=Athletic Department |url=https://www.hartfield.org/athletics/athletic-department |website=Hartfield.org |accessdate=11 December 2019}}</ref> These sports are run under the athletic department which sports include cheerleading, dance, football, softball, swimming, basketball, soccer, archery, baseball, track and field, cross country golf, and tennis.<ref>{{cite web |title=Sports Teams |url=https://www.hartfield.org/athletics/sports-teams |website=Hartfield.org |accessdate=11 December 2019 |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20191101195629/https://www.hartfield.org/athletics/sports-teams |archivedate=1 November 2019}}</ref> Hartfield Academy competes with member schools of [[Midsouth Association of Independent Schools]].\n\n===Robotics Team===\nHartfield Academy\u2019s robotics team N.E.K.O.S competes in the Mississippi [[FIRST Tech Challenge]] program, which is affiliated with CMSE (Center for Mathematics and Science Education) from the [[University of Mississippi]]. In 2019, the robotics team went to [[FIRST Championship|FIRST Worlds Championship]] in [[Houston, Texas]] during the [[Rover Ruckus|Rover Ruckus competition season]] when the team qualified as one of two Mississippi teams to go.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Coleman |first1=Candance |title=Cool Schools: Hartfield Academy |url=https://www.wjtv.com/news/local-news/cool-schools-hartfield-academy/ |website=WJTV |accessdate=6 December 2019 |date=1 April 2019}}</ref> Hartfield has had hosted local FIRST Tech Challenge robotics qualifiers in the past. As of September 2019, Mississippi FIRST Tech Challenge moved its kickoff event to the school as a new location for future kickoffs.<ref>{{cite web |title=Welcome to SKYSTONE (SM) and the 2019-2020 Mississippi FIRST Tech Challenge Season! |url=https://mailchi.mp/bd53687b4656/2019-20-email-blast-03-kickoff-registration |website=us5.campaign-archive.com |accessdate=6 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n<!-- Inline citations added to your article will automatically display here. See en.wikipedia.org/wiki/WP:REFB for instructions on how to add citations. -->\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Private high schools in Mississippi]]\n[[Category:Private middle schools in Mississippi]]\n[[Category:Private elementary schools in Mississippi]]\n[[Category:Private K-12 schools in Mississippi]]\n[[Category:Private schools in the Jackson metropolitan area, Mississippi]]\n[[Category:Christian schools in Mississippi]]\n[[Category:Schools in Rankin County, Mississippi]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox school\n| name                    = Hartfield Academy\n| image                   = Hartfield Academy.png\n| motto                   = Learn eagerly, Play skillfully, Live honorably\n| address                 = 1240 Luckney Road\n| city                    = [[Flowood, Mississippi|Flowood]]\n| state                   = [[Mississippi]]\n| zipcode                 = 39232\n| country                 = United States\n| coordinates             = {{Coord|32.3479226|-90.0486955|display=inline,title}}\n| former_names            = University Christian School, Pinelake Christian School\n| type                    = [[Independent school]]\n| religious_affiliation   = [[Christianity]]\n| established             = 2012\n| opened                  = {{Start date and age|2012|08}}\n| principal               = Jim Delaughter\n| principal_label         = High School Principal\n| principal1              = John Bakelaar\n| principal_label1        = Middle School Principal\n| head_of_school          = David Horner\n| grades                  = [[Kindergarten|K3]]\u2013[[Twelfth grade|12th]]\n| gender                  = [[Mixed-sex_education|Coeducational]]\n| campus_type             = [[Suburb|Suburban]]\n| colors                  = Garnet and Gold {{Color box|#97002d}} {{Color box|#bb9b6a}}\n| accreditations          = [[Southern Association of Colleges and Schools|SACS]], [[Mississippi_Association_of_Independent_Schools|MAIS]], [[Association of Christian Schools International|ACSI]], [[Southern Association of Independent Schools|SAIS]]\n| yearbook                = The Legacy\n| website                 = {{URL|www.hartfield.org}}\n}}\n\n'''Hartfield Academy''' (or simply known as '''Hartfield''') is an independent private school in [[Rankin County, Mississippi|Rankin County]], Mississippi.<ref>https://www.privateschoolreview.com/hartfield-academy-profile</ref> The school hosts K3-12th and has two campuses, West and East. Hartfield's main west campus, located in [[Flowood, Mississippi]], is home to grades 3rd\u201312th, and Hartfield's smaller east campus, located in [[Brandon, Mississippi]], is home to grades K3-2nd.\n\n==History==\n===Founding===\nHartfield Academy was formerly known as University Christian School and Pinelake Christian School, a well-known private school in Flowood, Mississippi and a elementary private school in Brandon, Mississippi respectively, which both schools merged together in 2012.<ref>{{cite web |title=Pres. Christian lands Hartfield Aca. coach Dorman |url=https://usatodayhss.com/2014/pres-christian-lands-hartfield-aca-coach-dorman |website=USA TODAY High School Sports |language=en |date=25 March 2014}}</ref> Prior to the founding of the school, the school was originally known as University Christian School, which was also known before as Brandon Academy. Brandon Academy established in July 1970, and in August 1990<ref>{{cite web |title=MPSA 25 Service Awards Nomination Email (2006-2007) |url=http://mailouts.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/toyawd.pdf |accessdate=11 December 2019 |pages=3, 7}}</ref>, the name changed from Brandon Academy to University Christian School.<ref>{{cite web |title=Brandon Academy Football Team History |url=http://www.ahsfhs.org/mississippi/teams/teampage.asp?Team=Brandon%20Academy |website=www.ahsfhs.org |accessdate=11 December 2019}}</ref> The school moved to a new location from Brandon, Mississippi to Flowood, Mississippi. In 2012, University Christian School merged with Pinelake Christian School, founding Hartfield Academy.\n<br><br>\nBefore the school opened its doors, the school went through a transition phase, which the west campus, formerly University Christian School, moved away from its former school identity.<ref>{{cite web |title=Rankin County coaching icon makes his return at Hartfield |url=https://www.wapt.com/article/newly-formed-hartfield-academy-taps-proven-winner/2078175 |website=WAPT |accessdate=4 December 2019 |language=en |date=30 March 2012}}</ref> After a substantial change in identity, Hartfield was open for school in August 2012. The school was renovated to adopt its new identity. The mascot was changed to the 'Hawks' and colors to garnet and gold.\n\n===Major expansion===\nHartfield Academy's main west campus was relatively small. The school administration and its Board of Trustees planned a new 45,000-square foot addition, which cost around $9 million. The school ran a capital campaign Undeniably Different for the expansion efforts, which raised nearly $4.5 million, and the expansion included new interactive classrooms, high school administrative offices, IT Help Center, Thomas W. Colbert Theater, a main plaza, Cockrell Administrative Offices, a redesigned dining hall, new athletic equipment, a basketball practice gym, and three labs. Construction began in the summer 2018 and finished before August 2019. <ref>{{cite web |title=Hartfield Academy opens doors to major expansion |url=https://www.northsidesun.com/news-breaking-news/hartfield-academy-opens-doors-major-expansion |website=The Northside Sun |publisher=The Northside Sun |accessdate=4 December 2019 |language=en |date=15 August 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Hartfield Academy Expansion and Renovation |url=https://www.ccdarchitects.com/portfolio-item/hartfield-academy-renovation/ |website=CANIZARO CAWTHON DAVIS |accessdate=5 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Academics==\nHartfield Academy focuses on the mission and vision that every student \"fulfill their God-given purpose\", and the school exists to help families to prepare their students to purse \"the next stage of life.\" Hartfield holds the five core values: Truth, Excellence, Service, Leadership, and Honor.<ref>{{cite web |title=Mission and Vision |url=https://www.hartfield.org/about-us/mission-and-vision |website=Hartfield.org |accessdate=5 December 2019}}</ref><br>\n\n===Partnership with Belhaven University===\nIn 2016, David Horner, Hartfield Academy's Head of School, and Kevin Russell, [[Belhaven University]]'s Vice President for Enrollment Management and University Marketing, signed an agreement, which Belhaven established a dual-enrollment program with Hartfield and gave eligable Hartfield's students a tutition discount for the university's undergraduate program.<ref>{{cite web |title=Hartfield and Belhaven Partner on Multiple Fronts |url=https://www.belhaven.edu/news/articles/Hartfield-and-Belhaven-Partner-on-Multiple-Fronts-2016-06-02.htm |website=Belhaven.edu |accessdate=5 December 2019 |date=2 June 2016}}</ref> Students as of 2019 can take up 40 hours of dual-enrollment classes before graduation.<ref>{{cite web |title=Why Hartfield |url=https://www.hartfield.org/admissions/why-hartfield |website=Hartfield.org |accessdate=5 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Extracurricular Activities==\n\n===Athletics===\nAs of 2019, Hartfield Academy provides 24 sports team ranging from junior high football to varsity baseball. <ref>{{cite web |title=Athletic Department |url=https://www.hartfield.org/athletics/athletic-department |website=Hartfield.org |accessdate=11 December 2019}}</ref> These sports are run under the athletic department which sports include cheerleading, dance, football, softball, swimming, basketball, soccer, archery, baseball, track and field, cross country golf, and tennis.<ref>{{cite web |title=Sports Teams |url=https://www.hartfield.org/athletics/sports-teams |website=Hartfield.org |accessdate=11 December 2019 |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20191101195629/https://www.hartfield.org/athletics/sports-teams |archivedate=1 November 2019}}</ref> Hartfield Academy competes with member schools of [[Midsouth Association of Independent_Schools]].\n\n===Robotics Team===\nHartfield Academy\u2019s robotics team N.E.K.O.S competes in the Mississippi [[FIRST Tech Challenge]] program, which is affiliated with CMSE (Center for Mathematics and Science Education) from the [[University of Mississippi]]. In 2019, the robotics team went to [[FIRST Championship|FIRST Worlds Championship]] in [[Houston, Texas]] during the [[Rover Ruckus|Rover Ruckus competition season]] when the team qualified as one of two Mississippi teams to go.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Coleman |first1=Candance |title=Cool Schools: Hartfield Academy |url=https://www.wjtv.com/news/local-news/cool-schools-hartfield-academy/ |website=WJTV |accessdate=6 December 2019 |date=1 April 2019}}</ref> Hartfield has had hosted local FIRST Tech Challenge robotics qualifiers in the past. As of September 2019, Mississippi FIRST Tech Challenge moved its kickoff event to the school as a new location for future kickoffs.<ref>{{cite web |title=Welcome to SKYSTONE (SM) and the 2019-2020 Mississippi FIRST Tech Challenge Season! |url=https://mailchi.mp/bd53687b4656/2019-20-email-blast-03-kickoff-registration |website=us5.campaign-archive.com |accessdate=6 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n<!-- Inline citations added to your article will automatically display here. See en.wikipedia.org/wiki/WP:REFB for instructions on how to add citations. -->\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Private high schools in Mississippi]]\n[[Category:Private middle schools in Mississippi]]\n[[Category:Private elementary schools in Mississippi]]\n[[Category:Private K-12 schools in Mississippi]]\n[[Category:Private schools in the Jackson metropolitan area, Mississippi]]\n[[Category:Christian schools in Mississippi]]\n[[Category:Schools in Rankin County, Mississippi]]\n", "name_user": "Billhpike", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eAthletics:CE", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hartfield_Academy"}
{"title_page": "Notre Dame de Namur University", "text_new": "{{about||Notre-Dame de la Paix University Faculties in Namur, Belgium|University of Namur}}\n{{coord|37.51729|-122.28443|format=dms|display=title}}\n{{Infobox university\n|name            = Notre Dame de Namur University\n|image_name      = Notre_Dame_de_Namur_University_logo.jpg\n|image_size      = 200px\n|motto           = [[Ora et labora|Ora et Labora]] ([[Latin]])\n|mottoeng        = Pray and Work\n|established     = 1851\n|type            = Private\n|religious_affiliation     = [[Roman Catholic]] ([[Sisters of Notre Dame de Namur]])\n|faculty         = 122 FTE\n|president       = Daniel J. Carey (interim)\n|students        = 1,492 (fall 2018)<ref name=about>{{cite web |url=http://www.ndnu.edu/about-us/fast-facts/ |title=Notre Dame de Namur University - Fast Facts |publisher=Notre Dame de Namur University |accessdate=April 11, 2019 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130320052030/http://www.ndnu.edu/about-us/fast-facts/ |archivedate=March 20, 2013 }}</ref>\n|undergrad       = 871 (fall 2018)\n|postgrad        = 621 (fall 2018)\n|city            = [[Belmont, California|Belmont]]\n|state           = [[California]]\n|country         = United States\n|former_names    = College of Notre Dame\n|campus          = Suburban ({{convert|50|acre|disp=or|abbr=on}})\n|colors          = Blue, Gold, White\n|nickname        = \n|mascot          = [[Argonauts|Argonaut]]\n|athletics       = \n|sports          =\n|affiliations    = [[Association of Catholic Colleges and Universities|ACCU]], AICCU<ref>https://www.aiccu.edu/member-colleges/</ref>\n|website         = [http://www.ndnu.edu/ www.ndnu.edu]\n|address         =\n|telephone       =\n|logo            = [[File:Notre Dame de Namur Argonauts logo.svg|150px|Argonauts athletics logo]]\n}}\n\n'''Notre Dame de Namur University''' ('''NDNU''')  is a [[private university|private]] [[Catholicism|Catholic]] university in [[Belmont, California]]. It is the third oldest college in [[California]] and the first college in the state authorized to grant the [[baccalaureate degree]] to women.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ndnu.edu/about-us/history/ |title=Notre Dame de Namur University - History |publisher=Notre Dame de Namur University |accessdate=March 19, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130327123243/http://www.ndnu.edu/about%2Dus/history/ |archivedate=March 27, 2013 }}</ref> The university will be closing at the conclusion of the spring 21\u2019 semester [https://www.ndnu.edu/future-of-ndnu/]\n\nThe university is organized into three schools: the College of Arts and Sciences, the School of Business and Management, and the School of Education and Leadership. Notre Dame de Namur University offers 15 [[undergraduate degree]]s, 10 [[graduate degree]]s and four [[teaching credential|credentials]]. In addition to traditional undergraduate and graduate programs, the university offers an evening bachelor's degree completion program for working adults as well as online degree programs.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ndnu.edu/academics/|title=Academics - Notre Dame de Namur University|website=Ndnu.edu|accessdate=24 October 2017}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nNotre Dame de Namur University was founded by the [[Sisters of Notre Dame de Namur]] as the Academy of Notre Dame in 1851 on 10 acres<ref>{{cite book |title=Where to educate, 1898-1899. A guide to the best private schools, higher institutions of learning, etc., in the United States |last=Thomas |first=Grace Powers |year=1898 |publisher=Brown and Company |location=Boston |page=17 |accessdate=August 17, 2012 |url=https://archive.org/stream/wheretoeducate1800thomrich#page/17/mode/1up}}</ref> in [[San Jose, California]]. The school was chartered in 1868 as the College of Notre Dame, the first college in the state of [[California]] authorized to grant the [[baccalaureate degree]] to women. In 1922, the [[Religious sisters|Sisters]] purchased [[Ralston Hall]], the country estate of [[William Chapman Ralston]], founder of the [[Bank of California]]. The college opened its doors in [[Belmont, California|Belmont]] in 1923.\n\nIn 1953 the College of Notre Dame became a four-year college with 23 Sisters of Notre Dame de Namur<ref name=\"snddenca.org\">{{cite web |url=http://www.snddenca.org/wp-content/uploads/2013/04/Final-1950-timeline_WEB.jpg |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2014-04-21 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140422233236/http://www.snddenca.org/wp-content/uploads/2013/04/Final-1950-timeline_WEB.jpg |archivedate=2014-04-22 }}</ref> involved in the school. The college introduced evening classes in 1955, and in 1965, started the [[teaching credential]] programs. Originally a women's institution, College of Notre Dame became [[Mixed-sex education|coeducational]] in 1969;<ref name=\"snddenca.org\"/> three men graduated as part of the class of 1970. The college expanded its offerings to include master's degrees in 1972 and added evening undergraduate programs in 1987.\n\nIn 2001, the college established a structure dividing the university into schools. The name of the institution was changed to Notre Dame de Namur University that same year. In 2009, the university began offering partnerships with local community colleges to provide greater access to higher education, and that same year it became a Hispanic-Serving Institution, meaning at least 25% of its undergraduate population is Hispanic, that same year. The online degree program was established in 2012, and in 2013, the university introduced one of the first PhD programs in art therapy in the nation. The university established a new campus in Tracy, California in 2015, offering evening undergraduate and graduate degree programs in business administration.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ndnu.edu/about-us/ndnu-history.aspx |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2012-03-20 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120403073458/http://www.ndnu.edu/about-us/ndnu-history.aspx |archivedate=2012-04-03 }}</ref>\n\nLaunched in 2013, Notre Dame de Namur University was one of the first universities in the United States to offer a Ph.D. in [[Art Therapy]]. The Art Therapy Ph.D. is also the first doctoral program offered at the university.\n\nIn 2016 the faculty, both full-time and adjunct, unionized with SEIU 1021. This was a historic move since tenure-line professors at Catholic universities have had trouble unionizing since the [https://www.aaup.org/import-tags/yeshiva-ruling Yeshiva ruling] (1980).<ref>https://www.insidehighered.com/quicktakes/2016/06/01/notre-dame-de-namur-recognizes-tenured-faculty-union</ref>\n\nIn December 2017, BINA48 (a [[Hanson Robotics]] robot) successfully participated as a guest student in a full semester college course on philosophy and love created and taught by Professor William J. Barry at Notre Dame de Namur University. The robot used an algorithm framework called TQ Theory created by Professor Barry to interact with rapport with students.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2017/12/21/meet-the-robot-that-passed-a-college-class-on-philosophy-and-love.html|title=Meet the robot that passed a college class on philosophy and love|last=Hess|first=Abigail|date=2017-12-21|work=CNBC|access-date=2018-01-04}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2020, the university announced major changes as a result of on-going financial issues, declining enrollment, and effects of the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]].<ref name=\"Future2020\">{{cite web |title=The Future of Notre Dame de Namur University |url=https://www.ndnu.edu/future-of-ndnu/ |publisher=Notre Dame de Namur University |date=March 23, 2020 |accessdate=1 April 2020}}</ref> The Board of Trustees made the decision to prioritize current students completing degrees by the end of the 2020\u201321 academic year while assisting other students in transfer options due to uncertainly of operations beyond the spring 2021 semester. As part of the plan, Notre Dame suspended new student admissions for summer and fall 2020 sessions.<ref name=\"Future2020\"/> The university also disbanded the athletics department at the conclusion of the 2019\u201320 academic year.<ref name=\"Future2020\"/><ref name=\"athdisband\">{{cite news |url=https://ndnuargos.com/news/2020/3/23/general-ndnu-athletics-will-not-continue-past-spring-2020.aspx |title=NDNU Athletics Will Not Continue Past Spring 2020 |accessdate=March 27, 2020 |work=ndnuargos.com |date=March 23, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Campus==\n\nNotre Dame de Namur University is located in [[Belmont, California]] on the [[San Francisco Peninsula|San Francisco Bay Area Peninsula]]  and near the [[Pacific Ocean]]. The campus is less than 30 miles from downtown [[San Francisco, California|San Francisco]] and downtown [[San Jose, California|San Jose]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ndnu.edu/visitors/location/ |title=Our Location {{!}} NDNU |accessdate=13 August 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Residence halls===\n\nNotre Dame de Namur University offers [[Dormitory|traditional dorm living]] in Julie Billiart Hall and St. Joseph's Hall, which are named for the co-foundresses of the Sisters of Notre Dame, Sister [[Julie Billiart]] and Sister [[Fran\u00e7oise Blin de Bourdon|St. Joseph Blin de Bourdon]]. The Carroll, Kane, and Wilkie Apartments are available for upperclassmen.  Students also have the option of suite living in New Hall, where suites feature four rooms joined by a common area and sharing a bathroom.  Residence hall floors are [[Mixed-sex education|co-ed]].<ref name=\"Named Buildings 2011\">''Named Buildings.'' Notre Dame de Namur University, 2011.</ref> Saint Joseph's hall has now been transformed into faculty offices and also contains a lounge and the Housing Office.\n\n===Academic buildings===\n\n[[Cuvilly]] Hall, named for Sr. Julie Billiart's birthplace, is one of the main instructional buildings and houses the School of Business and Management. [[Mary (mother of Jesus)|St. Mary's]] Hall is the largest instructional building and includes classrooms; science labs; two computer labs; public safety; and the financial aid, [[Registrar (education)|registrar]], and business offices. Gavin Hall is the smallest of the three main instructional buildings and houses the Art Therapy program.<ref name=\"Named Buildings 2011\"/>\n\nThe theater of Notre Dame de Namur University is located below the main campus on Ralston Avenue.\n\n===Ralston Hall Mansion===\n[[File:Ralston hall.JPG|thumb|250px|right|Ralston Hall]]\nThe Notre Dame de Namur University campus developed around [[Ralston Hall]] Mansion. William Chapman Ralston built Ralston Hall shortly after purchasing the property in 1864.<ref>\"Ralston Hall Mansion | A Celebrated History.\" Ralston Hall Mansion | A Celebrated History. Ralston Hall Mansion, 2013. Web. 27 Sept. 2013</ref>  William Ralston was a pivotal figure in the gold and silver bonanzas, which helped Ralston amass wealth.  Ralston Hall was built with a steamboat gothic design on the interior, which is rumored to have been influenced by Ralston's love of boating from a young age.<ref name=\"A Celebrated History 2013\">\"Ralston Hall Mansion | A Celebrated History.\" Ralston Hall Mansion | A Celebrated History. Ralston Hall Mansion, 2013. Web. 27 Sept. 2013.</ref> The interior of Ralston Hall is strikingly shaped like the inside of a boat.<ref name=\"A Celebrated History 2013\"/> Ralston Hall was built as an entertainment destination.<ref name=\"A Celebrated History 2013\"/> After William Ralston died, his business partner, [[William Sharon]], came to control the mansion.<ref name=\"A Celebrated History 2013\"/> Sharon was a [[United States Senator]] representing [[Nevada]] from 1875 to 1881.<ref name=\"A Celebrated History 2013\"/>  Ralston Hall has been used for a variety of jobs throughout its history; Ralston Hall held one of the largest American weddings when William Sharon's daughter Flora married Sir Thomas Fermor-Hesketh of England.<ref name=\"A Celebrated History 2013\"/> Notre Dame De Namur was chartered by the State of California in 1868 but was not affiliated with Ralston Hall until 1922.<ref name=\"A Celebrated History 2013\"/>  The mansion was a finishing school for young women until 1898.<ref name=\"Historic Architecture Campus Project 2013\">\"Historic Architecture Campus Project.\" Historic Colleges. N.p., Jan. 2013. Web. 16 Sept. 2013.</ref>  Since 1923 Ralston Hall has been affiliated with Notre Dame de Namur University.<ref name=\"Historic Architecture Campus Project 2013\"/>\n\nUntil April 2012, the mansion housed admissions, administrative and faculty offices, and its first floor rooms, including a [[ballroom]] modeled after the [[Hall of Mirrors (Palace of Versailles)|Hall of Mirrors at Versailles]], were rented for events. However, in late 2011, a preliminary assessment of the structural integrity of Ralston Hall suggested that occupants may not be safe in the event of an earthquake. The building is unoccupied indefinitely, until funds can be raised to complete a replacement or retrofit of the masonry foundation, in addition to extensive seismic work on the upper floors.  The renovation is estimated to cost more than $20 million <ref>{{cite web|title=Ralston Hall fixes get another look|url=https://www.smdailyjournal.com/news/local/ralston-hall-fixes-get-another-look/article_dd5c1b7e-d973-11e7-83a5-839d6fc28572.html|accessdate=24 January 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Satellite programs===\nNotre Dame de Namur University offers some bachelor's degree programs in partnership with local [[community college]] campuses. Adult students who have completed enough units to enter Notre Dame de Namur University's evening bachelor's program can take the remaining classes for their bachelor's degree on the community college campus and receive a degree from NDNU. The university established a partnership with [[Mission College (Santa Clara, California)|Mission College]] in [[Santa Clara, California]] in 2008 and offers a human services and a business degree on the community college campus.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ndnu.edu/public-relations/ndnu-news/newsMissionCollegePartnership.aspx |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2012-03-20 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111211042536/http://www.ndnu.edu/public-relations/ndnu-news/newsMissionCollegePartnership.aspx |archivedate=2011-12-11 }}</ref> A human services program was established with [[Ca\u00f1ada College]] in [[Redwood City, California]] in 2009.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ndnu.edu/public-relations/ndnu-news/newsCanada.aspx |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2012-03-20 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111211014342/http://www.ndnu.edu/public-relations/ndnu-news/newsCanada.aspx |archivedate=2011-12-11 }}</ref> In 2010, evening business <ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ndnu.edu/public-relations/ndnu-news/newsCanadaBus.aspx |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2012-03-20 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111211012047/http://www.ndnu.edu/public-relations/ndnu-news/newsCanadaBus.aspx |archivedate=2011-12-11 }}</ref> and psychology degrees were added to the partnership with Ca\u00f1ada College.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ndnu.edu/public-relations/ndnu-news/newsCanadaPsych.aspx |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2012-03-20 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111211012427/http://www.ndnu.edu/public-relations/ndnu-news/newsCanadaPsych.aspx |archivedate=2011-12-11 }}</ref>\n\nIn 2015, the university launched a satellite campus in Tracy, California. The NDNU Tracy campus offers undergraduate and graduate degree programs in business administration, a bachelor's in human services, as well as teaching credentials. The classes are held in the evening in an accelerated format.<ref>{{cite web |title=Admissions--NDNU Tracy campus website.|url=http://tracy.ndnu.edu/admissions//|website=Ndnu.edu|accessdate=24 January 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Organization and administration==\nNotre Dame de Namur University is a [[nonprofit organization]] governed by a [[Board of directors|Board of Trustees]].\n\nUniversity administration consists of a [[University president|president]], a [[Provost (education)|provost]], [[vice president]]s for enrollment management, advancement, and finance and administration, a [[Dean (education)|dean]] of students, and deans of the three schools.\n\nThe university is organized into three schools: the College of Arts and Sciences, the School of Business and Management, and the School of Education and Psychology. Each school is led by a dean.\n\n===Student Assembly===\n\nThe Student Assembly is the official [[Student government|student governing body]] of the university. The purpose of the Student Assembly Leadership Team (SALT) is to represent and to provide for the general welfare of the student body and the university. The leadership consists of a president, vice presidents for communications and finance, and two senators from each school.<ref>https://www.ndnu.edu/campus-life/clubs-activities/student-assembly/</ref>\n\n==Academics==\n\nNotre Dame de Namur University is a [[Liberal arts college|liberal arts institution]] offering bachelor's and master's degrees, a doctoral degree in Art Therapy, and teaching credentials. In addition to the degrees offered on the campus, several programs are available 100% online: bachelor's in Criminal Justice, Master of Arts in Teaching English to Speakers of Other Languages (TESOL), a Master of Science in Business Administration, and Master of Public Administration.\n\nNotre Dame de Namur University is currently ranked by U.S. News & World Report among the Best Regional Universities West and Best Value Schools.<ref>https://www.usnews.com/best-colleges/notre-dame-de-namur-university-1179</ref>\n\n===Community-based learning===\nAs part of the university's mission of social justice and the goal of equipping students with \"what they need to know for life,\" Notre Dame de Namur University offers over 20 community-based learning (CBL) courses, designed to promote learning through [[community engagement]]. These courses involve partnerships within the community, and work for an outcome of affecting positive social change. Many of the academic programs at Notre Dame de Namur University offer CBL courses, including [[psychology]], religious studies, [[sociology]], accounting, [[biological sciences]], [[communications]], [[natural science]], and [[music]]. NDNU has received the Carnegie Foundation's Elective Community Engagement Classification.<ref>http://nerche.org/images/stories/projects/Carnegie/2015/2010_and_2015_CE_Classified_Institutions_revised_8_10_16.pdf</ref>\n\n===Accreditation===\nNotre Dame de Namur University is accredited by the [[Western Association of Schools and Colleges]] (WASC), Senior College and University Commission. Accredited or approved programs at Notre Dame de Namur University include:\n*Education Credentials: [[California Commission on Teacher Credentialing]]\n*Art Therapy: [[American Art Therapy Association]]\n*Marriage and Family Therapy: meets established guidelines of the California Board of Behavioral Sciences\n*Clinical Psychology/MFT: meets established guidelines of the California Board of Behavioral Sciences\n*Business: [[Accreditation Council for Business Schools and Programs]]\n\n== Sister Dorothy Stang Center ==\nThe Sister Dorothy Stang Center for Social Justice and Community Engagement (DSC) was established on the Notre Dame de Namur University campus in honor of the work of [[Dorothy Stang|Sister Dorothy Stang, SNDdeN]], who was murdered in [[Brazil]] due to her efforts to aid the poor farmers and the environment in that country. The Center works to increase awareness of [[social justice|social]] and [[environmental justice]] issues, as well as encourage dialogue, community service, engagement, and activism in these areas. Members of the university and the larger community can work with the DSC to create positive social change, and come to a greater understanding of the issues that affect the community.\n\n== Athletics ==\nThe Notre Dame de Namur University [[Argonauts]] were the athletic teams of the university until 2020. The university mascot, the Argonaut, is named for the mythical [[Argonauts]] who sailed with Jason in search of the Golden Fleece. The team colors blue, gold and white reflected the colors of the university. The university most recently competed at the [[National Collegiate Athletic Association|National Collegiate Athletic Association (NCAA)]] [[NCAA Division II|Division II]] level as members of the [[Pacific West Conference]], except for men's lacrosse, which has an [[NCAA Division II independent schools|Independent]] affiliation after leaving the [[Western Intercollegiate Lacrosse Association]] at the end of the 2014 season.<ref name=\"athdisband\"/> In March 2020, the university announced the discontinuation of the athletics programs effective at the conclusion of the Spring 2020 semester. The decision was part of various changes to the university, citing an on-going financial situation and declining enrollment.<ref name=\"athdisband\"/> At the time of the discontinuation, NDNU had 12 varsity sports. Men's sports included [[College basketball|basketball]], [[Cross country running|cross country]], [[golf]], [[College lacrosse|lacrosse]], [[College soccer|soccer]], and [[track and field]] while women's sports included basketball, cross country, soccer, [[College softball|softball]], [[Intercollegiate Tennis Association|tennis]], track and field, and [[volleyball]].<ref name=\"athdisband\"/>\n\nNotre Dame athletics competed in the Division II [[Northern California Athletic Conference]] (NCAC) until 1997 when the conference disbanded. NDNU joined the [[National Association of Intercollegiate Athletics]] (NAIA) and the [[California Pacific Conference]] (Cal Pac).<ref name=\"grassroots\">{{cite news |last1=Kroichick |first1=Ron |title=A place where college sports are a grassroots movement |url=https://www.sfgate.com/bayarea/article/A-place-where-college-sports-are-a-grassroots-3229843.php |accessdate=1 April 2020 |publisher=SFGate |date=January 23, 2008}}</ref> The university rejoined the NCAA in 2005 when the Pacific West Conference voted to admit Notre Dame de Namur University.<ref name=\"grassroots\"/>\n\n== Diversity ==\n\nNotre Dame de Namur University is one of the most diverse private colleges in California, qualifying as both a Hispanic Serving Institution (HSI) and an Asian American Native American Pacific Islander Serving Institution (AANAPISI).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ndnu.edu/about/diversity/|title=Commitment to Diversity - Notre Dame de Namur University|website=Ndnu.edu|accessdate=24 January 2018}}</ref> The university's commitment to diversity is based on the Hallmarks of a Notre Dame de Namur Learning Community, which states, \"We embrace the gift of diversity.\" <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ndnu.edu/about/mission-strategy/hallmarks-of-a-notre-dame-de-namur-learning-community/|title=Hallmarks of a Notre Dame de Namur Learning Community - Notre Dame de Namur University|website=Ndnu.edu|accessdate=24 January 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Notable alumni==\n*[[Maria Cristina Villanova de Arbenz]], politician,  [[First Lady of Guatemala]].\n*[[Lailee Bakhtiar]], poet, journalist, author, novelist\n*[[Eddie Baza Calvo]], politician, Governor of Guam\n*[[Belo Cipriani]], blind and Latino writer and LGBT activist \n*[[Simon Enciso]], professional athlete in basketball<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20160820190604/http://www.smdailyjournal.com/articles/sports/2015-08-25/simon-enciso-taken-in-2nd-round-of-pba-draft/1776425149034.html]</ref>\n*[[Abigail Campbell Kaw\u0101nanakoa]], politician and Princess of Hawaii\n*[[Morghan King]], Olympic athlete in weightlifting<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ndnuargos.com/news/2016/6/3/womens-soccer-former-ndnu-soccer-player-morghan-king-secures-olympics-trip-in-weightlifting.aspx|title=Former NDNU Soccer Player Morghan King Secures Olympics Trip in Weightlifting|website=Notre Dame de Namur University|accessdate=24 October 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nbcolympics.com/news/who-morghan-king|title=Who is \u2026 Morghan King?|website=Nbcolympics.com|accessdate=24 October 2017}}</ref>\n*[[Matthew Mbu Junior]], politician, Senator of Federal Republic of Nigeria\n*Myles McCormick, former CEO of Bare Escentuals, currently an Advisory Director for Berkshire Partners<ref>{{cite web|title=Myles McCormick {{!}} LinkedIn|url=http://www.linkedin.com/pub/myles-mccormick/33/618/a17|accessdate=8 January 2013}}</ref> \n*[[Barbara Morgan]], NASA Astronaut\n*[[Susan Heon]] Preston, Olympic athlete in swimming<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.edmodo.com/spreston84|title=Edmodo|website=Edmodo|accessdate=24 October 2017}}</ref>\n*[[Santino Reynolds]], collegiate basketball coach at [[Fresno Pacific University]] in [[Fresno]], [[California]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Santino Reynolds|url=https://www.fpuathletics.com/sports/womens-basketball/roster/coaches/santino-reynolds/1100|website=Fresno Pacific University Athletics|accessdate=23 March 2020}}</ref>\n*[[Anton del Rosario]], professional athlete in soccer<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.abs-cbn.com/sports/06/25/11/azkals-close-anton-del-rosario|title=Azkals up close: Anton del Rosario|author=Barry Viloria|website=News.abs-cbn.com|accessdate=24 October 2017}}</ref>\n*[[Dorothy Stang]], class of 1964<ref>[https://archive.is/20130415224303/http://web.sndden.org/dev/triprov/DorothyStang.htm]</ref> - activist, Sister of Notre Dame de Namur\n*Phillip Walker, CEO, Network Solutions Provider, named to list of Top 10 Black Entrepreneurs by Inc. Magazine<ref>{{cite web|title=NDNU {{!}} Alumni {{!}} Alumni Stories|url=http://www.ndnu.edu/alumni/stories.aspx|accessdate=20 July 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=The 2011 INC. 5000 Top 10 Black Entrepreneurs {{!}} Inc.com|url=http://www.inc.com/ss/2011-inc-5000-top-10-black-entrepreneurs#5|accessdate=20 July 2012}}</ref>\n*[[Susie Wind]], M.A. 1997 in Art Therapy \u2014 visual artist \n*[[Emily Wu]], author, novelist\n*[[Wang Yi (volleyball)|Wang Yi]], Olympic athlete in volleyball<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gocolumbialions.com/ViewArticle.dbml?DB_OEM_ID=9600&ATCLID=1515143|title=Yi Wang|website=Gocolumbialions.com|accessdate=24 October 2017}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|http://www.ndnu.edu/}}\n*[http://www.ndnuargos.com/ Official athletics website]\n\n{{Women's Colleges that are Coeducational}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Notre Dame de Namur University}}\n[[Category:Notre Dame de Namur University]]\n[[Category:Universities and colleges in San Mateo County, California]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1851]]\n[[Category:Sisters of Notre Dame de Namur colleges and universities]]\n[[Category:California Historical Landmarks]]\n[[Category:School buildings on the National Register of Historic Places in California]]\n[[Category:National Register of Historic Places in the San Francisco Bay Area]]\n[[Category:Schools accredited by the Western Association of Schools and Colleges]]\n[[Category:Catholic universities and colleges in California]]\n[[Category:Association of Catholic Colleges and Universities]]\n[[Category:Former women's universities and colleges in the United States]]\n[[Category:1851 establishments in California]]\n", "text_old": "{{about||Notre-Dame de la Paix University Faculties in Namur, Belgium|University of Namur}}\n{{coord|37.51729|-122.28443|format=dms|display=title}}\n{{Infobox university\n|name            = Notre Dame de Namur University\n|image_name      = Notre_Dame_de_Namur_University_logo.jpg\n|image_size      = 200px\n|motto           = [[Ora et labora|Ora et Labora]] ([[Latin]])\n|mottoeng        = Pray and Work\n|established     = 1851\n|type            = Private\n|religious_affiliation     = [[Roman Catholic]] ([[Sisters of Notre Dame de Namur]])\n|faculty         = 122 FTE\n|president       = Daniel J. Carey (interim)\n|students        = 1,492 (fall 2018)<ref name=about>{{cite web |url=http://www.ndnu.edu/about-us/fast-facts/ |title=Notre Dame de Namur University - Fast Facts |publisher=Notre Dame de Namur University |accessdate=April 11, 2019 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130320052030/http://www.ndnu.edu/about-us/fast-facts/ |archivedate=March 20, 2013 }}</ref>\n|undergrad       = 871 (fall 2018)\n|postgrad        = 621 (fall 2018)\n|city            = [[Belmont, California|Belmont]]\n|state           = [[California]]\n|country         = United States\n|former_names    = College of Notre Dame\n|campus          = Suburban ({{convert|50|acre|disp=or|abbr=on}})\n|colors          = Blue, Gold, White\n|nickname        = \n|mascot          = [[Argonauts|Argonaut]]\n|athletics       = \n|sports          =\n|affiliations    = [[Association of Catholic Colleges and Universities|ACCU]], AICCU<ref>https://www.aiccu.edu/member-colleges/</ref>\n|website         = [http://www.ndnu.edu/ www.ndnu.edu]\n|address         =\n|telephone       =\n|logo            = [[File:Notre Dame de Namur Argonauts logo.svg|150px|Argonauts athletics logo]]\n}}\n\n'''Notre Dame de Namur University''' ('''NDNU''')  is a [[private university|private]] [[Catholicism|Catholic]] university in [[Belmont, California]]. It is the third oldest college in [[California]] and the first college in the state authorized to grant the [[baccalaureate degree]] to women.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ndnu.edu/about-us/history/ |title=Notre Dame de Namur University - History |publisher=Notre Dame de Namur University |accessdate=March 19, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130327123243/http://www.ndnu.edu/about%2Dus/history/ |archivedate=March 27, 2013 }}</ref>\n\nThe university is organized into three schools: the College of Arts and Sciences, the School of Business and Management, and the School of Education and Leadership. Notre Dame de Namur University offers 15 [[undergraduate degree]]s, 10 [[graduate degree]]s and four [[teaching credential|credentials]]. In addition to traditional undergraduate and graduate programs, the university offers an evening bachelor's degree completion program for working adults as well as online degree programs.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ndnu.edu/academics/|title=Academics - Notre Dame de Namur University|website=Ndnu.edu|accessdate=24 October 2017}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nNotre Dame de Namur University was founded by the [[Sisters of Notre Dame de Namur]] as the Academy of Notre Dame in 1851 on 10 acres<ref>{{cite book |title=Where to educate, 1898-1899. A guide to the best private schools, higher institutions of learning, etc., in the United States |last=Thomas |first=Grace Powers |year=1898 |publisher=Brown and Company |location=Boston |page=17 |accessdate=August 17, 2012 |url=https://archive.org/stream/wheretoeducate1800thomrich#page/17/mode/1up}}</ref> in [[San Jose, California]]. The school was chartered in 1868 as the College of Notre Dame, the first college in the state of [[California]] authorized to grant the [[baccalaureate degree]] to women. In 1922, the [[Religious sisters|Sisters]] purchased [[Ralston Hall]], the country estate of [[William Chapman Ralston]], founder of the [[Bank of California]]. The college opened its doors in [[Belmont, California|Belmont]] in 1923.\n\nIn 1953 the College of Notre Dame became a four-year college with 23 Sisters of Notre Dame de Namur<ref name=\"snddenca.org\">{{cite web |url=http://www.snddenca.org/wp-content/uploads/2013/04/Final-1950-timeline_WEB.jpg |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2014-04-21 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140422233236/http://www.snddenca.org/wp-content/uploads/2013/04/Final-1950-timeline_WEB.jpg |archivedate=2014-04-22 }}</ref> involved in the school. The college introduced evening classes in 1955, and in 1965, started the [[teaching credential]] programs. Originally a women's institution, College of Notre Dame became [[Mixed-sex education|coeducational]] in 1969;<ref name=\"snddenca.org\"/> three men graduated as part of the class of 1970. The college expanded its offerings to include master's degrees in 1972 and added evening undergraduate programs in 1987.\n\nIn 2001, the college established a structure dividing the university into schools. The name of the institution was changed to Notre Dame de Namur University that same year. In 2009, the university began offering partnerships with local community colleges to provide greater access to higher education, and that same year it became a Hispanic-Serving Institution, meaning at least 25% of its undergraduate population is Hispanic, that same year. The online degree program was established in 2012, and in 2013, the university introduced one of the first PhD programs in art therapy in the nation. The university established a new campus in Tracy, California in 2015, offering evening undergraduate and graduate degree programs in business administration.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ndnu.edu/about-us/ndnu-history.aspx |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2012-03-20 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120403073458/http://www.ndnu.edu/about-us/ndnu-history.aspx |archivedate=2012-04-03 }}</ref>\n\nLaunched in 2013, Notre Dame de Namur University was one of the first universities in the United States to offer a Ph.D. in [[Art Therapy]]. The Art Therapy Ph.D. is also the first doctoral program offered at the university.\n\nIn 2016 the faculty, both full-time and adjunct, unionized with SEIU 1021. This was a historic move since tenure-line professors at Catholic universities have had trouble unionizing since the [https://www.aaup.org/import-tags/yeshiva-ruling Yeshiva ruling] (1980).<ref>https://www.insidehighered.com/quicktakes/2016/06/01/notre-dame-de-namur-recognizes-tenured-faculty-union</ref>\n\nIn December 2017, BINA48 (a [[Hanson Robotics]] robot) successfully participated as a guest student in a full semester college course on philosophy and love created and taught by Professor William J. Barry at Notre Dame de Namur University. The robot used an algorithm framework called TQ Theory created by Professor Barry to interact with rapport with students.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2017/12/21/meet-the-robot-that-passed-a-college-class-on-philosophy-and-love.html|title=Meet the robot that passed a college class on philosophy and love|last=Hess|first=Abigail|date=2017-12-21|work=CNBC|access-date=2018-01-04}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2020, the university announced major changes as a result of on-going financial issues, declining enrollment, and effects of the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]].<ref name=\"Future2020\">{{cite web |title=The Future of Notre Dame de Namur University |url=https://www.ndnu.edu/future-of-ndnu/ |publisher=Notre Dame de Namur University |date=March 23, 2020 |accessdate=1 April 2020}}</ref> The Board of Trustees made the decision to prioritize current students completing degrees by the end of the 2020\u201321 academic year while assisting other students in transfer options due to uncertainly of operations beyond the spring 2021 semester. As part of the plan, Notre Dame suspended new student admissions for summer and fall 2020 sessions.<ref name=\"Future2020\"/> The university also disbanded the athletics department at the conclusion of the 2019\u201320 academic year.<ref name=\"Future2020\"/><ref name=\"athdisband\">{{cite news |url=https://ndnuargos.com/news/2020/3/23/general-ndnu-athletics-will-not-continue-past-spring-2020.aspx |title=NDNU Athletics Will Not Continue Past Spring 2020 |accessdate=March 27, 2020 |work=ndnuargos.com |date=March 23, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Campus==\n\nNotre Dame de Namur University is located in [[Belmont, California]] on the [[San Francisco Peninsula|San Francisco Bay Area Peninsula]]  and near the [[Pacific Ocean]]. The campus is less than 30 miles from downtown [[San Francisco, California|San Francisco]] and downtown [[San Jose, California|San Jose]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ndnu.edu/visitors/location/ |title=Our Location {{!}} NDNU |accessdate=13 August 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Residence halls===\n\nNotre Dame de Namur University offers [[Dormitory|traditional dorm living]] in Julie Billiart Hall and St. Joseph's Hall, which are named for the co-foundresses of the Sisters of Notre Dame, Sister [[Julie Billiart]] and Sister [[Fran\u00e7oise Blin de Bourdon|St. Joseph Blin de Bourdon]]. The Carroll, Kane, and Wilkie Apartments are available for upperclassmen.  Students also have the option of suite living in New Hall, where suites feature four rooms joined by a common area and sharing a bathroom.  Residence hall floors are [[Mixed-sex education|co-ed]].<ref name=\"Named Buildings 2011\">''Named Buildings.'' Notre Dame de Namur University, 2011.</ref> Saint Joseph's hall has now been transformed into faculty offices and also contains a lounge and the Housing Office.\n\n===Academic buildings===\n\n[[Cuvilly]] Hall, named for Sr. Julie Billiart's birthplace, is one of the main instructional buildings and houses the School of Business and Management. [[Mary (mother of Jesus)|St. Mary's]] Hall is the largest instructional building and includes classrooms; science labs; two computer labs; public safety; and the financial aid, [[Registrar (education)|registrar]], and business offices. Gavin Hall is the smallest of the three main instructional buildings and houses the Art Therapy program.<ref name=\"Named Buildings 2011\"/>\n\nThe theater of Notre Dame de Namur University is located below the main campus on Ralston Avenue.\n\n===Ralston Hall Mansion===\n[[File:Ralston hall.JPG|thumb|250px|right|Ralston Hall]]\nThe Notre Dame de Namur University campus developed around [[Ralston Hall]] Mansion. William Chapman Ralston built Ralston Hall shortly after purchasing the property in 1864.<ref>\"Ralston Hall Mansion | A Celebrated History.\" Ralston Hall Mansion | A Celebrated History. Ralston Hall Mansion, 2013. Web. 27 Sept. 2013</ref>  William Ralston was a pivotal figure in the gold and silver bonanzas, which helped Ralston amass wealth.  Ralston Hall was built with a steamboat gothic design on the interior, which is rumored to have been influenced by Ralston's love of boating from a young age.<ref name=\"A Celebrated History 2013\">\"Ralston Hall Mansion | A Celebrated History.\" Ralston Hall Mansion | A Celebrated History. Ralston Hall Mansion, 2013. Web. 27 Sept. 2013.</ref> The interior of Ralston Hall is strikingly shaped like the inside of a boat.<ref name=\"A Celebrated History 2013\"/> Ralston Hall was built as an entertainment destination.<ref name=\"A Celebrated History 2013\"/> After William Ralston died, his business partner, [[William Sharon]], came to control the mansion.<ref name=\"A Celebrated History 2013\"/> Sharon was a [[United States Senator]] representing [[Nevada]] from 1875 to 1881.<ref name=\"A Celebrated History 2013\"/>  Ralston Hall has been used for a variety of jobs throughout its history; Ralston Hall held one of the largest American weddings when William Sharon's daughter Flora married Sir Thomas Fermor-Hesketh of England.<ref name=\"A Celebrated History 2013\"/> Notre Dame De Namur was chartered by the State of California in 1868 but was not affiliated with Ralston Hall until 1922.<ref name=\"A Celebrated History 2013\"/>  The mansion was a finishing school for young women until 1898.<ref name=\"Historic Architecture Campus Project 2013\">\"Historic Architecture Campus Project.\" Historic Colleges. N.p., Jan. 2013. Web. 16 Sept. 2013.</ref>  Since 1923 Ralston Hall has been affiliated with Notre Dame de Namur University.<ref name=\"Historic Architecture Campus Project 2013\"/>\n\nUntil April 2012, the mansion housed admissions, administrative and faculty offices, and its first floor rooms, including a [[ballroom]] modeled after the [[Hall of Mirrors (Palace of Versailles)|Hall of Mirrors at Versailles]], were rented for events. However, in late 2011, a preliminary assessment of the structural integrity of Ralston Hall suggested that occupants may not be safe in the event of an earthquake. The building is unoccupied indefinitely, until funds can be raised to complete a replacement or retrofit of the masonry foundation, in addition to extensive seismic work on the upper floors.  The renovation is estimated to cost more than $20 million <ref>{{cite web|title=Ralston Hall fixes get another look|url=https://www.smdailyjournal.com/news/local/ralston-hall-fixes-get-another-look/article_dd5c1b7e-d973-11e7-83a5-839d6fc28572.html|accessdate=24 January 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Satellite programs===\nNotre Dame de Namur University offers some bachelor's degree programs in partnership with local [[community college]] campuses. Adult students who have completed enough units to enter Notre Dame de Namur University's evening bachelor's program can take the remaining classes for their bachelor's degree on the community college campus and receive a degree from NDNU. The university established a partnership with [[Mission College (Santa Clara, California)|Mission College]] in [[Santa Clara, California]] in 2008 and offers a human services and a business degree on the community college campus.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ndnu.edu/public-relations/ndnu-news/newsMissionCollegePartnership.aspx |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2012-03-20 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111211042536/http://www.ndnu.edu/public-relations/ndnu-news/newsMissionCollegePartnership.aspx |archivedate=2011-12-11 }}</ref> A human services program was established with [[Ca\u00f1ada College]] in [[Redwood City, California]] in 2009.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ndnu.edu/public-relations/ndnu-news/newsCanada.aspx |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2012-03-20 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111211014342/http://www.ndnu.edu/public-relations/ndnu-news/newsCanada.aspx |archivedate=2011-12-11 }}</ref> In 2010, evening business <ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ndnu.edu/public-relations/ndnu-news/newsCanadaBus.aspx |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2012-03-20 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111211012047/http://www.ndnu.edu/public-relations/ndnu-news/newsCanadaBus.aspx |archivedate=2011-12-11 }}</ref> and psychology degrees were added to the partnership with Ca\u00f1ada College.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ndnu.edu/public-relations/ndnu-news/newsCanadaPsych.aspx |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2012-03-20 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111211012427/http://www.ndnu.edu/public-relations/ndnu-news/newsCanadaPsych.aspx |archivedate=2011-12-11 }}</ref>\n\nIn 2015, the university launched a satellite campus in Tracy, California. The NDNU Tracy campus offers undergraduate and graduate degree programs in business administration, a bachelor's in human services, as well as teaching credentials. The classes are held in the evening in an accelerated format.<ref>{{cite web |title=Admissions--NDNU Tracy campus website.|url=http://tracy.ndnu.edu/admissions//|website=Ndnu.edu|accessdate=24 January 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Organization and administration==\nNotre Dame de Namur University is a [[nonprofit organization]] governed by a [[Board of directors|Board of Trustees]].\n\nUniversity administration consists of a [[University president|president]], a [[Provost (education)|provost]], [[vice president]]s for enrollment management, advancement, and finance and administration, a [[Dean (education)|dean]] of students, and deans of the three schools.\n\nThe university is organized into three schools: the College of Arts and Sciences, the School of Business and Management, and the School of Education and Psychology. Each school is led by a dean.\n\n===Student Assembly===\n\nThe Student Assembly is the official [[Student government|student governing body]] of the university. The purpose of the Student Assembly Leadership Team (SALT) is to represent and to provide for the general welfare of the student body and the university. The leadership consists of a president, vice presidents for communications and finance, and two senators from each school.<ref>https://www.ndnu.edu/campus-life/clubs-activities/student-assembly/</ref>\n\n==Academics==\n\nNotre Dame de Namur University is a [[Liberal arts college|liberal arts institution]] offering bachelor's and master's degrees, a doctoral degree in Art Therapy, and teaching credentials. In addition to the degrees offered on the campus, several programs are available 100% online: bachelor's in Criminal Justice, Master of Arts in Teaching English to Speakers of Other Languages (TESOL), a Master of Science in Business Administration, and Master of Public Administration.\n\nNotre Dame de Namur University is currently ranked by U.S. News & World Report among the Best Regional Universities West and Best Value Schools.<ref>https://www.usnews.com/best-colleges/notre-dame-de-namur-university-1179</ref>\n\n===Community-based learning===\nAs part of the university's mission of social justice and the goal of equipping students with \"what they need to know for life,\" Notre Dame de Namur University offers over 20 community-based learning (CBL) courses, designed to promote learning through [[community engagement]]. These courses involve partnerships within the community, and work for an outcome of affecting positive social change. Many of the academic programs at Notre Dame de Namur University offer CBL courses, including [[psychology]], religious studies, [[sociology]], accounting, [[biological sciences]], [[communications]], [[natural science]], and [[music]]. NDNU has received the Carnegie Foundation's Elective Community Engagement Classification.<ref>http://nerche.org/images/stories/projects/Carnegie/2015/2010_and_2015_CE_Classified_Institutions_revised_8_10_16.pdf</ref>\n\n===Accreditation===\nNotre Dame de Namur University is accredited by the [[Western Association of Schools and Colleges]] (WASC), Senior College and University Commission. Accredited or approved programs at Notre Dame de Namur University include:\n*Education Credentials: [[California Commission on Teacher Credentialing]]\n*Art Therapy: [[American Art Therapy Association]]\n*Marriage and Family Therapy: meets established guidelines of the California Board of Behavioral Sciences\n*Clinical Psychology/MFT: meets established guidelines of the California Board of Behavioral Sciences\n*Business: [[Accreditation Council for Business Schools and Programs]]\n\n== Sister Dorothy Stang Center ==\nThe Sister Dorothy Stang Center for Social Justice and Community Engagement (DSC) was established on the Notre Dame de Namur University campus in honor of the work of [[Dorothy Stang|Sister Dorothy Stang, SNDdeN]], who was murdered in [[Brazil]] due to her efforts to aid the poor farmers and the environment in that country. The Center works to increase awareness of [[social justice|social]] and [[environmental justice]] issues, as well as encourage dialogue, community service, engagement, and activism in these areas. Members of the university and the larger community can work with the DSC to create positive social change, and come to a greater understanding of the issues that affect the community.\n\n== Athletics ==\nThe Notre Dame de Namur University [[Argonauts]] were the athletic teams of the university until 2020. The university mascot, the Argonaut, is named for the mythical [[Argonauts]] who sailed with Jason in search of the Golden Fleece. The team colors blue, gold and white reflected the colors of the university. The university most recently competed at the [[National Collegiate Athletic Association|National Collegiate Athletic Association (NCAA)]] [[NCAA Division II|Division II]] level as members of the [[Pacific West Conference]], except for men's lacrosse, which has an [[NCAA Division II independent schools|Independent]] affiliation after leaving the [[Western Intercollegiate Lacrosse Association]] at the end of the 2014 season.<ref name=\"athdisband\"/> In March 2020, the university announced the discontinuation of the athletics programs effective at the conclusion of the Spring 2020 semester. The decision was part of various changes to the university, citing an on-going financial situation and declining enrollment.<ref name=\"athdisband\"/> At the time of the discontinuation, NDNU had 12 varsity sports. Men's sports included [[College basketball|basketball]], [[Cross country running|cross country]], [[golf]], [[College lacrosse|lacrosse]], [[College soccer|soccer]], and [[track and field]] while women's sports included basketball, cross country, soccer, [[College softball|softball]], [[Intercollegiate Tennis Association|tennis]], track and field, and [[volleyball]].<ref name=\"athdisband\"/>\n\nNotre Dame athletics competed in the Division II [[Northern California Athletic Conference]] (NCAC) until 1997 when the conference disbanded. NDNU joined the [[National Association of Intercollegiate Athletics]] (NAIA) and the [[California Pacific Conference]] (Cal Pac).<ref name=\"grassroots\">{{cite news |last1=Kroichick |first1=Ron |title=A place where college sports are a grassroots movement |url=https://www.sfgate.com/bayarea/article/A-place-where-college-sports-are-a-grassroots-3229843.php |accessdate=1 April 2020 |publisher=SFGate |date=January 23, 2008}}</ref> The university rejoined the NCAA in 2005 when the Pacific West Conference voted to admit Notre Dame de Namur University.<ref name=\"grassroots\"/>\n\n== Diversity ==\n\nNotre Dame de Namur University is one of the most diverse private colleges in California, qualifying as both a Hispanic Serving Institution (HSI) and an Asian American Native American Pacific Islander Serving Institution (AANAPISI).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ndnu.edu/about/diversity/|title=Commitment to Diversity - Notre Dame de Namur University|website=Ndnu.edu|accessdate=24 January 2018}}</ref> The university's commitment to diversity is based on the Hallmarks of a Notre Dame de Namur Learning Community, which states, \"We embrace the gift of diversity.\" <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ndnu.edu/about/mission-strategy/hallmarks-of-a-notre-dame-de-namur-learning-community/|title=Hallmarks of a Notre Dame de Namur Learning Community - Notre Dame de Namur University|website=Ndnu.edu|accessdate=24 January 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Notable alumni==\n*[[Maria Cristina Villanova de Arbenz]], politician,  [[First Lady of Guatemala]].\n*[[Lailee Bakhtiar]], poet, journalist, author, novelist\n*[[Eddie Baza Calvo]], politician, Governor of Guam\n*[[Belo Cipriani]], blind and Latino writer and LGBT activist \n*[[Simon Enciso]], professional athlete in basketball<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20160820190604/http://www.smdailyjournal.com/articles/sports/2015-08-25/simon-enciso-taken-in-2nd-round-of-pba-draft/1776425149034.html]</ref>\n*[[Abigail Campbell Kaw\u0101nanakoa]], politician and Princess of Hawaii\n*[[Morghan King]], Olympic athlete in weightlifting<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ndnuargos.com/news/2016/6/3/womens-soccer-former-ndnu-soccer-player-morghan-king-secures-olympics-trip-in-weightlifting.aspx|title=Former NDNU Soccer Player Morghan King Secures Olympics Trip in Weightlifting|website=Notre Dame de Namur University|accessdate=24 October 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nbcolympics.com/news/who-morghan-king|title=Who is \u2026 Morghan King?|website=Nbcolympics.com|accessdate=24 October 2017}}</ref>\n*[[Matthew Mbu Junior]], politician, Senator of Federal Republic of Nigeria\n*Myles McCormick, former CEO of Bare Escentuals, currently an Advisory Director for Berkshire Partners<ref>{{cite web|title=Myles McCormick {{!}} LinkedIn|url=http://www.linkedin.com/pub/myles-mccormick/33/618/a17|accessdate=8 January 2013}}</ref> \n*[[Barbara Morgan]], NASA Astronaut\n*[[Susan Heon]] Preston, Olympic athlete in swimming<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.edmodo.com/spreston84|title=Edmodo|website=Edmodo|accessdate=24 October 2017}}</ref>\n*[[Santino Reynolds]], collegiate basketball coach at [[Fresno Pacific University]] in [[Fresno]], [[California]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Santino Reynolds|url=https://www.fpuathletics.com/sports/womens-basketball/roster/coaches/santino-reynolds/1100|website=Fresno Pacific University Athletics|accessdate=23 March 2020}}</ref>\n*[[Anton del Rosario]], professional athlete in soccer<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.abs-cbn.com/sports/06/25/11/azkals-close-anton-del-rosario|title=Azkals up close: Anton del Rosario|author=Barry Viloria|website=News.abs-cbn.com|accessdate=24 October 2017}}</ref>\n*[[Dorothy Stang]], class of 1964<ref>[https://archive.is/20130415224303/http://web.sndden.org/dev/triprov/DorothyStang.htm]</ref> - activist, Sister of Notre Dame de Namur\n*Phillip Walker, CEO, Network Solutions Provider, named to list of Top 10 Black Entrepreneurs by Inc. Magazine<ref>{{cite web|title=NDNU {{!}} Alumni {{!}} Alumni Stories|url=http://www.ndnu.edu/alumni/stories.aspx|accessdate=20 July 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=The 2011 INC. 5000 Top 10 Black Entrepreneurs {{!}} Inc.com|url=http://www.inc.com/ss/2011-inc-5000-top-10-black-entrepreneurs#5|accessdate=20 July 2012}}</ref>\n*[[Susie Wind]], M.A. 1997 in Art Therapy \u2014 visual artist \n*[[Emily Wu]], author, novelist\n*[[Wang Yi (volleyball)|Wang Yi]], Olympic athlete in volleyball<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gocolumbialions.com/ViewArticle.dbml?DB_OEM_ID=9600&ATCLID=1515143|title=Yi Wang|website=Gocolumbialions.com|accessdate=24 October 2017}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|http://www.ndnu.edu/}}\n*[http://www.ndnuargos.com/ Official athletics website]\n\n{{Women's Colleges that are Coeducational}}\n\n{{authority control}}