->\n|}</onlyinclude>\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n<!--==Home video releases==\n===Japanese===\n\n===English===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center; width: 98%;\"\n|+ Sentai Filmworks (Region 1)\n|-\n! colspan=\"2\" | Volume\n! width=\"20%\" | Episodes\n! width=\"15%\" | Release date\n! width=\"5%\"  | Ref.\n|-\n| rowspan=\"1\" width=\"1%\" style=\"background: #;\" |\n| \n| 1-13\n| TBA 202X\n| <ref>{{cite web|url=|title=|publisher=|accessdate=}}</ref>\n|}-->\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Food Wars! Shokugeki no Soma}}\n\n[[Category:Food Wars!: Shokugeki no Soma episode lists]]\n[[Category:2020 Japanese television seasons]]\n", "text_old": "{{DISPLAYTITLE:''Food Wars! Shokugeki no Soma'' (season 5)}}\n{{Infobox television season\n |season_number= 5\n |image        = \n |caption      = \n |country      = Japan\n |num_episodes = 13\n |network      = [[Tokyo MX]], [[Nippon BS Broadcasting|BS11]], [[Animax]], [[AbemaTV]]\n |first_aired  = {{Start date|2020|4|11}}\n |last_aired   = {{End date|present}}\n |episode_list = List of Food Wars! Shokugeki no Soma episodes\n |prev_season  = [[Food Wars! Shokugeki no Soma (season 4)|Season 4]]\n}}\nThe fifth and last season of ''[[Food Wars!: Shokugeki no Soma]]'' anime television series, subtitled {{nihongo|''Food Wars! Shokugeki no Soma: The Fifth Plate''|\u98df\u621f\u306e\u30bd\u30fc\u30de \u8c6a\u30ce\u76bf|Shokugeki no S\u014dma: Go no Sara}}, was produced by [[J.C.Staff]] and directed by [[Yoshitomo Yonetani]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2020-03-22/food-wars-shokugeki-no-soma-anime-5th-season-casts-jun-fukuyama/.157797|title=Food Wars! Shokugeki no Soma Anime's 5th Season Casts Jun Fukuyama (Updated)|publisher=Anime News Network|accessdate=March 22, 2020}}</ref> The series was first broadcast in Japan on [[Tokyo MX]]. It premiered on April 11, 2020. The opening theme is \"Last Chapter\" by Nano Ripe, while the ending theme song is \"Crossing Road\" by [[Mai Fuchigami]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2020-02-09/nano.ripe-mai-fuchigami-perform-themes-for-food-wars-shokugeki-no-soma-anime-5th-season/.156244 |title=nano.RIPE, Mai Fuchigami Perform Themes for Food Wars! Shokugeki no Soma Anime's 5th Season |website=Anime News Network |date=February 9, 2020 |accessdate=February 9, 2020 }}</ref> On April 17, 2020, it was announced that after the second episode, the remaining episodes of the season has been delayed due to the effect of the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2020-04-17/food-wars-shokugeki-no-soma-anime-delays-new-episodes-due-to-covid-19/.158711|title=Food Wars! Shokugeki no Soma Anime Delays New Episodes Due to COVID-19|publisher=Anime News Network|date=April 17, 2020|accessdate=April 18, 2020}}</ref> \n\n__TOC__\n{{clear}}\n\n==Episode list==\n<onlyinclude>\n{|class=\"plainrowheaders wikitable\" style=\"width:98%; margin:auto; background:#FFF;\n|- style=\"border-bottom: 3px solid #CCF;\"\n! style=\"width:4em;\"      | {{Abbr|No.|Number}} in series\n! style=\"width:4em;\"      | {{Abbr|No.|Number}} in season\n! style=\"min-width:30em;\" | Title{{efn|English translated titles are taken from the official website.}}\n! style=\"width:12em;\"     | Original airdate\n|-\n{{Episode list/sublist\n| 1               = Food Wars! Shokugeki no Soma (season 5)\n| EpisodeNumber   = 74\n| EpisodeNumber2  = 1\n| Title           = Final Exams\n| TranslitTitle   = Gakkimatsu Shiken\n| NativeTitle     = \u5b66\u671f\u672b\u8a66\u9a13\n| NativeTitleLangCode = ja\n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2020|4|11}}\n| ShortSummary    = \n}}\n{{Episode list/sublist\n| 1               = Food Wars! Shokugeki no Soma (season 5)\n| EpisodeNumber   = 75\n| EpisodeNumber2  = 2\n| Title           = The BLUE Preliminaries\n| TranslitTitle   = Ao no Zensh\u014dsen\n| NativeTitle     = \u9752\u306e\u524d\u54e8\u6226\n| NativeTitleLangCode = ja\n| OriginalAirDate = {{start date|2020|4|18}}\n| ShortSummary    = \n}}\n{{Episode list/sublist\n| 1               = Food Wars! Shokugeki no Soma (season 5)\n| EpisodeNumber   = 76\n| EpisodeNumber2  = 3\n| Title           = Noir\n| TranslitTitle   = \n| NativeTitle     = \n| NativeTitleLangCode = ja\n| OriginalAirDate = TBD\n| ShortSummary    = \n}}<!--\n{{Episode list/sublist\n| 1               = Food Wars! Shokugeki no Soma (season 5)\n| EpisodeNumber   = 77\n| EpisodeNumber2  = 4\n| Title           = \n| TranslitTitle   = \n| NativeTitle     = \n| NativeTitleLangCode = ja\n| OriginalAirDate = \n| ShortSummary    = \n}}\n{{Episode list/sublist\n| 1               = Food Wars! Shokugeki no Soma (season 5)\n| EpisodeNumber   = 78\n| EpisodeNumber2  = 5\n| Title           = \n| TranslitTitle   = \n| NativeTitle     = \n| NativeTitleLangCode = ja\n| OriginalAirDate = \n| ShortSummary    = \n}}\n{{Episode list/sublist\n| 1               = Food Wars! Shokugeki no Soma (season 5)\n| EpisodeNumber   = 79\n| EpisodeNumber2  = 6\n| Title           = \n| TranslitTitle   = \n| NativeTitle     = \n| NativeTitleLangCode = ja\n| OriginalAirDate = \n| ShortSummary    = \n}}\n{{Episode list/sublist\n| 1               = Food Wars! Shokugeki no Soma (season 5)\n| EpisodeNumber   = 80\n| EpisodeNumber2  = 7\n| Title           = \n| TranslitTitle   = \n| NativeTitle     = \n| NativeTitleLangCode = ja\n| OriginalAirDate = \n| ShortSummary    = \n}}\n{{Episode list/sublist\n| 1               = Food Wars! Shokugeki no Soma (season 5)\n| EpisodeNumber   = 81\n| EpisodeNumber2  = 8\n| Title           = \n| TranslitTitle   = \n| NativeTitle     = \n| NativeTitleLangCode = ja\n| OriginalAirDate = \n| ShortSummary    = \n}}\n{{Episode list/sublist\n| 1               = Food Wars! Shokugeki no Soma (season 5)\n| EpisodeNumber   = 82\n| EpisodeNumber2  = 9\n| Title           = \n| TranslitTitle   = \n| NativeTitle     = \n| NativeTitleLangCode = ja\n| OriginalAirDate = \n| ShortSummary    = \n}}\n{{Episode list/sublist\n| 1               = Food Wars! Shokugeki no Soma (season 5)\n| EpisodeNumber   = 83\n| EpisodeNumber2  = 10\n| Title           = \n| TranslitTitle   = \n| NativeTitle     = \n| NativeTitleLangCode = ja\n| OriginalAirDate = \n| ShortSummary    = \n}}\n{{Episode list/sublist\n| 1               = Food Wars! Shokugeki no Soma (season 5)\n| EpisodeNumber   = 84\n| EpisodeNumber2  = 11\n| Title           = \n| TranslitTitle   = \n| NativeTitle     = \n| NativeTitleLangCode = ja\n| OriginalAirDate = \n| ShortSummary    = \n}}\n{{Episode list/sublist\n| 1               = Food Wars! Shokugeki no Soma (season 5)\n| EpisodeNumber   = 85\n| EpisodeNumber2  = 12\n| Title           = \n| TranslitTitle   = \n| NativeTitle     = \n| NativeTitleLangCode = ja\n| OriginalAirDate = \n| ShortSummary    = \n}}\n{{Episode list/sublist\n| 1               = Food Wars! Shokugeki no Soma (season 5)\n| EpisodeNumber   = 86\n| EpisodeNumber2  = 13\n| Title           = \n| TranslitTitle   = \n| NativeTitle     = \n| NativeTitleLangCode = ja\n| OriginalAirDate = \n| ShortSummary    = \n}}-->\n|}</onlyinclude>\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n<!--==Home video releases==\n===Japanese===\n\n===English===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center; width: 98%;\"\n|+ Sentai Filmworks (Region 1)\n|-\n! colspan=\"2\" | Volume\n! width=\"20%\" | Episodes\n! width=\"15%\" | Release date\n! width=\"5%\"  | Ref.\n|-\n| rowspan=\"1\" width=\"1%\" style=\"background: #;\" |\n| \n| 1-13\n| TBA 202X\n| <ref>{{cite web|url=|title=|publisher=|accessdate=}}</ref>\n|}-->\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Food Wars! Shokugeki no Soma}}\n\n[[Category:Food Wars!: Shokugeki no Soma episode lists]]\n[[Category:2020 Japanese television seasons]]\n[[Category:Anime postponed due to the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]]\n", "name_user": "81.154.188.36", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eAnime:THIS IS BULLSH*T)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Food_Wars!_Shokugeki_no_Soma_(season_5)"}
{"title_page": "June Almeida", "text_new": "{{under construction|date=April 2020}}\n{{short description|Scottish virologist}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2017}}\n{{Use British English|date=December 2017}}\n{{Infobox scientist\n| name              = June Dalziel Almeida\n| image             = June_Dalziel_Almeida_died_2007.png\n| image_size        = \n| alt               = \n| caption           = \n| birth_name        = June Dalziel Hart\n| birth_date        = {{Birth date|1930|10|05|df=yes|}}\n| birth_place       = [[Glasgow]], [[Scotland]]\n| death_date        = {{death date and age|2007|12|1|1930|10|5|df=yes}}\n| death_place       = [[Bexhill-on-Sea|Bexhill]], England\n| resting_place     = \n| residence         = \n| nationality  = [[Scotland|Scottish]]\n| citizenship  = [[Kingdom of Great Britain|British]]\n| fields            = [[Virology]], [[histopathology]]\n| workplaces        = [[Glasgow Royal Infirmary]], [[St Bartholomew's Hospital]], [[Ontario Cancer Institute]], [[Royal Postgraduate Medical School]], [[Wellcome Research Laboratory]]\n| alma_mater        = \n| thesis_title      = \n| thesis_url        = \n| thesis_year       = \n| doctoral_advisor  = \n| academic_advisors = \n| doctoral_students = \n| notable_students  = \n| known_for         = Pioneer of [[Immunostaining#Immuno-electron microscopy|immuno-electron microscopy]]\n| author_abbrev_bot = \n| author_abbrev_zoo = \n| influences        = \n| influenced        = [[Albert Kapikian]] and  [[Thomas Henry Flewett]]\n| awards            = \n| footnotes         = \n| spouse            = {{marriage|Enriques Rosalio (Henry) Almeida|1954|}} <br> {{marriage|Phillip Samuel Gardner|1982|1994}} (deceased)\n| children = 1\n}}\n\n'''June Dalziel Almeida''' (5 October 1930 \u2013 1 December 2007) was a Scottish [[Virology|virologist]] a pioneer in virus imaging, identification and diagnosis.<ref name=\"Booss_August_2013\"/> Her skills in electron microscopy earned her an international reputation.<ref name=\"BMJ_Obit_20080418\"/> In 1964, Almeida was she was invited to be part of a research team at [[St Thomas's Hospital Medical School]] in London.  By 1967, she earned her [[Doctor of Science]] (Sc.D.) on the basis of her research and the resulting publications, while working at the [[Ontario Cancer Institute]] in Toronto, Ontario in Canada and at St Thomas.<ref name=\"BMJ_Obit_20080418\"/> In 1967, she continued her research at the [[Royal Postgraduate Medical School]] (RPGMS),<ref name=\"BMJ_Obit_20080418\"/> which is now part of the [[Imperial College School of Medicine]]. She succeeded in identifying viruses that were previously unknown, including a virus that was called a [[coronavirus]] in 1966.<ref name=\"JGV_Almeida_1966\" group=\"Publications\"/><ref name=\"Tyrrell_Fielder_2002\"/>{{rp|96}} She contributed to the [[World Health Organization]] (WHO) 1979 ''Manual for rapid laboratory viral diagnosis.'' Her electron micrographs continue to be included in virology review textbooks, decades after she produced them.<ref name=\"BMJ_Obit_20080418\"/>  \n\n==Major contributions==\nIn their 2013 book entitled ''To catch a virus'', John Booss and Marilyn J. August describe how Almeida \"played a crucial role in adapting the electron microscope to clinical diagnostic virology work.\"<ref name=\"Booss_August_2013\"/>{{rp|209}} \n\nIn their chapter entitled \"Imaging viruses and tagging their antigenes\", they describe how from 1941 until the work of Almeida and Anthony P. Waterson in the early 1960s, very little progress had occurred from 1941 towards improving on the initial 1941 \"proof of priniciple, aggregation of virus by virus-specific antibody observable by [electron microscope (EI)].\"<ref name=\"Booss_August_2013\"/>{{rp|208}} \n\nIn the early 1960s, Almeida and Tony Waterson, were using negative staining for the EM of viruses, a technique that was both \"rapid and simple, and provided excellent detailed observations of viral morphology\" which Almeida and Waterson said, \"revolutionized the electron microscopy of viruses\" \"overnight\".<ref name=\"Booss_August_2013\"/>{{rp|208}} \n\nAlmeida pioneered a technique in immune electron microscopy (IEM), to better visualise viruses by using [[antibody|antibodies]] to aggregate them.<ref name=\"JEM_Almeida_1963\" group=\"Publications\"/> Using this method she produced the \"first visualization of rubella virus\" in 1967.<ref name=\"Lancet_Best_1967\">{{Cite journal| doi = 10.1016/S0140-6736(67)92302-1| issn = 0140-6736| volume = 290| issue = 7509| pages = 237\u2013239| last1 = Best| first1 = Jennifer M| last2 = Banatvala| first2 = J. E.| last3 = Almeida| first3 = June D| last4 = Waterson| first4 = A. P.| title = Morphological characteristics of rubella virus| journal = [[The Lancet]]| access-date =18 April 2020| date = 29 July 1967| url = https://www.thelancet.com/journals/lancet/article/PIIS0140-6736(67)92302-1/abstract}}</ref><ref name=\"BMJ_Obit_20080418\"/><ref>{{Cite book|title=Brilliant! Scottish inventors, innovators, scientists and engineers who changed the world|last=Paterson|first=Andrew|publisher=Austin Macauley|year=2017|isbn=9781786294357|location=London|pages=577}}</ref>\n\n==Early life ==\nJune Dalziel Hart was born on 5 October 1930 at 10 Duntroon Street, [[Glasgow]] to Jane Dalziel (n\u00e9e Steven) and Harry Leonard Hart, a bus driver.<ref name=\"BMJ_Obit_20080418\">{{Cite journal| volume = 336| issue = 7659| pages = 1511.1\u20131511| last = Almeida| first = Joyce| title = June Almeida (n\u00e9e Hart)| journal = [[The BMJ]]| publisher= [[BMJ Group]] | access-date = 18 April 2020| date = 28 June 2008| url = https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC2440895/| pmc = 2440895 |issn=| doi = 10.1136/bmj.a434 |bibcode = 1963Sci...142.1487A}}</ref>{{rp|1511.1\u20131511}}<ref name=\"Booss_August_2013\"/><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/|title=The Times & The Sunday Times|website=www.thetimes.co.uk}}</ref>   \n\n==Education==\nIn 1947, when Almeida was 16, she left school, and in spite of her academic strength, she did not have the financial means to attend university at that time.<ref name=\"BMJ_Obit_20080418\"/>\n\nBy 1964, Almeida had earned her doctorate in science (Sc.D.) based on her publications of her research undertaken at the Ontario Cancer Institute and at St Thomas on electron micrographic research of antibodies.<ref name=\"Booss_August_2013\"/>{{rp|209}}\n\n==Early career==\n\nIn 1947, she began working as a [[histopathology]] technician, first, at the [[Glasgow Royal Infirmary]], and then at [[St Bartholomew's Hospital]], where she worked until 1954.<ref name=\"BMJ_Obit_20080418\"/>\n\n===Ontario Cancer Institute===\n\nIn Toronto, Canada in 1954,  she was hired for a newly-opened position as [[Electron microscope|electron microscopy]] technician at the [[Ontario Cancer Institute]],<ref name=\"BMJ_Obit_20080418\"/><ref name=\"Booss_August_2013\"/>{{rp|209}} where she worked for ten years. \n\nWhile working as an electronmicroscopist, she and her Cancer Institute colleagues \"produced a series of studies applying negative staining to clinical problems.\"<ref name=\"Booss_August_2013\"/>{{rp|209}} \n\nIn 1963 she was the first  of three authors, who co-published an article in the journal ''[[Science]]'', in which they identified virus-like particles in cancer patients' blood.<ref name=\"Science_Almeida_1963\">{{Cite journal| title = Virus-Like Particles in Blood of Two Acute Leukemia Patients | access-date = 18 April 2020| url = https://science.sciencemag.org/content/142/3598/1487 |title=Virus-Like Particles in Blood of Two Acute Leukemia Patients |first1=June D. |last1=Almeida |first2=Richard C. |last2=Hasselback |first3=Arthur W. |last3=Ham|journal=Science  |date=December 13, 1963 |volume=142 |number=3598 |pages= 1487\u20131489 |doi=10.1126/science.142.3598.1487 |pmid=14077540}}</ref> \n\nIn 1963, she co-published her research in which she \"negatively stained aggregates of antigen...and antibody\" with the electron microscope.<ref name=\"JEM_Almeida_1963\" group=\"Publications\">{{Cite journal| doi = 10.1084/jem.118.3.327| issn = 0022-1007| volume = 118| issue = 3| pages = 327\u2013340| last1 = Almeida| first1 = June| last2 = Cinader| first2 = Bernhard| last3 = Howatson| first3 = Allan| title = The Structure of Antigen-Antibody Complexes: A Study by Electron Microscopy| journal = [[Journal of Experimental Medicine]] (JEM)| access-date = 18 April 2020| date = 1 September 1963| url = https://rupress.org/jem/article/118/3/327/3553/THE-STRUCTURE-OF-ANTIGEN-ANTIBODY-COMPLEXES-A}}</ref>\n\n===St Thomas's Hospital Medical School===\n{{main|St Thomas's Hospital Medical School}}\n\nIn 1964, Tony Waterson, a professor of virology, met Almeida while visiting Toronto, and recruited her to join his research team,<ref name=\"Tyrrell_Fielder_2002\">{{cite book |date=2002 |title=Cold wars: the fight against the common cold |first1=David |last1=Tyrrell |first2=Michael |last2=Fielder |location=Oxford, England |publisher=Oxford University Press |pages=253}}</ref>{{rp|96}} at one of the oldest and most prestigious medical schools in the United Kingdom, \u2014[[London]]'s [[St Thomas's Hospital Medical School]]\u2014now part of [[King's College London]]. In his 2002 co-authored book, entitled, ''Cold wars'', [[David Tyrrell (physician)|David Tyrrell]] described how Almeida seemed to be \"extending the range of the electron microscope to new limits.\"<ref name=\"Tyrrell_Fielder_2002\">{{cite book |date=2002 |title=Cold wars: the fight against the common cold |first1=David |last1=Tyrrell |first2=Michael |last2=Fielder |location=Oxford, England |publisher=Oxford University Press |pages=253}}</ref>{{rp|96}}\n\nAt St Thomas, she worked on [[hepatitis B virus]] and the [[Common cold|cold viruses]].<ref name=odnb/>\n\nIn 1966, Almeida using technique that she had pioneered, she was able to identify, what they named a corona virus.<ref name=\"Tyrrell_Fielder_2002\"/>{{rp|96}}\n\n{{clear left}}\n[[File:Virus surrounded by a distinct 200 A long fringe by Almeida and Tyrrell 1966.png|left|thumb|Virus identified by Almeida 1966]]In the article they co-authored in 1966 ''[[Journal of General Virology]]'', they identified a \"previously uncharacterized human respiratory viruses.\" \n\nIn 1966, Almeida and Tyrrell wrote that, \"The particles are pleomorphic, in the size range 800 to 1200 A, and are surrounded by a distinct 200 A long fringe. They are indistinguishable from the particles of avian infectious bronchitis.\"<ref name=\"JGV_Almeida_1966\" group=\"Publications\">{{Cite journal|last=Almeida|first=June D.|last2=Tyrrell|first2=D. A. J.|date=1967|title=The Morphology of Three Previously Uncharacterized Human Respiratory Viruses that Grow in Organ Culture|journal=Journal of General Virology|volume=1|issue=2|pages=175\u2013178|doi=10.1099/0022-1317-1-2-175|pmid=4293939|issn=0022-1317}}</ref>\n\nIn 1968, she co-published an article in ''[[Journal of General Virology]]'', on \"avian infectious bronchitis virus\".<ref name=\"JGV_Berry_Almeida_1968\" group=\"Publications\">{{Cite journal| doi = 10.1099/0022-1317-3-1-97| issn = 0022-1317| volume = 3| issue = 1| pages = 97\u2013102| last1 = Berry| first1 = D. M.| last2 = Almeida| first2 = June D.| title = The Morphological and Biological Effects of Various Antisera on Avian Infectious Bronchitis Virus| journal = [[Journal of General Virology]] (JGV)| access-date = 18 April 2020| date = 1968| url = https://www.microbiologyresearch.org/content/journal/jgv/10.1099/0022-1317-3-1-97}}</ref>\n\n[[David Tyrrell (physician)|David Tyrrell]] and Almeida worked on characterising a new type of [[coronavirus]].<ref name=\"Booss_August_2013\"/>{{rp|209}}\n\nThis family includes the [[SARS virus]] and the SARS-CoV2 virus that causes [[Coronavirus disease 2019|COVID-19]].\n\nShe finished her career at the [[Wellcome Institute]].<ref name=odnb>{{cite ODNB |first1=J. E. |last1=Banatvala |series=Almeida, June Dalziel (1930\u20132007) |title=Oxford Dictionary of National Biography |date= January 2011 |doi=10.1093/ref:odnb/99332 |url=http://www.oxforddnb.com/view/article/99332 |access-date= 18 October 2012}}</ref>  While working for Wellcome she was named on several patents in the field of imaging viruses.<ref>[http://patent.ipexl.com/inventor/Almeida_June_Dalziel_1.html Almeida, June Dalziel], patents, accessed October 2012</ref>\n\n{{clear left}}\n\n==Influences== \nAccording to a 7 March article in the ''[[Herald Scotland]],'' [[Hugh Pennington]] said that Almeida was his mentor.<ref name=\"heraldscotland_20200307\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.heraldscotland.com/news/18289806.june-almeida-tribute-scotlands-forgotten-hero-coronavirus/ |date= 7 March 2020 |access-date=18 April 2020|title=June Almeida, tribute to Scotland's forgotten hero of the coronavirus|newspaper=Herald Scotland}}</ref>\n\nIn 1970, [[Albert Kapikian]] studied Almeida's techniques in the United Kingdom for six months in order to use her techniques in the identification of a cause of non-bacterial gastroenteritis \u2013 the [[Norwalk virus]].<ref name=odnb/>\n\nDuring the early months of the coronavirus pandemic, Chinese scientists credited her work\u2014including techniques she developed\u2014with the early identification of [[Coronavirus disease 2019|COVID-19]], according to Pennington.<ref name=\"heraldscotland_20200307\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.heraldscotland.com/news/18289806.june-almeida-tribute-scotlands-forgotten-hero-coronavirus/ |date= 7 March 2020 |access-date=18 April 2020|title=June Almeida, tribute to Scotland's forgotten hero of the coronavirus|newspaper=Herald Scotland}}</ref>\n\n==Later career==\nAfter retiring from Wellcome Institute, she returned in an advisory role in the late 1980s when she helped take novel pictures of the [[HIV virus]].<ref name=\"BMJ_Obit_20080418\"/>\n\n==Research==\n\nIn the chapter entitled \"Imaging viruses and tagging their antigenes\" in John Booss and Marilyn J. August's 2013 ''To catch a virus'', they describe the how \"refinements in electron microscopy (EM)...greatly expanded the understanding of the structure and replication of viruses and facilitated the application of EM to viral diagnosis. The refinements included thin sectioning, negative staining, and immunoelectron microscopy (IEM) developed for clinical diagnostic work. The use of EM in discovering the viral causes of acute gastroenteritis and infectious hepatitis are then considered.\"<ref name=\"Booss_August_2013\">{{Cite book | last1 = Booss |first1=John |authorlink=John Boos| last2 = August |first2=Marilyn J. | title = To catch a virus | publisher = ASM Press | location = Washington, DC |chapter=Chapter 7: Imaging viruses and tagging their antigenes |pages=197-249| access-date = 18 April 2020| year = 2013 | url=https://archive.org/details/tocatchvirus0000boos/page/217 | isbn = 978-1-55581-507-3 |quote=ASM: \"This chapter first examines the refinements in electron microscopy (EM) that greatly expanded the understanding of the structure and replication of viruses and facilitated the application of EM to viral diagnosis. The refinements included thin sectioning, negative staining, and immunoelectron microscopy (IEM) developed for clinical diagnostic work. The use of EM in discovering the viral causes of acute gastroenteritis and infectious hepatitis are then considered.\"}}</ref>{{rp|209}} They cite a 1967 journal article by Tyrrell and Almeida, \"Direct electron-microscopy of organ culture for the detection and characterization of viruses.\"<ref name=\"Tyrrell_Almeida_1967\" group=\"Publications\">{{Cite journal| doi = 10.1007/bf01242962| issn = 0003-9012| volume = 22| issue = 3| pages = 417\u2013425| last1 = Tyrrell| first1 = D. A.| last2 = Almeida| first2 = J. D.| title = Direct electron-microscopy of organ culture for the detection and characterization of viruses| journal = Archiv Fur Die Gesamte Virusforschung| date = 1967| pmid = 4300621}}</ref>\n\nHer publications include the 1979 ''Manual for rapid laboratory viral diagnosis'' for the [[World Health Organisation]].<ref name=\"WHO_Almeida_1979\" group=\"Publications\">{{Cite web|url=http://whqlibdoc.who.int/offset/WHO_OFFSET_47.pdf|publisher=World Health Organization (WHO) |title=Manual for rapid laboratory viral diagnosis|date=1979 |last=Almeida |first=June D.}}</ref>\n\n==Media==\n\nA 15 April 2020 ''BBC Scotland News'' said that Almedia was \"the woman who discovered the first [[coronavirus]].\"<ref name=\"BBC_Brocklehurst_20200415\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-scotland-52278716|title=The woman who discovered the first coronavirus|work=BBC News |first=Steven |last=Brocklehurst |work=BBC Scotland News |date=15 April 2020 |access-date=17 April 2020}}</ref> \n\n== Coronaviruses ==\nIn a 7 March 2020 interview with the ''Herald'', Pennington spoke of Almeida's research had informed with work of Chinese researchers during the pandemic.<ref name=\"heraldscotland_20200307\"/>\n\nDuring the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|2019\u201320 COVID-19 pandemic]], the little known story was first published by the ''Herald'' in Scotland on 7 March, the [[BBC]] on 15 April,<ref name=\"BBC_Brocklehurst_20200415\"/> the ''[[National Geographic]]'' on April 17.<ref name=\"NatGeo\">{{cite news |last1=Combs |first1=Sydney |title=She Discovered Coronaviruses Decades Ago\u2014But Got Little Recognition |url=https://www.nationalgeographic.com/history/2020/04/june-almeida-discovered-coronaviruses-decades-ago-little-recognition/ |accessdate=18 April 2020 |agency=National Geographic |publisher=[[National Geographic Society]] |date=April 17, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nAlmeida moved to Toronto, Ontario and worked at the Cancer Institute after her marriage on December 11, 1954 to Enrique Rosalio (Henry) Almeida (1913\u20131993), a Venezuelan artist with whom she had a daughter, Joyce.  Almeida died in [[Bexhill-on-Sea|Bexhill]] from a heart attack in 2007.<ref name=odnb/>\n\n== See also ==\n\n* [[Timeline of women in science]]\n\n==Selected publications==\n{{reflist|group=\"Publications\"}}\n\n==References==\n{{Scholia}}\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Almeida, June Dalziel}}\n[[Category:1930 births]]\n[[Category:2007 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Glasgow]]\n[[Category:British virologists]]\n[[Category:20th-century Scottish scientists]]\n[[Category:British women biologists]]\n[[Category:Scottish women scientists]]\n[[Category:Wellcome Trust]]\n[[Category:20th-century women scientists]]\n[[Category:Women virologists]]\n", "text_old": "{{under construction|date=April 2020}}\n{{short description|Scottish virologist}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2017}}\n{{Use British English|date=December 2017}}\n{{Infobox scientist\n| name              = June Dalziel Almeida\n| image             = June_Dalziel_Almeida_died_2007.png\n| image_size        = \n| alt               = \n| caption           = \n| birth_name        = June Dalziel Hart\n| birth_date        = {{Birth date|1930|10|05|df=yes|}}\n| birth_place       = [[Glasgow]], [[Scotland]]\n| death_date        = {{death date and age|2007|12|1|1930|10|5|df=yes}}\n| death_place       = [[Bexhill-on-Sea|Bexhill]], England\n| resting_place     = \n| residence         = \n| nationality  = [[Scotland|Scottish]]\n| citizenship  = [[Kingdom of Great Britain|British]]\n| fields            = [[Virology]], [[histopathology]]\n| workplaces        = [[Glasgow Royal Infirmary]], [[St Bartholomew's Hospital]], [[Ontario Cancer Institute]], [[Royal Postgraduate Medical School]], [[Wellcome Research Laboratory]]\n| alma_mater        = \n| thesis_title      = \n| thesis_url        = \n| thesis_year       = \n| doctoral_advisor  = \n| academic_advisors = \n| doctoral_students = \n| notable_students  = \n| known_for         = Pioneer of [[Immunostaining#Immuno-electron microscopy|immuno-electron microscopy]]\n| author_abbrev_bot = \n| author_abbrev_zoo = \n| influences        = \n| influenced        = [[Albert Kapikian]] and  [[Thomas Henry Flewett]]\n| awards            = \n| footnotes         = \n| spouse            = {{marriage|Enriques Rosalio (Henry) Almeida|1954|}} <br> {{marriage|Phillip Samuel Gardner|1982|1994}} (deceased)\n| children = 1\n}}\n\n'''June Dalziel Almeida''' (5 October 1930 \u2013 1 December 2007) was a Scottish [[Virology|virologist]] a pioneer in virus imaging, identification and diagnosis.<ref name=\"Booss_August_2013\"/> Her skills in electron microscopy earned her an international reputation.<ref name=\"BMJ_Obit_20080418\"/> In 1964, Almeida was she was invited to be part of a research team at [[St Thomas's Hospital Medical School]] in London.  By 1967, she earned her [[Doctor of Science]] (Sc.D.) on the basis of her research and the resulting publications, while working at the [[Ontario Cancer Institute]] in Toronto, Ontario in Canada and at St Thomas.<ref name=\"BMJ_Obit_20080418\"/> In 1967, she continued her research at the [[Royal Postgraduate Medical School]] (RPGMS),<ref name=\"BMJ_Obit_20080418\"/> which is now part of the [[Imperial College School of Medicine]]. She succeeded in identifying viruses that were previously unknown, including a virus that was called a [[coronavirus]] in 1966.<ref name=\"JGV_Almeida_1966\" group=\"Publications\"/><ref name=\"Tyrrell_Fielder_2002\"/>{{rp|96}} She contributed to the [[World Health Organization]] (WHO) 1979 ''Manual for rapid laboratory viral diagnosis.'' Her electron micrographs continue to be included in virology review textbooks, decades after she produced them.<ref name=\"BMJ_Obit_20080418\"/>  \n\n==Major contributions==\nIn their 2013 book entitled ''To catch a virus'', John Booss and Marilyn J. August describe how Almeida \"played a crucial role in adapting the electron microscope to clinical diagnostic virology work.\"<ref name=\"Booss_August_2013\"/>{{rp|209}} \n\nIn their chapter entitled \"Imaging viruses and tagging their antigenes\", they describe how from 1941 until the work of Almeida and Anthony P. Waterson in the early 1960s, very little progress had occurred from 1941 towards improving on the initial 1941 \"proof of priniciple, aggregation of virus by virus-specific antibody observable by [electron microscope (EI)].\"<ref name=\"Booss_August_2013\"/>{{rp|208}} \n\nIn the early 1960s, Almeida and Tony Waterson, were using negative staining for the EM of viruses, a technique that was both \"rapid and simple, and provided excellent detailed observations of viral morphology\" which Almeida and Waterson said, \"revolutionized the electron microscopy of viruses\" \"overnight\".<ref name=\"Booss_August_2013\"/>{{rp|208}} \n\nAlmeida pioneered a technique in immune electron microscopy (IEM), to better visualise viruses by using [[antibody|antibodies]] to aggregate them.<ref name=\"JEM_Almeida_1963\" group=\"Publications\"/> Using this method she produced the \"first visualization of rubella virus\" in 1967.<ref name=\"Lancet_Best_1967\">{{Cite journal| doi = 10.1016/S0140-6736(67)92302-1| issn = 0140-6736| volume = 290| issue = 7509| pages = 237\u2013239| last1 = Best| first1 = Jennifer M| last2 = Banatvala| first2 = J. E.| last3 = Almeida| first3 = June D| last4 = Waterson| first4 = A. P.| title = Morphological characteristics of rubella virus| journal = [[The Lancet]]| access-date =18 April 2020| date = 29 July 1967| url = https://www.thelancet.com/journals/lancet/article/PIIS0140-6736(67)92302-1/abstract}}</ref><ref name=\"BMJ_Obit_20080418\"/><ref>{{Cite book|title=Brilliant! Scottish inventors, innovators, scientists and engineers who changed the world|last=Paterson|first=Andrew|publisher=Austin Macauley|year=2017|isbn=9781786294357|location=London|pages=577}}</ref>\n\n==Early life ==\nJune Dalziel Hart was born on 5 October 1930 at 10 Duntroon Street, [[Glasgow]] to Jane Dalziel (n\u00e9e Steven) and Harry Leonard Hart, a bus driver.<ref name=\"BMJ_Obit_20080418\">{{Cite journal| volume = 336| issue = 7659| pages = 1511.1\u20131511| last = Almeida| first = Joyce| title = June Almeida (n\u00e9e Hart)| journal = [[The BMJ]]| publisher= [[BMJ Group]] | access-date = 18 April 2020| date = 28 June 2008| url = https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC2440895/| pmc = 2440895 |issn=| doi = 10.1136/bmj.a434 |bibcode = 1963Sci...142.1487A}}</ref>{{rp|1511.1\u20131511}}<ref name=\"Booss_August_2013\"/><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/|title=The Times & The Sunday Times|website=www.thetimes.co.uk}}</ref>   \n\n==Education==\nIn 1947, when Almeida was 16, she left school, and in spite of her academic strength, she did not have the financial means to attend university at that time.<ref name=\"BMJ_Obit_20080418\"/>\n\nBy 1964, Almeida had earned her doctorate in science (Sc.D.) based on her publications of her research undertaken at the Ontario Cancer Institute working on electron micrographic research of antibodies.<ref name=\"Booss_August_2013\"/>{{rp|209}}\n\n==Early career==\n\nIn 1947, she began working as a [[histopathology]] technician, first, at the [[Glasgow Royal Infirmary]], and then at [[St Bartholomew's Hospital]], where she worked until 1954.<ref name=\"BMJ_Obit_20080418\"/>\n\n===Ontario Cancer Institute===\n\nIn Toronto, Canada in 1954,  she was hired for a newly-opened position as [[Electron microscope|electron microscopy]] technician at the [[Ontario Cancer Institute]],<ref name=\"BMJ_Obit_20080418\"/><ref name=\"Booss_August_2013\"/>{{rp|209}} where she worked for ten years. \n\nWhile working as an electronmicroscopist, she and her Cancer Institute colleagues \"produced a series of studies applying negative staining to clinical problems.\"<ref name=\"Booss_August_2013\"/>{{rp|209}} \n\nIn 1963 she was the first  of three authors, who co-published an article in the journal ''[[Science]]'', in which they identified virus-like particles in cancer patients' blood.<ref name=\"Science_Almeida_1963\">{{Cite journal| title = Virus-Like Particles in Blood of Two Acute Leukemia Patients | access-date = 18 April 2020| url = https://science.sciencemag.org/content/142/3598/1487 |title=Virus-Like Particles in Blood of Two Acute Leukemia Patients |first1=June D. |last1=Almeida |first2=Richard C. |last2=Hasselback |first3=Arthur W. |last3=Ham|journal=Science  |date=December 13, 1963 |volume=142 |number=3598 |pages= 1487\u20131489 |doi=10.1126/science.142.3598.1487 |pmid=14077540}}</ref> \n\nIn 1963, she co-published her research in which she \"negatively stained aggregates of antigen...and antibody\" with the electron microscope.<ref name=\"JEM_Almeida_1963\" group=\"Publications\">{{Cite journal| doi = 10.1084/jem.118.3.327| issn = 0022-1007| volume = 118| issue = 3| pages = 327\u2013340| last1 = Almeida| first1 = June| last2 = Cinader| first2 = Bernhard| last3 = Howatson| first3 = Allan| title = The Structure of Antigen-Antibody Complexes: A Study by Electron Microscopy| journal = [[Journal of Experimental Medicine]] (JEM)| access-date = 18 April 2020| date = 1 September 1963| url = https://rupress.org/jem/article/118/3/327/3553/THE-STRUCTURE-OF-ANTIGEN-ANTIBODY-COMPLEXES-A}}</ref>\n\n===St Thomas's Hospital Medical School===\n{{main|St Thomas's Hospital Medical School}}\n\nIn 1964, Tony Waterson, a professor of virology, met Almeida while visiting Toronto, and recruited her to join his research team,<ref name=\"Tyrrell_Fielder_2002\">{{cite book |date=2002 |title=Cold wars: the fight against the common cold |first1=David |last1=Tyrrell |first2=Michael |last2=Fielder |location=Oxford, England |publisher=Oxford University Press |pages=253}}</ref>{{rp|96}} at one of the oldest and most prestigious medical schools in the United Kingdom, \u2014[[London]]'s [[St Thomas's Hospital Medical School]]\u2014now part of [[King's College London]]. In his 2002 co-authored book, entitled, ''Cold wars'', [[David Tyrrell (physician)|David Tyrrell]] described how Almeida seemed to be \"extending the range of the electron microscope to new limits.\"<ref name=\"Tyrrell_Fielder_2002\">{{cite book |date=2002 |title=Cold wars: the fight against the common cold |first1=David |last1=Tyrrell |first2=Michael |last2=Fielder |location=Oxford, England |publisher=Oxford University Press |pages=253}}</ref>{{rp|96}}\n\nAt St Thomas, she worked on [[hepatitis B virus]] and the [[Common cold|cold viruses]].<ref name=odnb/>\n\nIn 1966, Almeida using technique that she had pioneered, she was able to identify, what they named a corona virus.<ref name=\"Tyrrell_Fielder_2002\"/>{{rp|96}}\n\n{{clear left}}\n[[File:Virus surrounded by a distinct 200 A long fringe by Almeida and Tyrrell 1966.png|left|thumb|Virus identified by Almeida 1966]]In the article they co-authored in 1966 ''[[Journal of General Virology]]'', they identified a \"previously uncharacterized human respiratory viruses.\" \n\nIn 1966, Almeida and Tyrrell wrote that, \"The particles are pleomorphic, in the size range 800 to 1200 A, and are surrounded by a distinct 200 A long fringe. They are indistinguishable from the particles of avian infectious bronchitis.\"<ref name=\"JGV_Almeida_1966\" group=\"Publications\">{{Cite journal|last=Almeida|first=June D.|last2=Tyrrell|first2=D. A. J.|date=1967|title=The Morphology of Three Previously Uncharacterized Human Respiratory Viruses that Grow in Organ Culture|journal=Journal of General Virology|volume=1|issue=2|pages=175\u2013178|doi=10.1099/0022-1317-1-2-175|pmid=4293939|issn=0022-1317}}</ref>\n\nIn 1968, she co-published an article in ''[[Journal of General Virology]]'', on \"avian infectious bronchitis virus\".<ref name=\"JGV_Berry_Almeida_1968\" group=\"Publications\">{{Cite journal| doi = 10.1099/0022-1317-3-1-97| issn = 0022-1317| volume = 3| issue = 1| pages = 97\u2013102| last1 = Berry| first1 = D. M.| last2 = Almeida| first2 = June D.| title = The Morphological and Biological Effects of Various Antisera on Avian Infectious Bronchitis Virus| journal = [[Journal of General Virology]] (JGV)| access-date = 18 April 2020| date = 1968| url = https://www.microbiologyresearch.org/content/journal/jgv/10.1099/0022-1317-3-1-97}}</ref>\n\n[[David Tyrrell (physician)|David Tyrrell]] and Almeida worked on characterising a new type of [[coronavirus]].<ref name=\"Booss_August_2013\"/>{{rp|209}}\n\nThis family includes the [[SARS virus]] and the SARS-CoV2 virus that causes [[Coronavirus disease 2019|COVID-19]].\n\nShe finished her career at the [[Wellcome Institute]].<ref name=odnb>{{cite ODNB |first1=J. E. |last1=Banatvala |series=Almeida, June Dalziel (1930\u20132007) |title=Oxford Dictionary of National Biography |date= January 2011 |doi=10.1093/ref:odnb/99332 |url=http://www.oxforddnb.com/view/article/99332 |access-date= 18 October 2012}}</ref>  While working for Wellcome she was named on several patents in the field of imaging viruses.<ref>[http://patent.ipexl.com/inventor/Almeida_June_Dalziel_1.html Almeida, June Dalziel], patents, accessed October 2012</ref>\n\n{{clear left}}\n\n==Influences== \nAccording to a 7 March article in the ''[[Herald Scotland]],'' [[Hugh Pennington]] said that Almeida was his mentor.<ref name=\"heraldscotland_20200307\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.heraldscotland.com/news/18289806.june-almeida-tribute-scotlands-forgotten-hero-coronavirus/ |date= 7 March 2020 |access-date=18 April 2020|title=June Almeida, tribute to Scotland's forgotten hero of the coronavirus|newspaper=Herald Scotland}}</ref>\n\nIn 1970, [[Albert Kapikian]] studied Almeida's techniques in the United Kingdom for six months in order to use her techniques in the identification of a cause of non-bacterial gastroenteritis \u2013 the [[Norwalk virus]].<ref name=odnb/>\n\nDuring the early months of the coronavirus pandemic, Chinese scientists credited her work\u2014including techniques she developed\u2014with the early identification of [[Coronavirus disease 2019|COVID-19]], according to Pennington.<ref name=\"heraldscotland_20200307\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.heraldscotland.com/news/18289806.june-almeida-tribute-scotlands-forgotten-hero-coronavirus/ |date= 7 March 2020 |access-date=18 April 2020|title=June Almeida, tribute to Scotland's forgotten hero of the coronavirus|newspaper=Herald Scotland}}</ref>\n\n==Later career==\nAfter retiring from Wellcome Institute, she returned in an advisory role in the late 1980s when she helped take novel pictures of the [[HIV virus]].<ref name=\"BMJ_Obit_20080418\"/>\n\n==Research==\n\nIn the chapter entitled \"Imaging viruses and tagging their antigenes\" in John Booss and Marilyn J. August's 2013 ''To catch a virus'', they describe the how \"refinements in electron microscopy (EM)...greatly expanded the understanding of the structure and replication of viruses and facilitated the application of EM to viral diagnosis. The refinements included thin sectioning, negative staining, and immunoelectron microscopy (IEM) developed for clinical diagnostic work. The use of EM in discovering the viral causes of acute gastroenteritis and infectious hepatitis are then considered.\"<ref name=\"Booss_August_2013\">{{Cite book | last1 = Booss |first1=John |authorlink=John Boos| last2 = August |first2=Marilyn J. | title = To catch a virus | publisher = ASM Press | location = Washington, DC |chapter=Chapter 7: Imaging viruses and tagging their antigenes |pages=197-249| access-date = 18 April 2020| year = 2013 | url=https://archive.org/details/tocatchvirus0000boos/page/217 | isbn = 978-1-55581-507-3 |quote=ASM: \"This chapter first examines the refinements in electron microscopy (EM) that greatly expanded the understanding of the structure and replication of viruses and facilitated the application of EM to viral diagnosis. The refinements included thin sectioning, negative staining, and immunoelectron microscopy (IEM) developed for clinical diagnostic work. The use of EM in discovering the viral causes of acute gastroenteritis and infectious hepatitis are then considered.\"}}</ref>{{rp|209}} They cite a 1967 journal article by Tyrrell and Almeida, \"Direct electron-microscopy of organ culture for the detection and characterization of viruses.\"<ref name=\"Tyrrell_Almeida_1967\" group=\"Publications\">{{Cite journal| doi = 10.1007/bf01242962| issn = 0003-9012| volume = 22| issue = 3| pages = 417\u2013425| last1 = Tyrrell| first1 = D. A.| last2 = Almeida| first2 = J. D.| title = Direct electron-microscopy of organ culture for the detection and characterization of viruses| journal = Archiv Fur Die Gesamte Virusforschung| date = 1967| pmid = 4300621}}</ref>\n\nHer publications include the 1979 ''Manual for rapid laboratory viral diagnosis'' for the [[World Health Organisation]].<ref name=\"WHO_Almeida_1979\" group=\"Publications\">{{Cite web|url=http://whqlibdoc.who.int/offset/WHO_OFFSET_47.pdf|publisher=World Health Organization (WHO) |title=Manual for rapid laboratory viral diagnosis|date=1979 |last=Almeida |first=June D.}}</ref>\n\n==Media==\n\nA 15 April 2020 ''BBC Scotland News'' said that Almedia was \"the woman who discovered the first [[coronavirus]].\"<ref name=\"BBC_Brocklehurst_20200415\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-scotland-52278716|title=The woman who discovered the first coronavirus|work=BBC News |first=Steven |last=Brocklehurst |work=BBC Scotland News |date=15 April 2020 |access-date=17 April 2020}}</ref> \n\n== Coronaviruses ==\nIn a 7 March 2020 interview with the ''Herald'', Pennington spoke of Almeida's research had informed with work of Chinese researchers during the pandemic.<ref name=\"heraldscotland_20200307\"/>\n\nDuring the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|2019\u201320 COVID-19 pandemic]], the little known story was first published by the ''Herald'' in Scotland on 7 March, the [[BBC]] on 15 April,<ref name=\"BBC_Brocklehurst_20200415\"/> the ''[[National Geographic]]'' on April 17.<ref name=\"NatGeo\">{{cite news |last1=Combs |first1=Sydney |title=She Discovered Coronaviruses Decades Ago\u2014But Got Little Recognition |url=https://www.nationalgeographic.com/history/2020/04/june-almeida-discovered-coronaviruses-decades-ago-little-recognition/ |accessdate=18 April 2020 |agency=National Geographic |publisher=[[National Geographic Society]] |date=April 17, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nAlmeida moved to Toronto, Ontario and worked at the Cancer Institute after her marriage on December 11, 1954 to Enrique Rosalio (Henry) Almeida (1913\u20131993), a Venezuelan artist with whom she had a daughter, Joyce.  Almeida died in [[Bexhill-on-Sea|Bexhill]] from a heart attack in 2007.<ref name=odnb/>\n\n== See also ==\n\n* [[Timeline of women in science]]\n\n==Selected publications==\n{{reflist|group=\"Publications\"}}\n\n==References==\n{{Scholia}}\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Almeida, June Dalziel}}\n[[Category:1930 births]]\n[[Category:2007 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Glasgow]]\n[[Category:British virologists]]\n[[Category:20th-century Scottish scientists]]\n[[Category:British women biologists]]\n[[Category:Scottish women scientists]]\n[[Category:Wellcome Trust]]\n[[Category:20th-century women scientists]]\n[[Category:Women virologists]]\n", "name_user": "Oceanflynn", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eEducation:ce", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/June_Almeida"}
{"title_page": "1996\u201397 Algerian Championnat National", "text_new": "{{one source|date=March 2016}}\n{{Infobox football league season\n| competition        = [[Algerian Championnat National]]\n| season             = 1996\u201397\n| winners            = [[CS Constantine]]\n| relegated          = [[USM A\u00efn Be\u00efda]]<br />[[NA Hussein Dey]]<br />[[WA Mostaganem]]\n| league topscorer   = [[Mohamed Djalti]] (15 goals)\n| biggest home win   = [[WA Mostaganem]] 6 - 0 [[JS Kabylie]]\n| biggest away win   = [[MC Alger]] 2 - 5 [[JS Kabylie]]<br />[[WA Mostaganem]] 0 - 3 [[WA Boufarik]]\n| highest scoring    = [[WA Mostaganem]] 4 - 3 [[CS Constantine]]<br />[[MC Alger]] 2 - 5 [[JS Kabylie]]<br />[[NA Hussein Dey]] 3 - 4 [[MC Oran]]<br />[[MC Alger]] 6 - 1 [[US Chaouia]]<br />[[CS Constantine]] 4 - 3 [[WA Mostaganem]]\n| matches            = 240\t\n| total goals        = 558\n| longest wins       = \n| title              = \n| longest unbeaten   = \n| longest losses     = \n| highest attendance = \n| lowest attendance  = \n| average attendance = \n| prevseason         = [[1995\u201396 Algerian Championnat National|1995\u201396]]\n| nextseason         = [[1997\u201398 Algerian Championnat National|1997\u201398]]\n}}\nThe '''1996\u201397 Algerian Championnat National''' was the 35th season of the [[Algerian Championnat National]] since its establishment in 1962. A total of 16 teams contested the league, with [[USM Alger]] as the defending champions, The Championnat started on [[october 10]], [[1996 in association football|1996]]. and ended on [[June 26]], [[1997 in association football|1997]].\n\n==Team summaries==\n\n=== Promotion and relegation ===\n'''Teams promoted from Algerian Division 2 1996-1997''' \n* [[ES Mostaganem]]\n* [[ES S\u00e9tif]]\n* [[USM Blida]]\n\n'''Teams relegated to Algerian Division 2 1997-1998'''\n* [[USM A\u00efn Be\u00efda]]\n* [[NA Hussein Dey]]\n* [[WA Mostaganem]]\n\n==League table==\n<onlyinclude>{{#invoke:sports table|main|style=WDL\n